const CCT_QUESTIONS = [{"id":"cct_001","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"Thomas, an employee of an organization, is restricted from accessing specific websites from his office system. He is trying to obtain admin credentials to remove the restrictions. While waiting for an opportunity, he sniffed communication between the administrator and an application server to retrieve the admin credentials. Identify the type of attack performed by Thomas.","options":{"A":"Vishing","B":"Eavesdropping","C":"Phishing","D":"Dumpster diving"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Vishing is voice phishing conducted over the phone.","B":"Correct! Sniffing network communications to capture sensitive credentials is a form of eavesdropping.","C":"Incorrect. Phishing uses deceptive emails or messages to trick users.","D":"Incorrect. Dumpster diving involves searching physical trash for sensitive information."}},{"id":"cct_002","domain":"Network Security Fundamentals","question":"Kayden successfully cracked the final round of interviews. He received his offer letter, provided an e-signature, and replied. The company validated the e-signature. Kayden could not deny the message, and the company could not deny his signature. Which information security element is described?","options":{"A":"Availability","B":"Non-repudiation","C":"Integrity","D":"Confidentiality"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Availability ensures that systems and data are accessible to authorized users when needed.","B":"Correct! Non-repudiation ensures that a party to a transaction or communication cannot deny the authenticity of their signature or sending of the message.","C":"Incorrect. Integrity guarantees that data has not been altered or tampered with.","D":"Incorrect. Confidentiality ensures that data is only accessible to authorized individuals."}},{"id":"cct_003","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"Sam, a software engineer, visited an organization to give a software demonstration. The administrator created a least privileged account for Sam that only accesses required files. Which type of account was given?","options":{"A":"Service account","B":"Guest account","C":"User account","D":"Administrator account"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Service accounts are used by applications or services to run background processes.","B":"Correct! A guest account is designed for temporary visitors who require restricted access to specific resources.","C":"Incorrect. A user account is for standard internal employees of the organization.","D":"Incorrect. An administrator account has full system privileges."}},{"id":"cct_004","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"Myles provided laptops for remote employees and installed antivirus software to detect/protect against external malicious events. Identify the PCI-DSS requirement followed.","options":{"A":"PCI-DSS requirement no 1.3.2","B":"PCI-DSS requirement no 1.3.5","C":"PCI-DSS requirement no 5.1","D":"PCI-DSS requirement no 1.3.1"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Requirement 1.3.2 deals with restricting traffic between the cardholder data environment and other networks.","B":"Incorrect. Requirement 1.3.5 deals with firewalls and filtering.","C":"Correct! PCI-DSS Requirement 5.1 specifies deploying antivirus software on all systems commonly affected by malicious software.","D":"Incorrect. Requirement 1.3.1 deals with inbound and outbound traffic."}},{"id":"cct_005","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"Ashton was instructed to strengthen the Internet access policy. He implemented a policy that forbids everything and imposes strict restrictions. Identify the policy type.","options":{"A":"Paranoid policy","B":"Prudent policy","C":"Permissive policy","D":"Promiscuous policy"},"correct_option":"A","explanations":{"A":"Correct! A paranoid policy forbids everything by default and has extreme restrictions.","B":"Incorrect. A prudent policy blocks everything by default but permits specific safe services individually.","C":"Incorrect. A permissive policy blocks only known dangerous services and allows everything else.","D":"Incorrect. A promiscuous policy does not impose any restrictions."}},{"id":"cct_006","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"Zion manages physical security equipment around the facility and checks its functionality. Identify Zion's designation.","options":{"A":"Supervisor","B":"Chief information security officer","C":"Guard","D":"Safety officer"},"correct_option":"D","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. A supervisor directs staff but does not specifically manage physical equipment.","B":"Incorrect. The CISO manages high-level information security strategies.","C":"Incorrect. A guard monitors access points but does not typically hold the administrative responsibility of managing physical security equipment.","D":"Correct! A Safety Officer is responsible for implementing and managing physical security equipment and verifying its operation."}},{"id":"cct_007","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"A sealed room with servers is protected with a physical lock system requiring a sequence of numbers/letters using a rotating dial that intermingles with other discs. Which lock is used?","options":{"A":"Digital locks","B":"Combination locks","C":"Mechanical locks","D":"Electromagnetic locks"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Digital locks require entering code on an electronic keypad.","B":"Correct! Combination locks use a rotating dial that aligns internal discs to open the lock.","C":"Incorrect. Mechanical locks generally refer to traditional key-and-cylinder locks.","D":"Incorrect. Electromagnetic locks use magnetic fields powered by electricity to keep a door closed."}},{"id":"cct_008","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"Lorenzo implemented centralized AAA for remote-access servers using a client-server protocol at the transport layer of the OSI model. Identify the protocol.","options":{"A":"SNMPv3","B":"RADIUS","C":"POP3S","D":"IMAPS"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. SNMPv3 is used for network management, not centralized AAA.","B":"Correct! RADIUS is a client-server protocol that provides centralized AAA and operates at the Transport layer (over UDP).","C":"Incorrect. POP3S is a secure email retrieval protocol.","D":"Incorrect. IMAPS is a secure email access protocol."}},{"id":"cct_009","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"Malachi deployed a firewall that works at the session layer of the OSI model and monitors the TCP handshake. Identify the firewall technology.","options":{"A":"Next generation firewall (NGFW)","B":"Circuit-level gateways","C":"Network address translation (NAT)","D":"Packet filtering"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. NGFWs operate at higher layers (up to Layer 7) with deep packet inspection.","B":"Correct! Circuit-level gateways operate at the Session layer (Layer 5) of the OSI model and verify the TCP handshake before establishing a connection.","C":"Incorrect. NAT translates IP addresses and operates at Layer 3/4.","D":"Incorrect. Packet filtering operates at Layers 3 and 4, inspecting headers of individual packets."}},{"id":"cct_010","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"Rhett deployed an IDS that creates models for possible intrusions and compares them with incoming events. Identify the detection method.","options":{"A":"Not-use detection","B":"Protocol anomaly detection","C":"Anomaly detection","D":"Signature recognition"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. This is a distractor.","B":"Incorrect. Protocol anomaly detection focuses specifically on RFC protocol violations.","C":"Correct! Anomaly detection creates behavioral models (representing normal or baseline activities) and monitors deviations.","D":"Incorrect. Signature recognition matches exact patterns of known attacks."}},{"id":"cct_011","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"Shawn, a forensic officer, collected a victim's mobile device. Which points must he follow while preserving the digital evidence? (Select the correct three points)","options":{"A":"Never record the screen display of the device; Do not turn the device ON if it is OFF; Make sure that the device is charged","B":"Do not turn the device ON if it is OFF; Do not leave the device as it is if it is ON; Make sure that the device is charged","C":"Never record the screen display of the device; Do not leave the device as it is if it is ON; Make sure that the device is charged","D":"Never record the screen display of the device; Do not turn the device ON if it is OFF; Do not leave the device as it is if it is ON"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. You should record/photograph the screen display to document the state of evidence.","B":"Correct! Leaving it OFF preserves volatile logs, isolating it if it is ON prevents remote wipes, and keeping it charged prevents loss of volatile memory.","C":"Incorrect. Screen recording is standard practice and should not be forbidden.","D":"Incorrect. Not recording the screen is incorrect."}},{"id":"cct_012","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"An organization used threat intelligence to understand how attackers perform attacks, identify information leakage, and determine attack goals/vectors. Identify the type.","options":{"A":"Operational threat intelligence","B":"Strategic threat intelligence","C":"Technical threat intelligence","D":"Tactical threat intelligence"},"correct_option":"D","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Operational threat intelligence focuses on specific live attacks or campaigns.","B":"Incorrect. Strategic threat intelligence looks at high-level business risks and trends.","C":"Incorrect. Technical threat intelligence focuses on specific indicators of compromise (IOCs) like IPs and hashes.","D":"Correct! Tactical threat intelligence analyzes attackers' TTPs (Tactics, Techniques, and Procedures), helping understand how they perform attacks."}},{"id":"cct_013","domain":"Application Security and Cloud Computing","question":"Which security measures can help prevent SQL injection attacks? (Select the correct options)","options":{"A":"Input validation and Cross-site scripting (XSS)","B":"Input validation and Parameterized queries or prepared statements","C":"Cross-site scripting (XSS) and Using weak passwords","D":"Using weak passwords and Parameterized queries or prepared statements"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. XSS is another type of attack, not a prevention measure.","B":"Correct! Input validation and Parameterized queries (prepared statements) are the primary countermeasures for SQL injection.","C":"Incorrect. Neither weak passwords nor XSS prevents SQL Injection.","D":"Incorrect. Weak passwords do not prevent SQL Injection."}},{"id":"cct_014","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"During which incident response phase are containment and eradication performed?","options":{"A":"Preparation","B":"Recovery","C":"Response","D":"Detection and analysis"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Preparation deals with setting up policies and tools before an incident.","B":"Incorrect. Recovery deals with restoring systems to normal operations.","C":"Correct! Containment and eradication are key components of the Response phase to mitigate damage.","D":"Incorrect. Detection and analysis focuses on identifying and assessing the scope of the threat."}},{"id":"cct_015","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"What is the key difference between a disaster recovery plan (DRP) and a business continuity plan (BCP)?","options":{"A":"DR plans focus on data backup, BCP focuses on personnel safety.","B":"DR plans concern technology recovery, BCP covers all aspects of business operations.","C":"DR plans apply to natural disasters, BCP covers man-made incidents.","D":"DR plans are shorter and simpler than BCPs."},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Safety is a part of both, but not the primary dividing line.","B":"Correct! DRP focuses on restoring IT infrastructure and technology systems, whereas BCP is a broader framework to keep all business operations running.","C":"Incorrect. Both plans address both natural and man-made disasters.","D":"Incorrect. Complexity depends on the organization, not the plan type."}},{"id":"cct_016","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"In an incident response plan, what are the phases of the incident response lifecycle? (Select the correct options)","options":{"A":"Detection and analysis, Recovery, and Prevention","B":"Detection and analysis, Recovery, and Containment","C":"Recovery, Prevention, and Containment","D":"Detection and analysis, Prevention, and Containment"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Prevention is a pre-incident activity, not a phase of the response lifecycle.","B":"Correct! Detection and analysis, Recovery, and Containment are all core phases of the incident response lifecycle.","C":"Incorrect. Prevention is not a phase in the response lifecycle.","D":"Incorrect. Prevention is not a phase in the response lifecycle."}},{"id":"cct_017","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"Tristan initiated zero-knowledge attacks on an organization's network with no prior information. Which type of penetration testing is this?","options":{"A":"Black-box testing","B":"White-box testing","C":"Gray-box testing","D":"Translucent-box testing"},"correct_option":"A","explanations":{"A":"Correct! Black-box testing (zero-knowledge) simulates an external attacker with no prior access or info.","B":"Incorrect. White-box testing provides the tester with full internal documentation and network schema.","C":"Incorrect. Gray-box testing provides partial information.","D":"Incorrect. This is a distractor."}},{"id":"cct_018","domain":"Data Security","question":"Andre replaced critical database information with special characters (e.g., * and #) before sharing it. Which technique was employed?","options":{"A":"Tokenization","B":"Masking","C":"Hashing","D":"Bucketing"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Tokenization replaces sensitive data with a non-sensitive equivalent (a token).","B":"Correct! Data masking replaces characters of sensitive data with dummy characters (like # or *) to hide them.","C":"Incorrect. Hashing uses a mathematical algorithm to convert data into a fixed-length string.","D":"Incorrect. Bucketing groups data into categories or buckets."}},{"id":"cct_019","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"Which of the following are examples of physical security controls? (Select the correct options)","options":{"A":"Security guards and Firewalls","B":"Firewalls and Encryption algorithms","C":"Security guards and Biometric access control","D":"Biometric access control and Encryption algorithms"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Firewalls are logical/technical controls.","B":"Incorrect. Firewalls and encryption algorithms are logical controls.","C":"Correct! Security guards and Biometric locks protect physical facilities.","D":"Incorrect. Encryption is a logical control."}},{"id":"cct_020","domain":"Data Security","question":"What can be used to ensure data confidentiality? (Select the correct options)","options":{"A":"Access control lists (ACLs) only","B":"Access control lists (ACLs) and Encryption","C":"Encryption and Regular system backups","D":"Access control lists (ACLs), Encryption, and Regular system backups"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Both ACLs and Encryption are critical confidentiality controls.","B":"Correct! Access Control Lists (authorization) and Encryption (obfuscation) ensure data is confidential.","C":"Incorrect. Backups ensure availability, not confidentiality.","D":"Incorrect. Backups ensure availability."}},{"id":"cct_021","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"Anderson monitored network traffic analyzing packet header fields (IP options, protocols, flags, offset) to check for alterations. Identify the attack signature analysis type.","options":{"A":"Context-based signature analysis","B":"Atomic-signature-based analysis","C":"Composite-signature-based analysis","D":"Content-based signature analysis"},"correct_option":"A","explanations":{"A":"Correct! Context-based signature analysis examines packet headers (context) for anomalies rather than payload data.","B":"Incorrect. Atomic signature analysis matches simple single-packet signatures.","C":"Incorrect. Composite signature analysis spans multiple packets or events over time.","D":"Incorrect. Content-based signature analysis inspects the actual payload content of the packet."}},{"id":"cct_022","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"Arabella filled out a forensic investigation report. In which section did she record the 'nature of the claim and information provided to the officers'?","options":{"A":"Investigation process","B":"Investigation objectives","C":"Evidence information","D":"Evaluation and analysis process"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Investigation process records the steps and timeline of the investigation.","B":"Correct! The 'nature of the claim and information provided' is recorded in the Investigation Objectives.","C":"Incorrect. Evidence information details technical aspects of the collected media.","D":"Incorrect. Evaluation and analysis details the analytical findings of the case."}},{"id":"cct_023","domain":"Application Security and Cloud Computing","question":"Dawson checks the performance of applications in the client's network to determine end-user issues. Which tier of the secure application development lifecycle is this?","options":{"A":"Development","B":"Staging","C":"Testing","D":"Quality assurance (QA)"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Development is where code is written.","B":"Incorrect. Staging is a pre-production mirroring environment.","C":"Correct! Checking application performance on network endpoints is part of the Testing tier.","D":"Incorrect. Quality assurance (QA) is a wider methodology."}},{"id":"cct_024","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"John the Ripper is a widely used password auditing tool. Which of the following describes the primary function of its '--wordlist' mode?","options":{"A":"It performs a full brute-force attack testing every possible character combination","B":"It uses a pre-existing dictionary file to attempt to crack password hashes","C":"It sniffs network traffic and extracts password hashes in real time","D":"It generates rainbow tables for offline hash comparison"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Testing every character combination is brute-force mode (--incremental in John the Ripper), not wordlist mode.","B":"Correct! The --wordlist mode loads a file containing common passwords and attempts each one against the captured hashes — this is a dictionary attack.","C":"Incorrect. John the Ripper does not sniff network traffic. Tools like Wireshark or Cain & Abel are used for credential capture.","D":"Incorrect. Rainbow table generation and lookup is performed by tools like Ophcrack or RainbowCrack, not John the Ripper's wordlist mode."}},{"id":"cct_025","domain":"Application Security and Cloud Computing","question":"During a web application vulnerability scan using OWASP ZAP, alerts are classified using WASC IDs. What does the acronym WASC stand for?","options":{"A":"Web Application Security Consortium","B":"Wireless Attack Surface Classification","C":"Web Access Security Committee","D":"Wide Area Security Control"},"correct_option":"A","explanations":{"A":"Correct! WASC stands for Web Application Security Consortium — the body that created the standardized threat classification taxonomy used by tools like OWASP ZAP to categorize web vulnerabilities.","B":"Incorrect. This is a distractor; WASC is not related to wireless.","C":"Incorrect. This is not a real organization.","D":"Incorrect. This is a fabricated expansion of the acronym."}},{"id":"cct_026","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"Cain & Abel is a Windows password recovery tool used by attackers and security testers. Which technique does Cain & Abel use to intercept and capture network credentials by associating its MAC address with the IP of a legitimate host on the LAN?","options":{"A":"DNS Spoofing","B":"ARP Poisoning (ARP Spoofing)","C":"DHCP Starvation","D":"TCP Session Hijacking"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. DNS spoofing redirects hostname resolution by injecting false records into DNS caches, but it is not the primary LAN interception method used by Cain & Abel's sniffer.","B":"Correct! Cain & Abel uses ARP Poisoning (ARP Spoofing) to send false ARP replies that link its own MAC address to the IP of the gateway or target, forcing LAN traffic through the attacker machine so credentials can be sniffed.","C":"Incorrect. DHCP starvation exhausts the IP address pool by sending thousands of fake DHCP Discover requests, a different attack type.","D":"Incorrect. TCP session hijacking involves taking over an already established TCP connection using sequence number prediction, not MAC-to-IP address manipulation."}},{"id":"cct_027","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"After a ransomware attack encrypts critical data, what is the MOST critical action to take immediately after identifying the attack?","options":{"A":"Analyze the attack vector to identify the source of the infection.","B":"Pay the ransom demand to regain access to encrypted data.","C":"Identify and isolate infected devices to prevent further spread.","D":"Restore critical systems from backups according to the BCP."},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Analysis should happen later; containment is the first priority.","B":"Incorrect. Paying the ransom is never recommended and does not stop current spread.","C":"Correct! Isolating infected endpoints prevents the ransomware from spreading laterally across the network.","D":"Incorrect. Restoring from backups can only happen after the network is clean and the threat is contained."}},{"id":"cct_028","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"Brielle observed a malicious actor logged in to access a network device. Which type of event did she identify?","options":{"A":"Success audit","B":"Failure audit","C":"Error","D":"Warning"},"correct_option":"A","explanations":{"A":"Correct! A successful login (even by a malicious actor) is logged as a Success Audit.","B":"Incorrect. A Failure Audit records failed login attempts.","C":"Incorrect. Errors deal with system/service failures.","D":"Incorrect. Warnings deal with resource thresholds or potential system issues."}},{"id":"cct_029","domain":"Wireless Device Security","question":"Which action would be the LEAST effective in protecting a new smart thermostat from unauthorized access?","options":{"A":"Changing the default password upon initial setup.","B":"Leaving the thermostat connected to an open 'Guest' Wi-Fi network.","C":"Keeping the firmware updated with security patches.","D":"Enabling remote access only on a secure home Wi-Fi network."},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Changing default passwords is highly effective.","B":"Correct! Connecting IoT devices to an unencrypted, open Guest Wi-Fi network leaves them highly exposed.","C":"Incorrect. Firmware updates are essential.","D":"Incorrect. Restricting remote access is a strong security measure."}},{"id":"cct_030","domain":"Application Security and Cloud Computing","question":"Walker performed an independent examination of cloud service controls to verify adherence to standards through objective evidence. Identify Walker's role.","options":{"A":"Cloud provider","B":"Cloud consumer","C":"Cloud auditor","D":"Cloud carrier"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. The cloud provider delivers the service.","B":"Incorrect. The consumer uses the service.","C":"Correct! A Cloud Auditor independently examines cloud controls to verify compliance.","D":"Incorrect. A cloud carrier provides connectivity."}},{"id":"cct_031","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"NetSafe Corp needs to establish a new baseline for normal and suspicious activities after a network overhaul. Which approach should they adopt?","options":{"A":"Continuously collect data for a week and define the average traffic pattern as the baseline.","B":"Analyze the last year's traffic logs and predict the baseline using historical data.","C":"Conduct a red team exercise and base the new baseline on the identified threats.","D":"Utilize machine learning algorithms to analyze traffic for a month and generate a dynamic baseline."},"correct_option":"D","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. One week is too short to capture all seasonal variations.","B":"Incorrect. Historical logs do not reflect the new network architecture.","C":"Incorrect. Red teaming tests controls but does not establish operational baselines.","D":"Correct! Using machine learning for a month allows the creation of a dynamic baseline that reduces false positives."}},{"id":"cct_032","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"Kasen established a program to restore the disaster site and damaged materials to pre-disaster levels. Which BC/DR activity did he perform?","options":{"A":"Response","B":"Prevention","C":"Resumption","D":"Recovery"},"correct_option":"D","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Response deals with immediate containment.","B":"Incorrect. Prevention reduces the likelihood of disaster occurrence.","C":"Incorrect. Resumption deals with bringing operations back online.","D":"Correct! Recovery processes restore the disaster site and damaged systems to their original baseline state."}},{"id":"cct_033","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"Steve used a utility to capture ICMP echo request packets and found packets dropping at the gateway. Identify the utility.","options":{"A":"ipconfig","B":"traceroute","C":"arp","D":"dnsenum"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. ipconfig displays network interface configurations.","B":"Correct! traceroute (tracert) traces the path of packets and shows which hops (gateways) are dropping them.","C":"Incorrect. arp displays/modifies IP-to-MAC translation tables.","D":"Incorrect. dnsenum is a DNS reconnaissance tool."}},{"id":"cct_034","domain":"Application Security and Cloud Computing","question":"GlobalTech needs a mobile security solution that secures data, provides device flexibility, and keeps administrative overhead low. Which is the best solution?","options":{"A":"Mobile Application Management (MAM)","B":"Unified Endpoint Management (UEM)","C":"Mobile Device Management (MDM)","D":"Containerization Solutions"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. MAM only manages apps, not endpoints.","B":"Correct! Unified Endpoint Management (UEM) centralizes MDM, MAM, and containerization across all endpoints to reduce overhead.","C":"Incorrect. MDM manages full devices but is less flexible for BYOD/privacy.","D":"Incorrect. Containerization is a technique, UEM is the complete solution."}},{"id":"cct_035","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"Which type of firewall operates at the Network Layer (Layer 3) of the OSI model and evaluates network traffic based on source and destination IP addresses, protocols, and port numbers without inspecting the payload?","options":{"A":"Application-level gateway","B":"Stateful inspection firewall","C":"Packet filtering firewall","D":"Circuit-level gateway"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Application-level gateways operate at Layer 7 and inspect payloads.","B":"Incorrect. Stateful inspection firewalls track the state of active sessions.","C":"Correct! Packet filtering firewalls inspect Layer 3 and Layer 4 headers (IP, ports, protocols) without analyzing payloads.","D":"Incorrect. Circuit-level gateways operate at the Session layer (Layer 5) to monitor the TCP handshake."}},{"id":"cct_036","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"You are performing a live incident response on a compromised Windows machine. According to the order of volatility, which of the following should be collected FIRST?","options":{"A":"Routing tables and ARP cache","B":"CPU registers and cache memory","C":"Temporary system files","D":"Hard drive data"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Routing tables and ARP cache are volatile but less volatile than CPU registers and cache.","B":"Correct! CPU registers and cache memory are the most volatile data and should be collected first.","C":"Incorrect. Temporary system files reside on disk and are relatively stable.","D":"Incorrect. Hard drive data is non-volatile."}},{"id":"cct_037","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"An organization decides to purchase cyber liability insurance to cover potential financial losses in the event of a ransomware attack. Which risk treatment strategy does this represent?","options":{"A":"Risk Mitigation","B":"Risk Acceptance","C":"Risk Transference","D":"Risk Avoidance"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Risk Mitigation implements controls to reduce vulnerability risk.","B":"Incorrect. Risk Acceptance means tolerating the potential loss.","C":"Correct! Cyber insurance transfers the financial consequences of risk to a third party.","D":"Incorrect. Risk Avoidance involves eliminating the activity that causes the risk."}},{"id":"cct_038","domain":"Data Security","question":"Which of the following cryptographic hash functions produces a 160-bit digest and is considered vulnerable to collision attacks?","options":{"A":"MD5","B":"SHA-1","C":"SHA-256","D":"AES-128"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. MD5 produces a 128-bit digest.","B":"Correct! SHA-1 produces a 160-bit digest and is no longer secure against collision attacks.","C":"Incorrect. SHA-256 produces a 256-bit digest.","D":"Incorrect. AES-128 is a symmetric key cipher, not a hash function."}},{"id":"cct_039","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"A network administrator wants to establish a secure, encrypted command-line session to a remote Linux server. Which protocol and default port should be used?","options":{"A":"Telnet, Port 23","B":"RDP, Port 3389","C":"SSH, Port 22","D":"FTP, Port 21"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Telnet (Port 23) is unencrypted and insecure.","B":"Incorrect. RDP (Port 3389) is for remote desktop GUI sessions.","C":"Correct! SSH (Secure Shell) runs on default port 22 and provides secure, encrypted terminal sessions.","D":"Incorrect. FTP (Port 21) is for file transfer and is unencrypted."}},{"id":"cct_040","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"During a vulnerability assessment, an analyst finds a reference to 'CVE-2021-44228'. What does 'CVE' stand for in this context?","options":{"A":"Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures","B":"Critical Vulnerability Evaluation","C":"Certified Vulnerability Enumeration","D":"Cyber Vulnerability Exploit"},"correct_option":"A","explanations":{"A":"Correct! CVE stands for Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures, the standard dictionary of publicly known security vulnerabilities.","B":"Incorrect. This is a distractor.","C":"Incorrect. This is a distractor.","D":"Incorrect. This is a distractor."}},{"id":"cct_041","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"A physical security access control system requires an employee to swipe a smart card and then enter a 4-digit PIN to open a server room door. What type of authentication is this?","options":{"A":"Single-factor authentication","B":"Two-factor authentication (MFA)","C":"Biometric authentication","D":"Mandatory access control"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Single-factor uses only one category of credentials.","B":"Correct! This requires something you have (smart card) and something you know (PIN), representing Two-Factor Authentication.","C":"Incorrect. Biometric authentication uses unique physical traits (e.g. fingerprint).","D":"Incorrect. Mandatory access control is an authorization model, not authentication."}},{"id":"cct_042","domain":"Application Security and Cloud Computing","question":"In an Industrial Control System (ICS) environment, what is the primary function of a SCADA system?","options":{"A":"To provide endpoint protection for office laptops.","B":"To gather real-time data and control industrial processes remotely.","C":"To encrypt communication between corporate headquarters and branch offices.","D":"To filter web traffic and block malicious URLs."},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. SCADA does not secure office laptops.","B":"Correct! SCADA (Supervisory Control and Data Acquisition) gathers metrics and controls remote industrial operations.","C":"Incorrect. VPNs or encryption standards secure site-to-site communication.","D":"Incorrect. Firewalls and web filters restrict web traffic."}},{"id":"cct_043","domain":"Wireless Device Security","question":"Which wireless security protocol introduced the Simultaneous Authentication of Equals (SAE) handshake to protect against offline dictionary attacks?","options":{"A":"WEP","B":"WPA","C":"WPA2","D":"WPA3"},"correct_option":"D","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. WEP is highly vulnerable and uses insecure RC4 keys.","B":"Incorrect. WPA uses temporal key integrity protocol (TKIP).","C":"Incorrect. WPA2 uses a 4-way handshake vulnerable to offline dictionary attack.","D":"Correct! WPA3 uses the SAE handshake to defend against offline password cracking."}},{"id":"cct_044","domain":"Application Security and Cloud Computing","question":"A company hosts its web application on a cloud platform where the cloud provider manages the underlying hardware, hypervisor, and physical networking, while the company is responsible for managing the operating system, middleware, and application data. Which cloud service model is this?","options":{"A":"Software as a Service (SaaS)","B":"Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS)","C":"Platform as a Service (PaaS)","D":"Function as a Service (FaaS)"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. In SaaS, the provider manages the entire application and system stacks.","B":"Correct! In IaaS, the provider manages core hardware, and the customer manages the OS and software layers.","C":"Incorrect. In PaaS, the provider manages the OS and middleware, leaving only application code to the user.","D":"Incorrect. FaaS is event-driven serverless computing."}},{"id":"cct_045","domain":"Network Security Fundamentals","question":"During a TCP three-way handshake, a client sends a SYN packet to a server to initiate a connection. What is the correct response from the server if the port is open?","options":{"A":"ACK","B":"SYN","C":"SYN-ACK","D":"FIN-ACK"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. ACK is sent by the client to finalize the handshake.","B":"Incorrect. SYN is only the opening request.","C":"Correct! The server acknowledges the request and requests sync back with a SYN-ACK.","D":"Incorrect. FIN-ACK is sent during session termination."}},{"id":"cct_046","domain":"Application Security and Cloud Computing","question":"An attacker injects a malicious script (<script>alert(document.cookie)</script>) into a web application's comment section. When other users view the comments, their browsers execute the script. What type of vulnerability is being exploited?","options":{"A":"SQL Injection (SQLi)","B":"Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)","C":"Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)","D":"Buffer Overflow"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. SQL Injection exploits database querying inputs.","B":"Incorrect. CSRF tricks the user browser into performing unauthorized actions on a trusted site.","C":"Correct! Stored Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) occurs when malicious code is saved in a server database and executed in client browsers.","D":"Incorrect. Buffer overflow involves writing excess data to buffer memory."}},{"id":"cct_047","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"A backup strategy is configured to copy only the files that have been modified since the last full backup. The restore process requires the last full backup and the latest backup from this specific method. What type of backup is this?","options":{"A":"Incremental backup","B":"Differential backup","C":"Snapshot","D":"Mirror backup"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Incremental backups save changes since the latest backup of any type, requiring all incrementals since the last full backup to restore.","B":"Correct! Differential backups save all changes since the last full backup, requiring only the full and the latest differential to restore.","C":"Incorrect. A snapshot is a point-in-time state capture of a virtual system.","D":"Incorrect. Mirror backup duplicates the files in real-time."}},{"id":"cct_048","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"What is the primary purpose of maintaining a chain of custody document during a digital forensics investigation?","options":{"A":"To document the IP addresses of the attackers.","B":"To ensure the evidence has not been tampered with and remains admissible in court.","C":"To list the tools used to decrypt the seized hard drives.","D":"To provide a timeline of the victim's network activity."},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. The chain of custody documents the people handling the evidence, not hacker IPs.","B":"Correct! Chain of custody documents the chronologic sequence of custody to verify integrity for legal presentation.","C":"Incorrect. Forensic tools are documented in the analysis logs.","D":"Incorrect. Network activity is documented in traffic analyses."}},{"id":"cct_049","domain":"Network Security Fundamentals","question":"A user reports that they can access internal web servers using their IP addresses (e.g., 192.168.1.50) but cannot access them using their hostnames (e.g., intranet.local). Which network protocol is most likely failing?","options":{"A":"DHCP","B":"ICMP","C":"DNS","D":"ARP"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. DHCP allocates IP configurations to devices.","B":"Incorrect. ICMP transmits network control messages.","C":"Correct! DNS (Domain Name System) translates hostnames to IP addresses. A failure prevents name resolution.","D":"Incorrect. ARP maps IP addresses to physical MAC addresses."}},{"id":"cct_050","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"What type of malware is explicitly designed to remain hidden deeply within an operating system, often altering core OS functions to avoid detection and maintain persistent privileged access?","options":{"A":"Ransomware","B":"Adware","C":"Rootkit","D":"Keylogger"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Ransomware locks and encrypts user data.","B":"Incorrect. Adware displays spam ads.","C":"Correct! Rootkits infect deep system folders and hook OS API calls to remain completely hidden.","D":"Incorrect. Keyloggers capture keystrokes."}},{"id":"cct_051","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"Which administrative security policy dictates that users, programs, and processes should only be granted the bare minimum access rights required to perform their legitimate functions?","options":{"A":"Separation of Duties","B":"Principle of Least Privilege","C":"Acceptable Use Policy","D":"Mandatory Vacations"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Separation of duties splits a task among multiple people to prevent fraud.","B":"Correct! The Principle of Least Privilege grants only the minimum privileges required to perform tasks.","C":"Incorrect. Acceptable use policies dictate how company equipment can be used.","D":"Incorrect. Mandatory vacations are used to detect internal fraud."}},{"id":"cct_052","domain":"Application Security and Cloud Computing","question":"What feature of a Mobile Device Management (MDM) solution allows administrators to securely separate personal applications and data from corporate applications and data on a BYOD (Bring Your Own Device) mobile phone?","options":{"A":"Geofencing","B":"Containerization","C":"Remote Wipe","D":"Biometrics"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Geofencing triggers actions based on location coordinates.","B":"Correct! Containerization sandboxes and encrypts corporate files inside a dedicated container on the user's phone.","C":"Incorrect. Remote wipe deletes all data on the device.","D":"Incorrect. Biometrics validates user authentication."}},{"id":"cct_053","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"To prevent tailgating into a highly sensitive datacenter, an organization installs a small physical enclosure with two sets of interlocking doors, where the first door must close completely before the second door can be opened. What is this control called?","options":{"A":"Faraday cage","B":"Bollard","C":"Mantrap","D":"Turnstile"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. A Faraday cage blocks electromagnetic fields.","B":"Incorrect. A bollard prevents vehicles from ramming gates.","C":"Correct! A mantrap isolates visitors between two interlocking doors to verify access.","D":"Incorrect. A turnstile controls individual access flow but is easily tailgated compared to a mantrap."}},{"id":"cct_054","domain":"Data Security","question":"In a Public Key Infrastructure (PKI), which entity is primarily responsible for verifying identities, issuing digital certificates, and maintaining Certificate Revocation Lists (CRLs)?","options":{"A":"Registration Authority (RA)","B":"Certificate Authority (CA)","C":"Key Distribution Center (KDC)","D":"Domain Name Server (DNS)"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. The RA only verifies identity requests before passing them to the CA.","B":"Correct! The Certificate Authority (CA) signs and issues digital certificates and keeps revocation records.","C":"Incorrect. KDCs issue Kerberos tickets.","D":"Incorrect. DNS maps domain names."}},{"id":"cct_055","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"Which version of the Simple Network Management Protocol (SNMP) introduced critical security enhancements such as message integrity, authentication, and encryption?","options":{"A":"SNMPv1","B":"SNMPv2","C":"SNMPv2c","D":"SNMPv3"},"correct_option":"D","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. SNMPv1 transmits credentials in plaintext.","B":"Incorrect. SNMPv2 lacks built-in encryption.","C":"Incorrect. SNMPv2c uses community strings in plaintext.","D":"Correct! SNMPv3 provides message integrity checking, authentication hashing, and payload encryption."}},{"id":"cct_056","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"What is the primary function of a Security Information and Event Management (SIEM) system in a Security Operations Center (SOC)?","options":{"A":"To automatically block DDoS attacks at the network perimeter.","B":"To scan web applications for coding vulnerabilities.","C":"To aggregate, correlate, and analyze log data from multiple security devices and systems in real-time.","D":"To encrypt data at rest on enterprise storage arrays."},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. SIEM is not a blocking firewall.","B":"Incorrect. Coding scans are done by SAST/DAST tools.","C":"Correct! SIEM aggregates logs from all devices and uses correlation engines to detect suspicious activity patterns.","D":"Incorrect. SIEM does not manage storage encryption."}},{"id":"cct_057","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"Which of the following is considered a typical Indicator of Compromise (IoC) that a security analyst might look for during threat hunting?","options":{"A":"Regular, scheduled backups completing successfully.","B":"An unusual outbound network connection to a known malicious IP address.","C":"Users logging into the VPN during standard business hours.","D":"An updated antivirus definition file."},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Backups are healthy operations.","B":"Correct! Connections to known command-and-control server IPs are critical Indicators of Compromise.","C":"Incorrect. Regular VPN logins are normal.","D":"Incorrect. Updates are healthy system actions."}},{"id":"cct_058","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"A penetration tester is using Nmap and wants to determine the operating system of the target machine by analyzing TCP/IP stack fingerprinting. Which Nmap command-line switch should be used?","options":{"A":"-sS","B":"-p","C":"-O","D":"-sV"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. -sS performs a TCP SYN stealth scan.","B":"Incorrect. -p specifies port targets.","C":"Correct! The -O flag enables OS detection based on stack fingerprinting.","D":"Incorrect. -sV determines service/version details."}},{"id":"cct_059","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"During the Business Continuity Planning (BCP) process, which activity is used to identify critical business functions, quantify the impact of their disruption, and determine recovery time objectives (RTOs)?","options":{"A":"Vulnerability Scanning","B":"Penetration Testing","C":"Business Impact Analysis (BIA)","D":"Incident Response Planning"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Vulnerability scanning searches for software bugs.","B":"Incorrect. Penetration testing evaluates system defense strengths.","C":"Correct! BIA (Business Impact Analysis) assesses the consequences of business interruptions to determine recovery schedules.","D":"Incorrect. Incident response planning designs actions taken immediately during an incident."}},{"id":"cct_060","domain":"Data Security","question":"Which access control model assigns permissions based on security clearance levels of the subjects and classification labels assigned to the objects, commonly used in military environments?","options":{"A":"Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","B":"Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","C":"Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","D":"Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC)"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. DAC permits data owners to pass permissions.","B":"Incorrect. RBAC assigns permissions based on roles.","C":"Correct! Mandatory Access Control (MAC) enforces permissions based on strict clearance classifications.","D":"Incorrect. ABAC uses attributes (such as department, location, time) to decide access."}},{"id":"cct_061","domain":"Data Security","question":"Which of the following cryptographic algorithms is an asymmetric (public-key) algorithm used for secure key exchange and digital signatures?","options":{"A":"AES","B":"DES","C":"RSA","D":"RC4"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. AES is a symmetric block cipher.","B":"Incorrect. DES is a symmetric block cipher.","C":"Correct! RSA is an asymmetric algorithm used for public/private key pairs, encryption, and signing.","D":"Incorrect. RC4 is a symmetric stream cipher."}},{"id":"cct_062","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"An attacker calls the company helpdesk, pretending to be a senior executive who forgot their password, and convinces the technician to reset it. What type of attack is this?","options":{"A":"Spear Phishing","B":"Vishing","C":"Whaling","D":"Social Engineering (Pretexting)"},"correct_option":"D","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Spear phishing is highly targeted email baiting.","B":"Incorrect. Vishing is generic phone phishing.","C":"Incorrect. Whaling targets senior executives rather than impersonating them.","D":"Correct! Pretexting involves fabricating a scenario (pretext) to impersonate someone else and trick support staff."}},{"id":"cct_063","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"During the incident response process, the security team successfully removes the malware from the affected systems, disables breached accounts, and applies necessary security patches. Which phase of the incident response lifecycle are they currently executing?","options":{"A":"Preparation","B":"Detection and Analysis","C":"Containment","D":"Eradication"},"correct_option":"D","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Preparation deals with system hardening before attacks.","B":"Incorrect. Detection and analysis focuses on logging and scoping.","C":"Incorrect. Containment acts to stop malware from spreading (e.g. unplugging lines).","D":"Correct! Eradication removes the root threat components (e.g. malware files, compromised accounts)."}},{"id":"cct_064","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"A security analyst configures a port mirror on a core switch to send a copy of all network traffic to an Intrusion Detection System (IDS). Which operational mode does this IDS utilize?","options":{"A":"Inline mode","B":"Promiscuous (out-of-band) mode","C":"Blocking mode","D":"Proxy mode"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Inline mode places the security device directly in the traffic flow.","B":"Correct! In promiscuous (out-of-band) mode, the device receives copies of traffic from a SPAN/port mirror to inspect it passively.","C":"Incorrect. Blocking is active IPS operation.","D":"Incorrect. Proxy mode intercepts client connections directly."}},{"id":"cct_065","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"Which network security device acts as an intermediary for requests from clients seeking resources from other servers, often providing caching, anonymity, and web filtering?","options":{"A":"Load Balancer","B":"Proxy Server","C":"Layer 2 Switch","D":"Repeater"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Load balancers distribute incoming traffic across multiple backend servers.","B":"Correct! A proxy server acts as an intermediary, forwarding client requests and offering caching, security, and filtering.","C":"Incorrect. Layer 2 switches forward frames within a local network.","D":"Incorrect. Repeaters physically regenerate signal strength."}},{"id":"cct_066","domain":"Wireless Device Security","question":"An attacker sets up a fraudulent wireless access point with the exact same SSID as the legitimate corporate network to intercept user credentials. What is this specific attack called?","options":{"A":"Bluejacking","B":"Evil Twin","C":"Wardriving","D":"Jamming"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Bluejacking sends unsolicited messages via Bluetooth.","B":"Correct! An Evil Twin is a rogue wireless access point that mimics a legitimate SSID to steal logins.","C":"Incorrect. Wardriving is scanning for active wireless networks from a moving vehicle.","D":"Incorrect. Jamming is active wireless signal interference."}},{"id":"cct_067","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"In a Linux environment, which command is used to change the file permissions so that the owner has read, write, and execute permissions (7), while the group and others have only read and execute permissions (5)?","options":{"A":"chmod 777","B":"chmod 755","C":"chmod 644","D":"chown 755"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. chmod 777 grants read, write, and execute to everyone.","B":"Correct! chmod 755 grants full rights (7) to owner and read/execute rights (5) to group and others.","C":"Incorrect. chmod 644 grants read/write to owner, and read-only to others.","D":"Incorrect. chown changes file ownership, not permission bits."}},{"id":"cct_068","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"Which phase of the Cyber Kill Chain involves the attacker creating a malicious payload, such as a PDF file with a built-in exploit, tailored to a specific vulnerability in the target's environment?","options":{"A":"Reconnaissance","B":"Weaponization","C":"Exploitation","D":"Actions on Objectives"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Reconnaissance gathers info on the target.","B":"Correct! Weaponization couples exploits with delivery payloads (like PDF or DOCX files).","C":"Incorrect. Exploitation triggers the payload on the target system.","D":"Incorrect. Actions on Objectives is the final step to achieve the attack's goal."}},{"id":"cct_069","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"A security analyst uses the CVSS framework to evaluate a newly discovered vulnerability. What does CVSS stand for?","options":{"A":"Common Vulnerability Scoring System","B":"Critical Vector Security Standard","C":"Cyber Vulnerability Severity Scale","D":"Certified Vulnerability Scanning System"},"correct_option":"A","explanations":{"A":"Correct! CVSS stands for Common Vulnerability Scoring System, the global standard for rating vulnerability severity.","B":"Incorrect. This is a distractor.","C":"Incorrect. This is a distractor.","D":"Incorrect. This is a distractor."}},{"id":"cct_070","domain":"Data Security","question":"What is the primary purpose of adding a cryptographic 'salt' to a password before hashing it in a database?","options":{"A":"To encrypt the password in transit.","B":"To reduce the length of the resulting hash.","C":"To defend against dictionary and rainbow table attacks.","D":"To allow the password to be decrypted later."},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Salting does not secure transit communications.","B":"Incorrect. Hash digests have fixed lengths regardless of salting.","C":"Correct! Adding a salt ensures unique hashes for identical passwords, breaking precomputed rainbow tables.","D":"Incorrect. Hashes are one-way functions and cannot be decrypted."}},{"id":"cct_071","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"An employee plugs a randomly found USB drive into their corporate workstation out of curiosity, which triggers the installation of a backdoor. Which type of social engineering attack does this represent?","options":{"A":"Phishing","B":"Tailgating","C":"Baiting","D":"Quid pro quo"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Phishing uses digital communication channels.","B":"Incorrect. Tailgating is physically following someone through a door.","C":"Correct! Baiting uses physical media (like USBs) left in public spots to trigger user curiosity.","D":"Incorrect. Quid pro quo offers a service/benefit in exchange for access."}},{"id":"cct_072","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"Which business continuity metric defines the maximum acceptable amount of time that a system, network, or application can be offline after a disaster occurs?","options":{"A":"RPO (Recovery Point Objective)","B":"RTO (Recovery Time Objective)","C":"MTBF (Mean Time Between Failures)","D":"MTTR (Mean Time to Repair)"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. RPO defines maximum acceptable data loss in terms of time.","B":"Correct! RTO (Recovery Time Objective) defines the target maximum time allowed to restore operations.","C":"Incorrect. MTBF measures average time between equipment failures.","D":"Incorrect. MTTR measures average time to repair a failure."}},{"id":"cct_073","domain":"Application Security and Cloud Computing","question":"An attacker manipulates a web application's URL input field by entering ../../etc/passwd to access files outside the intended web root directory. What type of attack is this?","options":{"A":"SQL Injection","B":"Command Injection","C":"Directory Traversal","D":"Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. SQL injection exploits SQL queries.","B":"Incorrect. Command injection runs OS terminal commands.","C":"Correct! Directory traversal uses dot-dot-slash sequence inputs to break out of directories.","D":"Incorrect. XSS runs scripts in the client browser."}},{"id":"cct_074","domain":"Application Security and Cloud Computing","question":"Which Cloud computing model requires the customer to manage the operating system, applications, and data, while the cloud provider only manages the physical servers, storage, and networking?","options":{"A":"SaaS (Software as a Service)","B":"PaaS (Platform as a Service)","C":"IaaS (Infrastructure as a Service)","D":"DaaS (Desktop as a Service)"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. SaaS manages all layers including apps.","B":"Incorrect. PaaS manages middleware and operating systems.","C":"Correct! Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) supplies raw infrastructure, requiring the customer to manage OS and applications.","D":"Incorrect. DaaS is virtual desktop hosting."}},{"id":"cct_075","domain":"Network Security Fundamentals","question":"Which protocol is used by the standard command-line ping utility to send echo request and echo reply messages to test network connectivity?","options":{"A":"TCP","B":"UDP","C":"ICMP","D":"IGMP"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. TCP is a connection-oriented transport protocol.","B":"Incorrect. UDP is a connectionless transport protocol.","C":"Correct! The ping utility uses ICMP (Internet Control Message Protocol) packets.","D":"Incorrect. IGMP is used for multicast group management."}},{"id":"cct_076","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"In digital forensics, why is it critical to create a bit-by-bit forensic image of a seized hard drive rather than just copying the files via the operating system to a USB drive?","options":{"A":"A bit-by-bit image is significantly faster to create.","B":"Copying files alters file metadata and misses deleted/hidden files in unallocated space.","C":"Standard USB drives cannot store operating system system files.","D":"Bit-by-bit images automatically decrypt BitLocker encrypted drives."},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Bit-by-bit cloning is typically slower than file copying.","B":"Correct! Forensic bit-level images capture all storage areas (including deleted sectors) without modifying file timestamps.","C":"Incorrect. USB drives can store any file type.","D":"Incorrect. Decryption requires specific keys/passwords regardless of imaging."}},{"id":"cct_077","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"What type of malicious software relies on a specific event, specific date/time, or logical condition to trigger its destructive payload?","options":{"A":"Ransomware","B":"Logic Bomb","C":"Worm","D":"Spyware"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Ransomware triggers immediately upon infection.","B":"Correct! A logic bomb lies dormant until triggered by an exact logical condition.","C":"Incorrect. Worms spread actively across networks.","D":"Incorrect. Spyware monitors and reports user activities silently."}},{"id":"cct_078","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"Which network architecture concept involves placing public-facing servers (like web and email servers) in a separate, isolated subnetwork to protect the internal corporate LAN?","options":{"A":"VPN","B":"VLAN","C":"DMZ","D":"Intranet"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. A VPN extends private networks over public networks.","B":"Incorrect. A VLAN segment is logical and inside the LAN.","C":"Correct! A DMZ (Demilitarized Zone) isolates internet-facing services to protect internal private networks.","D":"Incorrect. The intranet is the internal network itself."}},{"id":"cct_079","domain":"Data Security","question":"Which cryptographic principle guarantees that a message has not been altered, modified, or corrupted in transit between the sender and the receiver?","options":{"A":"Confidentiality","B":"Integrity","C":"Non-repudiation","D":"Availability"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Confidentiality keeps data hidden from unauthorized eyes.","B":"Correct! Integrity guarantees that data remains unaltered.","C":"Incorrect. Non-repudiation prevents denying actions.","D":"Incorrect. Availability ensures data remains accessible."}},{"id":"cct_080","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"An administrator configures a Windows Active Directory environment so that employees automatically map network drives and receive password policies based on their department. Which AD feature is used to apply these configurations en masse?","options":{"A":"Domain Name System (DNS)","B":"Group Policy Objects (GPO)","C":"Remote Desktop Protocol (RDP)","D":"Windows Server Update Services (WSUS)"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. DNS maps hostnames to IPs.","B":"Correct! Group Policy Objects (GPOs) manage security and configuration baselines across AD groups.","C":"Incorrect. RDP is for remote desktop sessions.","D":"Incorrect. WSUS manages Windows patch distributions."}},{"id":"cct_081","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"A security team conducts a paper-based exercise where they discuss their roles and theoretical responses to a simulated ransomware attack scenario without affecting actual production systems. What type of test is this?","options":{"A":"Penetration Test","B":"Tabletop Exercise","C":"Vulnerability Scan","D":"Parallel Test"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Penetration tests are active system attacks.","B":"Correct! A tabletop exercise is a discussion-based simulation to walk through response playbooks.","C":"Incorrect. Vulnerability scanning evaluates software code automatically.","D":"Incorrect. Parallel testing runs redundant systems simultaneously."}},{"id":"cct_082","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"Which Windows command-line utility is specifically used to display active TCP connections, listening ports, and Ethernet statistics?","options":{"A":"ipconfig","B":"tracert","C":"netstat","D":"nslookup"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. ipconfig displays network interface IP settings.","B":"Incorrect. tracert displays router paths.","C":"Correct! netstat displays active port mappings, active socket connections, and network metrics.","D":"Incorrect. nslookup queries DNS records."}},{"id":"cct_083","domain":"Application Security and Cloud Computing","question":"What is the fundamental architectural difference between a Type 1 (Bare Metal) and a Type 2 (Hosted) hypervisor?","options":{"A":"Type 1 hypervisors require internet access; Type 2 do not.","B":"Type 1 hypervisors run directly on the host's hardware; Type 2 run on top of a pre-existing host operating system.","C":"Type 1 hypervisors are open-source; Type 2 are commercial.","D":"Type 1 hypervisors only support Linux VMs; Type 2 support Windows VMs."},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Hypervisor installation location does not determine network needs.","B":"Correct! Type 1 hypervisors sit directly on the computer hardware, whereas Type 2 hypervisors sit on a host OS.","C":"Incorrect. Licensing models vary widely for both types.","D":"Incorrect. Both hypervisor types support diverse guest OS platforms."}},{"id":"cct_084","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"An organization implements an access control system where access permissions are strictly determined by the user's job function and responsibilities within the company. What type of access control is this?","options":{"A":"Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","B":"Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","C":"Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","D":"Rule-Based Access Control (RuBAC)"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. MAC uses clearances and labels.","B":"Incorrect. DAC allows file owners to distribute access.","C":"Correct! Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) maps privileges to corporate job responsibilities/roles.","D":"Incorrect. Rule-based access uses system settings rules (like firewall policies)."}},{"id":"cct_085","domain":"Network Security Fundamentals","question":"During a network traffic analysis using Wireshark, a technician observes heavy traffic exclusively on UDP port 53. Which fundamental network protocol is generating this traffic?","options":{"A":"HTTP","B":"DNS","C":"DHCP","D":"SMTP"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. HTTP uses TCP port 80.","B":"Correct! DNS requests run primarily on UDP port 53.","C":"Incorrect. DHCP uses UDP ports 67/68.","D":"Incorrect. SMTP uses TCP port 25."}},{"id":"cct_086","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"Which Layer 2 attack technique is used to trick a switch into functioning like a simple hub (broadcasting all traffic to all ports) by overwhelming its CAM table, thereby allowing an attacker to sniff traffic?","options":{"A":"ARP Spoofing","B":"MAC Flooding","C":"DHCP Starvation","D":"VLAN Hopping"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. ARP spoofing targets IP-to-MAC association tables.","B":"Correct! MAC Flooding overflows the CAM table, triggering a fail-open state where the switch broadcasts like a hub.","C":"Incorrect. DHCP starvation exhausts DHCP IP pools.","D":"Incorrect. VLAN hopping bypasses logical segment isolations."}},{"id":"cct_087","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"In the context of risk management, calculating the Annualized Loss Expectancy (ALE) by multiplying the Single Loss Expectancy (SLE) by the Annualized Rate of Occurrence (ARO) is an example of:","options":{"A":"Qualitative Risk Assessment","B":"Quantitative Risk Assessment","C":"Risk Avoidance","D":"Business Impact Analysis"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Qualitative assessment uses descriptive scenarios rather than math formulas.","B":"Correct! Multiplying Single Loss (SLE) by annual rate (ARO) to get Annualized Loss (ALE) is a mathematical, Quantitative Risk Assessment method.","C":"Incorrect. Risk avoidance is a response strategy, not a risk calculation type.","D":"Incorrect. BIA is a wider BCP phase assessing interruption impacts."}},{"id":"cct_088","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"Which authentication framework allows a user to log in once with a single set of credentials and access multiple independent software systems without being prompted to log in again?","options":{"A":"Multi-Factor Authentication (MFA)","B":"Single Sign-On (SSO)","C":"Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","D":"Point-to-Point Protocol (PPP)"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. MFA requires multiple credentials factors.","B":"Correct! Single Sign-On (SSO) enables logging in once to gain access to multiple independent software systems.","C":"Incorrect. RBAC determines permissions based on roles.","D":"Incorrect. PPP is a Layer 2 communication protocol."}},{"id":"cct_089","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"A piece of malware self-replicates and spreads across the network exploiting vulnerabilities, without requiring any user interaction or a host file to attach itself to. Which type of malware is this?","options":{"A":"Virus","B":"Trojan","C":"Worm","D":"Keylogger"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Viruses require host files and user execution.","B":"Incorrect. Trojans pose as safe software.","C":"Correct! A worm is a standalone self-replicating malware that spreads over network connections.","D":"Incorrect. Keyloggers record keystrokes."}},{"id":"cct_090","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"Which security concept describes the practice of removing unnecessary software, disabling unused services, and closing unneeded ports on an operating system to systematically reduce its attack surface?","options":{"A":"Patch Management","B":"System Hardening","C":"Network Segmentation","D":"Penetration Testing"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Patch management applies system updates.","B":"Correct! System hardening secures computers by turning off unused services, blocking ports, and configuring settings.","C":"Incorrect. Network segmentation divides networks into logical segments.","D":"Incorrect. Penetration testing probes systems for vulnerabilities."}},{"id":"cct_091","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"An attacker intercepts communications between a user and a secure banking site by impersonating the bank's digital certificate and the user's session. What type of attack is occurring?","options":{"A":"Denial of Service (DoS)","B":"Man-in-the-Middle (MitM)","C":"SQL Injection","D":"Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. DoS blocks service availability.","B":"Correct! Intercepting session communication by posing as the banking server is a Man-in-the-Middle (MitM) attack.","C":"Incorrect. SQL injection attacks databases.","D":"Incorrect. XSS injects scripts into browsers."}},{"id":"cct_092","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"Which physical and environmental security control ensures that if a sudden power outage occurs, critical servers remain operational long enough to safely shut down or transition to a backup generator?","options":{"A":"HVAC System","B":"Faraday Cage","C":"Uninterruptible Power Supply (UPS)","D":"Mantrap"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. HVAC monitors heating and air conditioning.","B":"Incorrect. Faraday cages block signals.","C":"Correct! An Uninterruptible Power Supply (UPS) provides backup power during sudden outages.","D":"Incorrect. Mantraps protect doors."}},{"id":"cct_093","domain":"Data Security","question":"In asymmetric cryptography, if Alice wants to send a confidential, encrypted message to Bob (and only Bob should be able to read it), which key should Alice use to encrypt the message?","options":{"A":"Alice's Public Key","B":"Alice's Private Key","C":"Bob's Public Key","D":"Bob's Private Key"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Encrypting with Alice's public key makes it readable only by Alice.","B":"Incorrect. Encrypting with Alice's private key provides signatures (anyone can read it using her public key).","C":"Correct! Alice encrypts using Bob's Public Key to ensure only Bob (holding his private key) can decrypt it.","D":"Incorrect. Alice does not have access to Bob's Private Key."}},{"id":"cct_094","domain":"Data Security","question":"Which data state specifically refers to information being actively processed in computer memory (RAM) or CPU registers, where it is generally unencrypted?","options":{"A":"Data at Rest","B":"Data in Transit","C":"Data in Use","D":"Data in Motion"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Data at rest is stored statically on disk.","B":"Incorrect. Data in transit is crossing cables/network links.","C":"Correct! Data in use is actively being processed by applications in RAM or registers.","D":"Incorrect. Data in motion is another term for data in transit."}},{"id":"cct_095","domain":"Data Security","question":"A network engineer is configuring a storage array and needs a setup that provides both data striping and parity to ensure fault tolerance, requiring a minimum of three disk drives. Which RAID level should be implemented?","options":{"A":"RAID 0","B":"RAID 1","C":"RAID 5","D":"RAID 10"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. RAID 0 provides striping only, no fault tolerance, and requires a minimum of two disks.","B":"Incorrect. RAID 1 provides mirroring only, no parity, and requires a minimum of two disks.","C":"Correct! RAID 5 uses block-level striping with distributed parity, requiring a minimum of three disks to provide fault tolerance.","D":"Incorrect. RAID 10 combines mirroring and striping, requiring a minimum of four disks."}},{"id":"cct_096","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"What is the primary difference between an Intrusion Detection System (IDS) and an Intrusion Prevention System (IPS)?","options":{"A":"An IDS is placed out-of-band and only alerts on malicious traffic, whereas an IPS is placed inline and can actively block malicious traffic.","B":"An IDS only analyzes network traffic, whereas an IPS only analyzes host-based logs.","C":"An IDS is used for encrypted traffic, whereas an IPS is used for unencrypted traffic.","D":"An IDS blocks traffic based on IP addresses, whereas an IPS blocks traffic based on MAC addresses."},"correct_option":"A","explanations":{"A":"Correct! An IDS passively inspects traffic out-of-band (alerting only), while an IPS sits inline directly in the traffic flow and can actively drop packets to block attacks.","B":"Incorrect. Both IDS and IPS can be either host-based (HIDS/HIPS) or network-based (NIDS/NIPS).","C":"Incorrect. Neither is limited exclusively to encrypted or unencrypted traffic.","D":"Incorrect. This is not the primary difference; both analyze payloads for signatures and anomalies, rather than filtering purely by Layer 2/3 headers."}},{"id":"cct_097","domain":"Application Security and Cloud Computing","question":"An attacker tricks an authenticated user's browser into executing an unwanted action (such as a fund transfer) on a trusted website where the user is currently logged in. Which web application vulnerability is being exploited?","options":{"A":"Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)","B":"Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF)","C":"Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF)","D":"Local File Inclusion (LFI)"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. XSS involves injecting malicious scripts to execute on the client's browser.","B":"Incorrect. SSRF tricks the backend server into making requests to unauthorized internal destinations.","C":"Correct! Cross-Site Request Forgery (CSRF) exploits the trust relationship of a browser session by tricking it into performing unauthorized actions.","D":"Incorrect. LFI involves including local files on the server through input manipulation."}},{"id":"cct_098","domain":"Application Security and Cloud Computing","question":"To enforce security policies, monitor user activity, and detect threats between an organization's on-premises infrastructure and a cloud provider's infrastructure, which security solution should be deployed?","options":{"A":"Web Application Firewall (WAF)","B":"Cloud Access Security Broker (CASB)","C":"Virtual Private Network (VPN)","D":"Mobile Device Management (MDM)"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. A WAF protects web applications from typical web exploits but does not enforce general cloud service policies.","B":"Correct! A Cloud Access Security Broker (CASB) is a software or hardware tool placed between cloud service consumers and providers to enforce security, compliance, and threat prevention policies.","C":"Incorrect. A VPN provides a secure tunnel but doesn't perform threat/compliance checking and policy enforcement for cloud services.","D":"Incorrect. MDM manages and secures end-user mobile devices."}},{"id":"cct_099","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"Which UDP port is used by default for the Syslog protocol to send event messages to a centralized logging server?","options":{"A":"Port 22","B":"Port 161","C":"Port 443","D":"Port 514"},"correct_option":"D","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Port 22 is used by default for SSH.","B":"Incorrect. Port 161 is used by default for SNMP.","C":"Incorrect. Port 443 is used by default for HTTPS.","D":"Correct! Syslog uses UDP port 514 by default to send event logging messages to a collector."}},{"id":"cct_100","domain":"Data Security","question":"In cryptography, what is the primary security goal achieved by having a sender digitally sign a document using their private key?","options":{"A":"Confidentiality","B":"Non-repudiation","C":"Availability","D":"Obfuscation"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Confidentiality is achieved by encrypting the document with the recipient's public key.","B":"Correct! Signing with a private key provides authenticity and integrity, ensuring the sender cannot deny sending the document (Non-repudiation).","C":"Incorrect. Availability ensures systems and data are accessible, which is not direct to cryptographic signing.","D":"Incorrect. Obfuscation hides data structure/meaning, whereas signing verifies origin without necessarily encrypting the data."}},{"id":"cct_101","domain":"Wireless Device Security","question":"An organization provides smartphones to its employees. The devices are owned by the company, but employees are allowed to use them for personal tasks as long as corporate data is containerized. Which mobile deployment model is this?","options":{"A":"BYOD (Bring Your Own Device)","B":"CYOD (Choose Your Own Device)","C":"COPE (Corporate-Owned, Personally Enabled)","D":"COBO (Corporate-Owned, Business Only)"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. BYOD allows employees to use their personal devices for work.","B":"Incorrect. CYOD lets employees choose from a list of approved corporate-owned devices, but it refers to selection rather than personal enablement policy.","C":"Correct! COPE (Corporate-Owned, Personally Enabled) means the organization owns the device but allows personal use, separating work and personal profiles via containerization.","D":"Incorrect. COBO strictly forbids any personal use on company-owned devices."}},{"id":"cct_102","domain":"Wireless Device Security","question":"What is the most common vulnerability found in consumer Internet of Things (IoT) devices that allows botnets like Mirai to easily compromise them?","options":{"A":"Use of state-of-the-art encryption","B":"Hardcoded, default usernames and passwords","C":"Complex, multifactor authentication requirements","D":"Frequent, automatic firmware updates"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Mirai exploits weak access controls, not advanced encryption.","B":"Correct! The Mirai botnet compromised hundreds of thousands of IoT devices by scanning for open Telnet ports and trying a list of well-known default credentials.","C":"Incorrect. Multi-factor authentication would have prevented Mirai, but IoT devices rarely support it by default.","D":"Incorrect. Frequent updates patch vulnerabilities, whereas IoT devices often suffer from lack of updates."}},{"id":"cct_103","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"During a digital forensics investigation, an analyst runs an MD5 hashing tool on a seized hard drive. What is the purpose of this action?","options":{"A":"To encrypt the hard drive's contents.","B":"To prove the integrity of the evidence by verifying it has not changed.","C":"To extract hidden files from unallocated space.","D":"To decrypt passwords stored in the registry."},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Hashing is a one-way mathematical function and does not encrypt files for storage.","B":"Correct! Computing a cryptographic hash (like MD5 or SHA-256) of the seized media allows investigators to prove that the evidence has remained pristine and unaltered throughout its custody chain.","C":"Incorrect. Carving or file extraction tools (not hashes) recover deleted files from unallocated space.","D":"Incorrect. Hashing is one-way and cannot be used to decrypt passwords."}},{"id":"cct_104","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"Which attack technique involves sending falsified Address Resolution Protocol (ARP) messages over a Local Area Network (LAN) to link an attacker's MAC address with the IP address of a legitimate computer or server?","options":{"A":"DNS Spoofing","B":"MAC Spoofing","C":"ARP Poisoning","D":"DHCP Starvation"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. DNS spoofing redirects name resolution queries.","B":"Incorrect. MAC spoofing changes an attacker's NIC physical address to match a victim's MAC address.","C":"Correct! ARP Poisoning (or ARP Spoofing) sends fraudulent ARP packets to a LAN to associate the attacker's MAC address with a target's IP address, enabling Man-in-the-Middle attacks.","D":"Incorrect. DHCP starvation exhausts IP pools by spoofing multiple DHCP client requests."}},{"id":"cct_105","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"In Risk Management, what term is used to describe the amount of risk that remains after an organization has implemented appropriate security controls to mitigate a threat?","options":{"A":"Inherent Risk","B":"Residual Risk","C":"Accepted Risk","D":"Calculated Risk"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Inherent risk is the raw risk level before any security controls or countermeasures are applied.","B":"Correct! Residual risk is the leftover risk that remains after an organization implements mitigation controls.","C":"Incorrect. Accepted risk is what the organization decides to tolerate, which might be a response to the residual risk.","D":"Incorrect. Calculated risk is a generic term for risk assessment values."}},{"id":"cct_106","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"A security operations center (SOC) analyst uses a SIEM tool to link a failed login attempt on a firewall, a malware detection alert from an endpoint, and an unusual outbound connection attempt. What SIEM capability is the analyst utilizing?","options":{"A":"Log Aggregation","B":"Data Retention","C":"Event Correlation","D":"Alert Suppression"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Log aggregation collects and normalizes logs from multiple sources but doesn't link them logically into a combined alert.","B":"Incorrect. Data retention is the practice of storing log data over historical periods.","C":"Correct! Event correlation is a SIEM capability that connects separate security events from different systems using logical rules to identify complex attack patterns.","D":"Incorrect. Alert suppression hides repetitive alerts to reduce alarm fatigue."}},{"id":"cct_107","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"A company establishes an alternate data center facility equipped with fully configured servers, active internet connections, and up-to-date data backups that can take over operations within minutes of a disaster. What type of disaster recovery site is this?","options":{"A":"Cold Site","B":"Warm Site","C":"Hot Site","D":"Mobile Site"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. A cold site contains raw floor space, power, and cooling, but no pre-configured hardware.","B":"Incorrect. A warm site has hardware and network links configured but needs data restoration and configuration before going live.","C":"Correct! A hot site is a fully mirrored, redundant data center that is active and contains synchronized data, capable of taking over operations within minutes of a failure.","D":"Incorrect. A mobile site is a portable trailer with hardware, not a permanent datacenter."}},{"id":"cct_108","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"To capture all network traffic traveling across a network segment using a packet sniffer like Wireshark, the computer's Network Interface Card (NIC) must be placed into which operational mode?","options":{"A":"Managed mode","B":"Promiscuous mode","C":"Monitor mode","D":"Stealth mode"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Managed mode is a wireless interface mode for connecting to access points.","B":"Correct! In promiscuous mode, a wired NIC captures and forwards all received frames on the shared medium to the OS, rather than discarding frames not addressed to its own MAC address.","C":"Incorrect. Monitor mode is used on wireless networks to sniff RF traffic without associating with an AP.","D":"Incorrect. Stealth mode generally refers to firewalls not responding to ping probes."}},{"id":"cct_109","domain":"Application Security and Cloud Computing","question":"What is the practice of integrating security testing, vulnerability management, and compliance checks directly into the continuous integration and continuous deployment (CI/CD) software development pipeline?","options":{"A":"Waterfall Development","B":"Agile Methodology","C":"DevSecOps","D":"Black-Box Testing"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Waterfall is a sequential software development lifecycle model.","B":"Incorrect. Agile is a methodology focusing on iterative development and delivery.","C":"Correct! DevSecOps integrates security controls, testing, and vulnerability checks directly into the continuous integration and deployment pipeline (DevOps).","D":"Incorrect. Black-box testing evaluates software from an external perspective without source code access."}},{"id":"cct_110","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"When evaluating biometric authentication systems, what metric represents the point where the False Acceptance Rate (FAR) and the False Rejection Rate (FRR) intersect, indicating the overall accuracy of the system?","options":{"A":"Crossover Error Rate (CER)","B":"True Positive Rate (TPR)","C":"Equal Error Rate (EER)","D":"Both A and C"},"correct_option":"D","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. While CER (Crossover Error Rate) is correct, it is identical to EER (Equal Error Rate), making option D the best answer.","B":"Incorrect. True Positive Rate measures the percentage of correctly identified authorized users.","C":"Incorrect. While EER is correct, it is also known as CER.","D":"Correct! Crossover Error Rate (CER) and Equal Error Rate (EER) are interchangeable terms representing the intersection point of FAR and FRR, where a lower rate indicates higher accuracy."}},{"id":"cct_111","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"When configuring an IPsec Virtual Private Network (VPN), which mode encrypts the entire original IP packet (including the original header) and adds a new IP header for routing?","options":{"A":"Transport Mode","B":"Tunnel Mode","C":"Transparent Mode","D":"Bridge Mode"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Transport mode only encrypts the IP payload, preserving the original IP header for routing.","B":"Correct! Tunnel mode encrypts the entire original IP packet (header and payload) and wraps it with a new routing header, typically used in site-to-site VPNs.","C":"Incorrect. Transparent mode is a firewall configuration, not an IPsec mode.","D":"Incorrect. Bridge mode links networks at Layer 2."}},{"id":"cct_112","domain":"Data Security","question":"An organization wants to prevent employees from accidentally or maliciously emailing documents containing credit card numbers and Social Security Numbers outside the corporate network. Which type of system should be implemented?","options":{"A":"Data Loss Prevention (DLP)","B":"Intrusion Prevention System (IPS)","C":"Security Information and Event Management (SIEM)","D":"Endpoint Detection and Response (EDR)"},"correct_option":"A","explanations":{"A":"Correct! Data Loss Prevention (DLP) systems scan outbound traffic (like emails) for patterns matching sensitive information (such as credit cards or SSNs) and block unauthorized transfers.","B":"Incorrect. An IPS blocks network-based attacks and exploits, not general outbound data leakage.","C":"Incorrect. A SIEM aggregates logs for correlation and alerting, but does not actively filter email content.","D":"Incorrect. EDR monitors endpoints for malicious execution and process activity."}},{"id":"cct_113","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"An attacker sifts through the trash bins outside a target organization's office building looking for discarded documents containing passwords, organizational charts, and financial data. What is this technique called?","options":{"A":"Tailgating","B":"Eavesdropping","C":"Dumpster Diving","D":"Shoulder Surfing"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Tailgating is physically passing through an access point behind an authorized employee.","B":"Incorrect. Eavesdropping is interception of communications.","C":"Correct! Dumpster diving is searching physical waste bins for sensitive, discarded business materials.","D":"Incorrect. Shoulder surfing is looking over a user's shoulder to capture input."}},{"id":"cct_114","domain":"Wireless Device Security","question":"Which legacy wireless encryption standard is considered highly insecure because it uses a 24-bit Initialization Vector (IV) and the RC4 stream cipher, allowing its keys to be easily cracked?","options":{"A":"WPA3","B":"WPA2","C":"WPA","D":"WEP"},"correct_option":"D","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. WPA3 is the latest standard using highly secure GCMP-256 and SAE handshakes.","B":"Incorrect. WPA2 uses robust CCMP/AES encryption.","C":"Incorrect. WPA uses TKIP to improve on WEP, but is also deprecated.","D":"Correct! WEP (Wired Equivalent Privacy) uses a short 24-bit IV and the RC4 cipher, making it extremely easy to compromise."}},{"id":"cct_115","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"On a router or firewall, what type of Access Control List (ACL) allows network traffic to be filtered based on a combination of source IP, destination IP, protocol type, and specific port numbers?","options":{"A":"Standard ACL","B":"Extended ACL","C":"MAC ACL","D":"Dynamic ACL"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Standard ACLs can only filter traffic based on the source IP address.","B":"Correct! Extended ACLs filter traffic based on source IP, destination IP, protocol (TCP/UDP/ICMP), and destination port numbers.","C":"Incorrect. MAC ACLs filter traffic based on hardware Layer 2 addresses.","D":"Incorrect. Dynamic ACLs use authentication to temporarily permit access."}},{"id":"cct_116","domain":"Application Security and Cloud Computing","question":"In a virtualized environment, what is the term for a theoretical attack where a malicious process running inside a guest Virtual Machine (VM) bypasses the hypervisor to interact directly with the host operating system or other guest VMs?","options":{"A":"VM Sprawl","B":"VM Escape","C":"Hyperjacking","D":"Snapshot Poisoning"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. VM sprawl is the uncontrolled growth of virtual machines within a network.","B":"Correct! VM Escape is a vulnerability where an attacker running code on a guest VM breaks out to interact directly with the hypervisor or host OS.","C":"Incorrect. Hyperjacking is installing a rogue hypervisor beneath an OS.","D":"Incorrect. Snapshot poisoning is a distractor."}},{"id":"cct_117","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"In the context of Incident Response, what is a \"playbook\" or \"runbook\"?","options":{"A":"A legal document signed by the CISO acknowledging a breach.","B":"A standard operating procedure (SOP) containing step-by-step instructions for responding to specific types of security incidents.","C":"A log file generated by the SIEM showing attacker movements.","D":"A list of approved software allowed on corporate machines."},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. A playbook is an operational tactical guide, not a legal liability document.","B":"Correct! An incident response playbook is a standard operating procedure outlining step-by-step containment, eradication, and response actions for specific incident types.","C":"Incorrect. SIEM logs are transaction records, not structured response workflows.","D":"Incorrect. An approved software list is a whitelist, not an incident response playbook."}},{"id":"cct_118","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"In digital forensics, what is \"slack space\"?","options":{"A":"The empty space left on a desk after physical evidence is removed.","B":"The unused space between the end of a logical file and the end of the physical cluster it occupies, which can contain residual data.","C":"The reserved memory in the CPU used for cryptographic calculations.","D":"The space on a server rack left empty for cooling purposes."},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. This is a physical space distractor.","B":"Correct! Slack space occurs because file systems allocate space in fixed clusters. If a file is smaller than the cluster, the remaining \"slack\" contains bytes from previously deleted files.","C":"Incorrect. Memory allocated to CPU registers is register memory or cache.","D":"Incorrect. Server rack spacing is airflow gap."}},{"id":"cct_119","domain":"Application Security and Cloud Computing","question":"A developer wants to secure a web application against SQL Injection (SQLi) attacks. Which of the following is the MOST effective coding practice to achieve this?","options":{"A":"Implementing client-side JavaScript validation.","B":"Using parameterized queries (prepared statements).","C":"Encrypting the database at rest.","D":"Hiding the database error messages from the user."},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Client-side validation is easily bypassed by intercepting and modifying the HTTP request.","B":"Correct! Parameterized queries (prepared statements) ensure the database treats user input strictly as data, never executable SQL commands.","C":"Incorrect. Encrypting the database at rest protects against disk theft, not injection queries.","D":"Incorrect. Hiding errors prevents disclosure of database structure details, but does not stop the injection execution."}},{"id":"cct_120","domain":"Network Security Fundamentals","question":"A network technician needs to manually query a Domain Name System (DNS) server to troubleshoot hostname-to-IP address resolution issues. Which command-line tool should be used?","options":{"A":"arp -a","B":"netstat -ano","C":"nslookup (or dig)","D":"route print"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. arp -a lists local IP-to-MAC resolutions.","B":"Incorrect. netstat -ano displays active TCP/UDP ports and connection PIDs.","C":"Correct! The nslookup (or dig on Linux/macOS) tool queries DNS servers directly to test hostname resolution.","D":"Incorrect. route print displays the local routing table."}},{"id":"cct_121","domain":"Data Security","question":"An attacker hides a malicious payload inside the code of an otherwise normal-looking JPEG image file without visibly altering the image. Which technique is being used?","options":{"A":"Cryptography","B":"Hashing","C":"Steganography","D":"Obfuscation"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Cryptography scrambles data to ensure confidentiality, making it look like ciphertext.","B":"Incorrect. Hashing creates a unique checksum to verify integrity.","C":"Correct! Steganography is the practice of hiding a secret message or data inside another file (like an image or audio file) without altering its visible appearance.","D":"Incorrect. Obfuscation makes code harder to read but does not hide the file itself inside an image container."}},{"id":"cct_122","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"Which type of firewall keeps track of the state of active network connections (such as the TCP handshake) and makes decisions based on the context of the traffic flow rather than just individual packets?","options":{"A":"Stateless packet filter","B":"Stateful inspection firewall","C":"Web Application Firewall","D":"MAC filtering firewall"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Stateless packet filters evaluate packets individually without connection context.","B":"Correct! A stateful inspection firewall monitors the state of active sessions (like the TCP 3-way handshake) and only permits incoming packets matching an established outbound connection.","C":"Incorrect. A Web Application Firewall (WAF) filters Layer 7 HTTP requests.","D":"Incorrect. MAC filtering permits/denies access based on device hardware addresses."}},{"id":"cct_123","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"Which security document requires employees to agree to specific rules and guidelines before they are granted access to corporate network resources and the internet?","options":{"A":"Non-Disclosure Agreement (NDA)","B":"Business Impact Analysis (BIA)","C":"Acceptable Use Policy (AUP)","D":"Service Level Agreement (SLA)"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. An NDA protects proprietary and confidential business information from being disclosed.","B":"Incorrect. A BIA evaluates the potential impacts of business disruptions.","C":"Correct! An Acceptable Use Policy (AUP) outlines the rules, constraints, and responsibilities employees must agree to when using corporate network assets.","D":"Incorrect. An SLA defines service metrics between a vendor and a customer."}},{"id":"cct_124","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"To effectively mitigate the risk of a ransomware attack causing total data loss, which operational security control is considered the most critical?","options":{"A":"Changing user passwords every 30 days.","B":"Maintaining isolated, offline, and regularly tested data backups.","C":"Disabling USB ports on all corporate laptops.","D":"Upgrading the corporate Wi-Fi to WPA3."},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Changing passwords every 30 days is a credential control, but does not restore encrypted systems.","B":"Correct! Regular, offline (isolated) backups ensure that even if ransomware encrypts production environments, the data can be recovered without paying the ransom.","C":"Incorrect. Disabling USB ports reduces malware vectors but does not assist in system recovery.","D":"Incorrect. Upgrading Wi-Fi to WPA3 secures wireless access but doesn't prevent ransomware payload execution or recover data."}},{"id":"cct_125","domain":"Data Security","question":"In cryptography, what is the primary purpose of the Diffie-Hellman algorithm?","options":{"A":"To encrypt large bulk data files on a hard drive.","B":"To securely exchange cryptographic keys over an insecure public channel.","C":"To generate a fixed-length hash for password storage.","D":"To digitally sign email communications."},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Bulk data encryption is handled by symmetric algorithms like AES.","B":"Correct! Diffie-Hellman (DH) is a key-exchange protocol that allows two parties to establish a shared secret key over an unsecure channel.","C":"Incorrect. Password hashing uses algorithms like bcrypt, Argon2, or SHA-256.","D":"Incorrect. Digital signatures are generated using algorithms like RSA or ECDSA."}},{"id":"cct_126","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"A digital forensics investigator needs to capture the volatile memory (RAM) of a running, compromised Windows server. Which type of tool should be used for this specific task?","options":{"A":"A network packet sniffer (e.g., Wireshark)","B":"A memory dumping utility (e.g., FTK Imager, DumpIt)","C":"A vulnerability scanner (e.g., Nessus)","D":"A password cracker (e.g., Hashcat)"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Packet sniffers capture network traffic in transit, not local volatile memory.","B":"Correct! Utilities like FTK Imager, DumpIt, or LiME are designed to copy the physical RAM of a live system to a file.","C":"Incorrect. Vulnerability scanners check for software flaws and misconfigurations.","D":"Incorrect. Password crackers attempt to reverse hashes using dictionary or brute-force attacks."}},{"id":"cct_127","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"Which security extension is designed to protect the Domain Name System (DNS) by adding cryptographic digital signatures to DNS records, preventing DNS spoofing and cache poisoning?","options":{"A":"DNS over HTTPS (DoH)","B":"IPsec","C":"DNSSEC","D":"TLS/SSL"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. DNS over HTTPS (DoH) encrypts DNS traffic to prevent eavesdropping, but does not provide cryptographically signed origin validation for DNS zones.","B":"Incorrect. IPsec secures traffic between hosts or gateways at the IP layer.","C":"Correct! DNSSEC (DNS Security Extensions) adds digital signatures to DNS records to protect clients from spoofing and cache poisoning.","D":"Incorrect. TLS/SSL secures transport connections (TCP), not the hierarchical DNS database records themselves."}},{"id":"cct_128","domain":"Application Security and Cloud Computing","question":"An attacker manipulates an API request by changing the user ID parameter in the URL from user_id=101 to user_id=102, successfully accessing another user's private account details. Which API vulnerability is this?","options":{"A":"Broken Object Level Authorization (BOLA / IDOR)","B":"Cross-Site Scripting (XSS)","C":"Security Misconfiguration","D":"SQL Injection (SQLi)"},"correct_option":"A","explanations":{"A":"Correct! Broken Object Level Authorization (BOLA), also known as Insecure Direct Object Reference (IDOR), happens when an application fails to check authorization for access to specific database resources via URL input parameters.","B":"Incorrect. XSS involves executing scripts on client browsers.","C":"Incorrect. Security Misconfiguration refers to default accounts, open directories, or unpatched services.","D":"Incorrect. SQL Injection is about executing database commands, not bypassing application-level authorization parameters."}},{"id":"cct_129","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"What is the primary purpose of the MITRE ATT&CK framework in cybersecurity operations?","options":{"A":"To provide a regulatory compliance checklist for financial institutions.","B":"To score the severity of software vulnerabilities on a scale of 1 to 10.","C":"To provide a globally accessible knowledge base of adversary tactics and techniques based on real-world observations.","D":"To automatically patch operating systems against zero-day exploits."},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. ATT&CK is not a regulatory standard or compliance checklist.","B":"Incorrect. The scoring of vulnerability severity is done by the CVSS system.","C":"Correct! The MITRE ATT&CK framework is a structured knowledge base classifying adversary tactics, techniques, and procedures (TTPs) observed in actual cyberattacks.","D":"Incorrect. ATT&CK does not execute patch deployment or direct automated remediation."}},{"id":"cct_130","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"Which protocol is an open standard for access delegation, commonly used as a way for Internet users to grant websites or applications access to their information on other websites but without giving them the passwords?","options":{"A":"RADIUS","B":"OAuth 2.0","C":"IPsec","D":"Kerberos"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. RADIUS is a AAA client-server protocol.","B":"Correct! OAuth 2.0 is an authorization framework allowing third-party apps to obtain restricted access to an HTTP service on behalf of a user.","C":"Incorrect. IPsec is a suite of protocols securing IP communications.","D":"Incorrect. Kerberos is an authentication protocol using tickets to authenticate clients."}},{"id":"cct_131","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"During the incident response process, the team creates an exact bit-by-bit copy of a compromised hard drive. What must be documented immediately to track who handled the evidence, when, and where it was stored?","options":{"A":"Service Level Agreement (SLA)","B":"Chain of Custody","C":"Business Impact Analysis (BIA)","D":"Acceptable Use Policy (AUP)"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. An SLA defines service metrics between a vendor and customer.","B":"Correct! Chain of custody is a chronological paper trail logging the collection, control, transfer, and analysis of physical or digital evidence.","C":"Incorrect. A BIA evaluates disruption impacts for BCP.","D":"Incorrect. An AUP sets rules for employee network usage."}},{"id":"cct_132","domain":"Application Security and Cloud Computing","question":"In an Infrastructure as a Service (IaaS) cloud model, under the Shared Responsibility Model, who is primarily responsible for installing security patches on the guest operating system (e.g., Windows Server or Linux)?","options":{"A":"The Cloud Service Provider (e.g., AWS, Azure)","B":"The Cloud Consumer (The Customer)","C":"The Internet Service Provider (ISP)","D":"Both the Provider and the ISP"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. The provider manages the physical infrastructure, hypervisor, and hosting hardware in IaaS.","B":"Correct! Under the Shared Responsibility Model, the cloud customer is fully responsible for securing the guest operating system and the applications installed on it.","C":"Incorrect. ISPs only manage communication links.","D":"Incorrect. Neither the provider nor the ISP manages the customer's guest OS configuration."}},{"id":"cct_133","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"Which IEEE standard defines port-based network access control (PNAC), ensuring that devices must authenticate (often using EAP/RADIUS) before they are granted access to a switch port or wireless LAN?","options":{"A":"802.11ac","B":"802.1X","C":"802.3af","D":"802.1Q"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. 802.11ac is a wireless communication standard.","B":"Correct! IEEE 802.1X is the standard for port-based network access control (PNAC), ensuring client authentication before access is granted.","C":"Incorrect. 802.3af defines Power over Ethernet (PoE).","D":"Incorrect. 802.1Q defines VLAN tagging on Ethernet frames."}},{"id":"cct_134","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"A security manager calculates risk by categorizing threats using terms like \"High,\" \"Medium,\" and \"Low\" on a risk matrix based on likelihood and impact, rather than using exact monetary values. What type of risk assessment is this?","options":{"A":"Quantitative Risk Assessment","B":"Qualitative Risk Assessment","C":"Penetration Testing","D":"Vulnerability Assessment"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Quantitative assessment uses exact numbers and monetary figures.","B":"Correct! Qualitative risk assessments use descriptive values (such as High, Medium, Low) to rate the likelihood and impact of risks.","C":"Incorrect. Penetration testing actively exploits systems to find vulnerabilities.","D":"Incorrect. Vulnerability assessment identifies weaknesses without evaluating organizational risk levels."}},{"id":"cct_135","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"In a Security Operations Center (SOC), what is a SOAR (Security Orchestration, Automation, and Response) platform primarily used for?","options":{"A":"To manually review printed firewall logs.","B":"To automatically execute playbooks that respond to low-level security alerts, reducing alert fatigue for analysts.","C":"To design physical security layouts for data centers.","D":"To train employees on phishing awareness."},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Reviewing logs manually is a traditional, slow process that SOAR helps replace.","B":"Correct! SOAR platforms combine security orchestration, automation, and response to execute automated workflows (playbooks) and handle threats instantly.","C":"Incorrect. SOAR handles software and network incidents, not physical datacenter blueprints.","D":"Incorrect. SOAR handles incident response automation, not user phishing training."}},{"id":"cct_136","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"In Operational Technology (OT) and Industrial Control Systems (ICS), what is the term used for physically and logically isolating the industrial network from the corporate IT network and the public internet?","options":{"A":"VLAN Tagging","B":"Air-Gapping","C":"Subnetting","D":"Port Mirroring"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. VLAN tagging isolates traffic logically but keeps it on the same physical infrastructure.","B":"Correct! Air-gapping is a security measure that physically isolates a secure network from unsecured networks.","C":"Incorrect. Subnetting creates logical divisions within an IP network.","D":"Incorrect. Port mirroring sends packet copies for analysis but does not isolate networks."}},{"id":"cct_137","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"An attacker compromises a system without installing any traditional executable files on the hard drive. Instead, they use built-in tools like PowerShell and WMI to execute scripts directly in memory. What is this technique called?","options":{"A":"Ransomware","B":"Fileless Malware (Living off the Land)","C":"Boot sector virus","D":"Macro virus"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Ransomware encrypts user files.","B":"Correct! Fileless malware executes malicious scripts directly in RAM or registers using native system utilities like PowerShell (Living off the Land).","C":"Incorrect. Boot sector viruses infect the Master Boot Record on the physical disk.","D":"Incorrect. Macro viruses are embedded within document files."}},{"id":"cct_138","domain":"Application Security and Cloud Computing","question":"Which security control is specifically designed to sit in front of web applications to inspect inbound HTTP/HTTPS traffic and block attacks such as SQL injection, XSS, and directory traversal?","options":{"A":"Network Intrusion Detection System (NIDS)","B":"Web Application Firewall (WAF)","C":"Stateful Packet Inspection Firewall","D":"Load Balancer"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. A NIDS alerts on network-wide attack patterns but does not sit in front of web applications to filter Layer 7 traffic.","B":"Correct! A Web Application Firewall (WAF) monitors and filters HTTP/HTTPS requests to protect web applications from Layer 7 attacks.","C":"Incorrect. Stateful firewalls filter traffic at Layer 3/4 based on ports and IP addresses.","D":"Incorrect. Load balancers distribute requests but do not specialize in web application threat blocking."}},{"id":"cct_139","domain":"Data Security","question":"In a Public Key Infrastructure (PKI), if an employee's laptop is stolen, their digital certificate must be invalidated before it expires naturally. Where is this invalidated certificate's serial number published by the CA?","options":{"A":"Domain Name System (DNS)","B":"Certificate Revocation List (CRL)","C":"Active Directory (AD)","D":"Key Escrow"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. DNS resolves domains to IPs.","B":"Correct! A Certificate Revocation List (CRL) is a list of digital certificates that have been revoked by the issuing Certificate Authority (CA) before their scheduled expiration date.","C":"Incorrect. Active Directory stores directory services information.","D":"Incorrect. Key Escrow stores copies of keys to prevent data loss."}},{"id":"cct_140","domain":"Data Security","question":"A forensic analyst suspects that an attacker is secretly exfiltrating data by hiding secret text messages within the pixels of standard digital photographs. What is the process of detecting this called?","options":{"A":"Cryptanalysis","B":"Steganalysis","C":"Hash checking","D":"Reverse engineering"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Cryptanalysis is the study of cracking cryptographic ciphers and codes.","B":"Correct! Steganalysis is the science of detecting hidden messages within a carrier medium (like finding steganography in images).","C":"Incorrect. Hash checking verifies file integrity, not the presence of steganographic messages.","D":"Incorrect. Reverse engineering analyzes software binary code to understand its function."}},{"id":"cct_141","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"A network administrator configures a switch to restrict input to an interface by limiting and identifying MAC addresses of the workstations that are allowed to access the port. What is this security feature called?","options":{"A":"Port Security","B":"Spanning Tree Protocol (STP)","C":"Port Address Translation (PAT)","D":"Quality of Service (QoS)"},"correct_option":"A","explanations":{"A":"Correct! Port Security is a Cisco switch feature that restricts interface access to specific MAC addresses of authorized computers.","B":"Incorrect. STP prevents Layer 2 switching loops.","C":"Incorrect. PAT maps multiple private IPs to a single public IP.","D":"Incorrect. QoS prioritizes network traffic bandwidth."}},{"id":"cct_142","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"Unlike traditional reactive security monitoring (waiting for an alert to trigger), which practice involves proactively and iteratively searching through networks to detect and isolate advanced threats that evade existing security solutions?","options":{"A":"Penetration Testing","B":"Threat Hunting","C":"Vulnerability Scanning","D":"Patch Management"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Penetration testing simulates active attacks to find exploit routes.","B":"Correct! Threat hunting is the proactive, search-based methodology used by analysts to detect persistent, stealthy threats that have bypassed standard security controls.","C":"Incorrect. Vulnerability scanning is automated vulnerability testing.","D":"Incorrect. Patch management updates software."}},{"id":"cct_143","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"Which modern security framework operates on the strict principle of \"Never trust, always verify,\" requiring strict identity verification for every person and device trying to access resources, regardless of whether they are sitting inside or outside the network perimeter?","options":{"A":"Zero Trust Architecture","B":"Defense in Depth","C":"Discretionary Access Control","D":"Open Systems Interconnection (OSI)"},"correct_option":"A","explanations":{"A":"Correct! Zero Trust Architecture is a framework built on the premise that no device or user should be trusted by default, regardless of their network location.","B":"Incorrect. Defense in depth implements multiple layers of controls.","C":"Incorrect. DAC is an access control model based on file ownership.","D":"Incorrect. OSI is a reference model mapping network communication layers."}},{"id":"cct_144","domain":"Application Security and Cloud Computing","question":"When securing containerized applications (like Docker), which practice is crucial before deploying a container image to a production environment?","options":{"A":"Ensuring the container runs with root privileges.","B":"Scanning the container image for known vulnerabilities and hardcoded secrets.","C":"Disabling all network interfaces on the host machine.","D":"Encrypting the host's BIOS."},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Containers should be run with the least privileges (non-root) to prevent sandbox breakout attacks.","B":"Correct! Scanning the image identifies outdated libraries, known vulnerabilities, and hardcoded credentials before deployment.","C":"Incorrect. Disabling network interfaces would prevent the container application from communicating.","D":"Incorrect. Encrypting the BIOS is a physical host security configuration, not container security."}},{"id":"cct_145","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"A security team sets up a deliberately vulnerable server on an isolated network segment to attract attackers, observe their techniques, and gather threat intelligence. What is this system called?","options":{"A":"Sandbox","B":"Honeypot","C":"Jump Server","D":"Proxy Server"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. A sandbox is an isolated testing environment to safely execute untrusted programs.","B":"Correct! A honeypot is a decoy server set up to attract attackers, allowing defenders to analyze their methods.","C":"Incorrect. A jump server is a secure gateway used to manage administrative devices in a segregated zone.","D":"Incorrect. A proxy server forwards client requests to other servers."}},{"id":"cct_146","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"During a Business Impact Analysis (BIA), an organization determines the absolute maximum amount of time that a critical business process can be down before the organization suffers permanent, unrecoverable damage. What is this metric called?","options":{"A":"RTO (Recovery Time Objective)","B":"MTD (Maximum Tolerable Downtime) / MAO (Maximum Acceptable Outage)","C":"RPO (Recovery Point Objective)","D":"SLA (Service Level Agreement)"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. RTO is the target recovery time set by management, which must be lower than or equal to MTD.","B":"Correct! MTD (Maximum Tolerable Downtime) represents the maximum threshold of downtime a business can withstand before going out of business.","C":"Incorrect. RPO is the maximum acceptable data loss in terms of time.","D":"Incorrect. SLA is a contract between service providers and clients."}},{"id":"cct_147","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"According to the NIST SP 800-61 Incident Response Lifecycle, which phase occurs immediately after the incident has been contained, eradicated, and recovered, focusing on improving future responses?","options":{"A":"Preparation","B":"Detection and Analysis","C":"Post-Incident Activity (Lessons Learned)","D":"Threat Hunting"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Preparation is the first phase, building defenses and training teams.","B":"Incorrect. Detection and analysis precedes containment.","C":"Correct! Post-Incident Activity (Lessons Learned) is the final NIST incident phase where teams evaluate their response and update playbooks.","D":"Incorrect. Threat hunting is a proactive operational task."}},{"id":"cct_148","domain":"Data Security","question":"In cryptography, what occurs when two completely different inputs (files or text) produce the exact same hash value output?","options":{"A":"Key Escrow","B":"Hash Collision","C":"Salting","D":"Key Stretching"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Key escrow holds decryption keys in backup storage.","B":"Correct! A hash collision occurs when two distinct inputs yield the exact same hash output.","C":"Incorrect. Salting is adding random data to passwords before hashing.","D":"Incorrect. Key stretching is running a hash function multiple times to slow down brute force attacks."}},{"id":"cct_149","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"An attacker registers the domain name www.g0ogle.com (using a zero instead of an 'o') hoping to catch users who mistype the legitimate URL, subsequently serving them malware. What is this attack called?","options":{"A":"DNS Spoofing","B":"Typosquatting (URL Hijacking)","C":"Phishing","D":"Session Hijacking"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. DNS spoofing redirects requests by poisoning resolution records.","B":"Correct! Typosquatting (URL Hijacking) registers domains with slight spelling variations of popular sites to trick users.","C":"Incorrect. Phishing is a general social engineering delivery method.","D":"Incorrect. Session hijacking steals active connection session IDs."}},{"id":"cct_150","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"To prevent financial fraud, a company requires that the person who creates a purchase order cannot be the same person who approves it. Which security principle is being enforced?","options":{"A":"Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","B":"Least Privilege","C":"Separation of Duties","D":"Job Rotation"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. MAC is an access model based on security levels and clearances.","B":"Incorrect. Least privilege gives users only the permissions necessary to complete their job functions.","C":"Correct! Separation of Duties ensures no single individual has total control over a critical transaction or process, preventing internal fraud.","D":"Incorrect. Job rotation periodically rotates employee responsibilities."}},{"id":"cct_151","domain":"Application Security and Cloud Computing","question":"Which HTTP response header can a web administrator implement to significantly reduce the risk of Cross-Site Scripting (XSS) attacks by explicitly declaring which dynamic resources are allowed to load?","options":{"A":"Strict-Transport-Security (HSTS)","B":"Content-Security-Policy (CSP)","C":"X-Frame-Options","D":"Cache-Control"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. HSTS enforces HTTPS connections on client browsers.","B":"Correct! The Content-Security-Policy (CSP) header declares which script and resource origins are trusted, blocking XSS payloads from executing.","C":"Incorrect. X-Frame-Options prevents clickjacking attacks.","D":"Incorrect. Cache-Control manages client caching parameters."}},{"id":"cct_152","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"Compared to traditional antivirus (AV) software that relies on known malware signatures, what is the primary advantage of an Endpoint Detection and Response (EDR) solution?","options":{"A":"EDR uses less CPU and RAM.","B":"EDR continuously monitors and records endpoint behavior to detect anomalous activities and zero-day threats.","C":"EDR automatically decrypts ransomware files.","D":"EDR is entirely free and open-source."},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. EDR usually uses more resources than basic signature matching because it records and evaluates system behaviors.","B":"Correct! EDR solutions monitor endpoint process, network, and file behaviors to spot unknown anomalies and zero-day threats.","C":"Incorrect. EDR does not automatically decrypt files encrypted by ransomware.","D":"Incorrect. Many EDR solutions are commercial, proprietary corporate platforms."}},{"id":"cct_153","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"When configuring IPsec for a VPN, which protocol provides data confidentiality (encryption) as well as authentication and integrity?","options":{"A":"Authentication Header (AH)","B":"Encapsulating Security Payload (ESP)","C":"Internet Key Exchange (IKE)","D":"Point-to-Point Tunneling Protocol (PPTP)"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Authentication Header (AH) provides authentication and integrity but does not encrypt data.","B":"Correct! Encapsulating Security Payload (ESP) provides bulk data confidentiality (encryption), as well as authentication and integrity checking.","C":"Incorrect. IKE is the key negotiation protocol.","D":"Incorrect. PPTP is an older, insecure VPN protocol."}},{"id":"cct_154","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"In a data center, what type of environmental control is essential to automatically suppress fires without damaging the electronic server equipment with water?","options":{"A":"Dry-pipe sprinkler systems","B":"Clean agent gas systems (e.g., FM-200, Novec 1230)","C":"Carbon monoxide detectors","D":"High-voltage HVAC systems"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Dry-pipe sprinkler systems use water, which damages servers.","B":"Correct! Clean agent gas systems (such as FM-200 or Novec 1230) extinguish fires by removing heat or oxygen without conducting electricity or leaving residue.","C":"Incorrect. Carbon monoxide detectors only sound alarms.","D":"Incorrect. HVAC systems manage airflow and cooling."}},{"id":"cct_155","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"A security analyst uses search engines, public social media profiles, government databases, and WHOIS records to gather intelligence about a target organization prior to a penetration test. What type of intelligence gathering is this?","options":{"A":"Social Engineering","B":"Open-Source Intelligence (OSINT)","C":"Active Footprinting","D":"Dumpster Diving"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Social engineering manipulates human behavior to extract information.","B":"Correct! Open-Source Intelligence (OSINT) is the collection and analysis of information gathered from public, open sources.","C":"Incorrect. Active footprinting interacts directly with target servers (e.g., port scanning).","D":"Incorrect. Dumpster diving searches physical waste bins."}},{"id":"cct_156","domain":"Wireless Device Security","question":"What is the primary security risk associated with \"jailbreaking\" (iOS) or \"rooting\" (Android) a mobile device?","options":{"A":"It permanently bricks the device's battery.","B":"It bypasses the operating system's built-in security controls and sandboxing, making the device highly vulnerable to malware.","C":"It encrypts all personal data making it unreadable.","D":"It forces the device to only connect to 3G networks."},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. It does not damage battery hardware.","B":"Correct! Jailbreaking/rooting disables the security sandbox, allowing any app to run with root privileges and expose the device to malware.","C":"Incorrect. It does not automatically encrypt device storage.","D":"Incorrect. It does not affect cellular band support."}},{"id":"cct_157","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"In the context of a Security Information and Event Management (SIEM) system, what occurs when an actual cyberattack takes place, but the SIEM fails to generate an alert?","options":{"A":"False Positive","B":"True Positive","C":"False Negative","D":"True Negative"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. A false positive triggers an alert for harmless activity.","B":"Incorrect. A true positive correctly triggers an alert during a real attack.","C":"Correct! A false negative occurs when an attack goes undetected and the system fails to raise an alert.","D":"Incorrect. A true negative occurs when there is no attack and no alert is triggered."}},{"id":"cct_158","domain":"Data Security","question":"When comparing Symmetric cryptography to Asymmetric cryptography, which of the following statements is TRUE?","options":{"A":"Symmetric cryptography is generally much faster and is best suited for encrypting large amounts of bulk data.","B":"Asymmetric cryptography uses a single shared key for both encryption and decryption.","C":"Symmetric cryptography natively provides non-repudiation.","D":"Asymmetric cryptography is significantly faster than symmetric cryptography."},"correct_option":"A","explanations":{"A":"Correct! Symmetric algorithms (like AES) are highly optimized and faster, making them ideal for bulk data encryption.","B":"Incorrect. Asymmetric cryptography uses a public-private key pair.","C":"Incorrect. Symmetric cryptography does not natively provide non-repudiation because both parties share the exact same key.","D":"Incorrect. Asymmetric cryptography is significantly slower."}},{"id":"cct_159","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"A corporate VPN is configured so that traffic destined for the internal corporate network travels through the encrypted VPN tunnel, but standard internet browsing traffic goes directly out the user's local ISP. What is this configuration called?","options":{"A":"Full Tunneling","B":"Split Tunneling","C":"Port Forwarding","D":"Proxy Chaining"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Full tunneling routes all traffic through the VPN.","B":"Correct! Split tunneling divides VPN client traffic: corporate-destined packets go through the VPN, and standard web traffic goes directly through the local ISP.","C":"Incorrect. Port forwarding routes external connections to an internal IP/port.","D":"Incorrect. Proxy chaining routes traffic through multiple proxies."}},{"id":"cct_160","domain":"Information Security Threats and Attacks","question":"Under the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which principle mandates that organizations must delete a user's personal data upon their explicit request, provided there is no compelling legitimate or legal reason to keep it?","options":{"A":"Right to be Informed","B":"Data Portability","C":"Right to Erasure (Right to be Forgotten)","D":"Privacy by Design"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Right to be Informed requires providing transparency about how data is used.","B":"Incorrect. Data portability allows users to request transfer of their data to another provider.","C":"Correct! Under GDPR, the Right to Erasure (Right to be Forgotten) allows individuals to request the deletion of their personal data.","D":"Incorrect. Privacy by Design means incorporating privacy controls during system engineering."}},{"id":"cct_161","domain":"Network Security Fundamentals","question":"A user reports they cannot access a specific website by entering the domain name (e.g., www.example.com) in their browser, but the page loads perfectly if they enter the server's IP address. What is the most likely problem?","options":{"A":"The DHCP server is down.","B":"DNS resolution failure.","C":"A routing loop at the gateway.","D":"The local ARP table is corrupted."},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. If DHCP were down, the machine would not have an IP address and could not access the site via the IP address either.","B":"Correct! A domain name works by querying a DNS server to resolve it to an IP. If name resolution fails but the IP address works directly, the DNS server settings or resolution path is broken.","C":"Incorrect. A routing loop would block all traffic to the IP address as well.","D":"Incorrect. A corrupted ARP table would block local subnet IP communications, preventing access by IP address."}},{"id":"cct_162","domain":"Network Security Fundamentals","question":"A network administrator runs the tracert (or traceroute) command and observes that packets bounce continuously between two specific routers until the Time to Live (TTL) expires and the packet is dropped. What network issue does this indicate?","options":{"A":"Routing Loop.","B":"Broadcast Storm.","C":"Port blocking by the Firewall.","D":"IPsec encapsulation failure."},"correct_option":"A","explanations":{"A":"Correct! A routing loop occurs when packets bounce between routers indefinitely because of misconfigured routing tables, eventually getting dropped when the Time to Live (TTL) reaches zero.","B":"Incorrect. A broadcast storm is caused by Layer 2 switching loops that flood the network with broadcasts.","C":"Incorrect. Firewalls blocking traffic drop packets immediately; they do not cause them to bounce between routers.","D":"Incorrect. IPsec failure causes packet decryption or negotiation errors, not routing bounces."}},{"id":"cct_163","domain":"Network Security Fundamentals","question":"Two devices connected to the same switch experience extremely slow communication and packet loss. Upon checking the interfaces, one port is configured for Full-Duplex and the other for Half-Duplex. What is the result of this configuration?","options":{"A":"Failed Network Address Translation (NAT).","B":"VLAN negotiation failure.","C":"Duplex mismatch causing late collisions.","D":"Spanning Tree Protocol (STP) blocking."},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. NAT translations translate IP addresses and operate at Layer 3/4, unaffected by Layer 1 duplex states.","B":"Incorrect. VLANs segment traffic at Layer 2 and are independent of physical link duplex mismatch issues.","C":"Correct! A duplex mismatch (one end full-duplex, the other half-duplex) causes the half-duplex side to experience late collisions and packet drop issues under load.","D":"Incorrect. STP prevents switching loops and does not disable ports purely due to a duplex mismatch."}},{"id":"cct_164","domain":"Network Security Fundamentals","question":"A technician checks the network configuration of a Windows machine using the ipconfig /all command and notices the assigned IPv4 address is 169.254.15.22. What does this IP address indicate?","options":{"A":"The machine is successfully connected to the WAN.","B":"It is an APIPA address, indicating the machine could not contact the DHCP server.","C":"It is a loopback address for hardware testing.","D":"The machine was isolated by Network Access Control (NAC)."},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. APIPA addresses are self-assigned link-local addresses that do not allow routing to the WAN/internet.","B":"Correct! The 169.254.0.0/16 address range is designated for Automatic Private IP Addressing (APIPA), indicating the client interface configured for DHCP failed to obtain an address from a DHCP server.","C":"Incorrect. The loopback IPv4 address range is 127.0.0.0/8 (typically 127.0.0.1).","D":"Incorrect. NAC isolation assigns a quarantine VLAN, which still uses a routable IP from a quarantine DHCP server, not an APIPA address."}},{"id":"cct_165","domain":"Network Security Fundamentals","question":"If a fiber optic network cable is accidentally cut by heavy machinery outside the data center, interrupting communication, which OSI model layer is failing?","options":{"A":"Layer 1 (Physical)","B":"Layer 2 (Data Link)","C":"Layer 3 (Network)","D":"Layer 4 (Transport)"},"correct_option":"A","explanations":{"A":"Correct! Physical cables, connectors, and light signals operate at Layer 1 (Physical) of the OSI model.","B":"Incorrect. Layer 2 (Data Link) deals with frames and hardware addresses (MAC).","C":"Incorrect. Layer 3 (Network) handles logical routing and IP addresses.","D":"Incorrect. Layer 4 (Transport) manages host-to-host transport protocols (TCP/UDP)."}},{"id":"cct_166","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"In a Windows infrastructure, a SOC analyst is reviewing the Event Viewer for successful logons to a critical server. Which Event ID in the Security log should they filter for?","options":{"A":"Event ID 4624","B":"Event ID 4625","C":"Event ID 4720","D":"Event ID 1102"},"correct_option":"A","explanations":{"A":"Correct! Event ID 4624 in the Windows Security Log indicates a successful user logon.","B":"Incorrect. Event ID 4625 indicates a failed user logon attempt.","C":"Incorrect. Event ID 4720 logs the creation of a new user account.","D":"Incorrect. Event ID 1102 logs when the Security audit log is cleared."}},{"id":"cct_167","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"A Linux system administrator suspects an attacker is attempting SSH brute-force attacks against an Ubuntu server. Which log file should they primarily check to find failed login attempts?","options":{"A":"/var/log/syslog","B":"/var/log/messages","C":"/var/log/auth.log","D":"/var/log/dmesg"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. /var/log/syslog contains generic system logs but isn't the primary specialized auth log on Debian/Ubuntu systems.","B":"Incorrect. /var/log/messages is used on RedHat/CentOS systems for general logs, but Ubuntu utilizes auth.log for sshd logs.","C":"Correct! On Debian-based systems like Ubuntu, authentication and authorization events (such as SSH logins and sudo attempts) are logged to /var/log/auth.log.","D":"Incorrect. /var/log/dmesg contains kernel ring buffer and driver boot messages."}},{"id":"cct_168","domain":"Network Security Controls","question":"When analyzing perimeter firewall logs, an analyst notices a rule is configured to apply the \"Drop\" action to certain packets instead of \"Reject\". What is the main difference between these two actions from the firewall's perspective?","options":{"A":"\"Drop\" saves the packet for future analysis; \"Reject\" deletes it immediately.","B":"\"Drop\" silently discards the packet without notifying the sender; \"Reject\" sends an ICMP error message back to the sender.","C":"\"Drop\" applies only to UDP traffic; \"Reject\" applies only to TCP traffic.","D":"\"Drop\" is an IDS action; \"Reject\" is an IPS action."},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Neither action saves the packet contents for future analysis (both discard it).","B":"Correct! A \"Drop\" rule discards packets silently, making the sender wait until a timeout occurs. A \"Reject\" rule discards the packet and explicitly replies with a TCP RST or an ICMP port/destination unreachable message.","C":"Incorrect. Both Drop and Reject can be applied to any IP packet regardless of transport protocol (TCP or UDP).","D":"Incorrect. Drop and Reject are standard firewall filtering actions, not unique to IDS or IPS systems."}},{"id":"cct_169","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"What is the primary purpose of enabling and configuring NTP (Network Time Protocol) on all servers and network devices before forwarding their logs to a centralized SIEM server?","options":{"A":"To encrypt the log content in transit.","B":"To compress log files to save storage.","C":"To ensure time synchronization to allow accurate event correlation across the network.","D":"To assign dynamic IP addresses to SIEM agents."},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. NTP does not encrypt log data in transit.","B":"Incorrect. NTP does not perform log compression or storage reduction.","C":"Correct! Accurate time synchronization across devices using NTP (Network Time Protocol) is vital for correlating events across multiple server logs in a SIEM.","D":"Incorrect. DHCP assigns dynamic IP addresses, not NTP."}},{"id":"cct_170","domain":"Network Monitoring and Analysis","question":"Which log format is an industry standard widely used by web servers (like Apache and Nginx) to log HTTP requests, containing fields such as client IP, timestamp, HTTP method, and status code?","options":{"A":"Common Log Format (CLF)","B":"Windows Event Trace (ETW)","C":"JSON Web Token (JWT)","D":"PCAP"},"correct_option":"A","explanations":{"A":"Correct! Common Log Format (CLF) is the industry-standard log format used by Apache, Nginx, and other web servers, containing fields such as client IP, timestamp, HTTP method, requested resource, and status code.","B":"Incorrect. Windows Event Trace (ETW) is a Windows kernel-level software event tracing framework used for system diagnostics, not a web server HTTP request log standard.","C":"Incorrect. JSON Web Token (JWT) is a client-side authentication and authorization token standard, not a log format.","D":"Incorrect. PCAP is a binary packet capture format used by tools like Wireshark to record raw network traffic, not a structured web server request log."}},{"id":"cct_171","domain":"Data Security","question":"An organization reviews all its information repositories and tags documents as \"Public,\" \"Internal Use,\" \"Confidential,\" and \"Restricted.\" What is this fundamental data security process called?","options":{"A":"Data Encryption","B":"Data Classification","C":"Tokenization","D":"Data Masking"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Data encryption scrambles data to ensure confidentiality.","B":"Correct! Data classification is the process of organizing data into categories based on sensitivity and security levels to apply appropriate controls.","C":"Incorrect. Tokenization replaces sensitive data with non-sensitive identifiers.","D":"Incorrect. Data masking replaces characters of data with placeholders."}},{"id":"cct_172","domain":"Data Security","question":"To comply with PCI-DSS regulations, a payment gateway takes credit card numbers (PANs) and replaces them with random alphanumeric strings that have no intrinsic mathematical value. Which technique is being used?","options":{"A":"Hashing","B":"Asymmetric Encryption","C":"Salting","D":"Tokenization"},"correct_option":"D","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Hashing is a one-way mathematical function that yields a fixed-size signature.","B":"Incorrect. Asymmetric encryption uses public/private keys to protect data.","C":"Incorrect. Salting is adding random characters to a password input before hashing.","D":"Correct! Tokenization replaces critical sensitive data (like credit card numbers) with a non-sensitive equivalent (a token) that has no mathematical relationship to the original data."}},{"id":"cct_173","domain":"Data Security","question":"A server hosting highly sensitive corporate databases has reached the end of its lifecycle. What is the most secure physical data destruction method before disposing of the magnetic hard drives?","options":{"A":"Quick formatting via the operating system.","B":"Deleting partitions using the command line.","C":"Degaussing followed by physical destruction (shredding).","D":"Zero-fill overwriting in a single pass."},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Quick formatting only clears the file system index, leaving raw database data fully recoverable.","B":"Incorrect. Deleting partitions does not erase the sectors containing data.","C":"Correct! Degaussing uses a powerful magnetic field to neutralize the magnetic domains on the disk platters, making the data completely unrecoverable, followed by shredding to ensure total physical destruction.","D":"Incorrect. Single-pass zero filling can still leave residual trace signatures on older magnetic media."}},{"id":"cct_174","domain":"Data Security","question":"What is the primary difference between Data Masking and Data Encryption?","options":{"A":"Masking is used for data in transit; encryption for data at rest.","B":"Masking is generally irreversible and often used in dev/test databases; encryption uses a key so original information can be recovered by authorized users.","C":"Masking requires a Public Key Infrastructure (PKI); encryption does not.","D":"Masking only applies to emails; encryption applies to databases."},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Encryption is used for both in-transit and at-rest data, while masking is mostly used for database scrubbing.","B":"Correct! Data masking replaces characters permanently to protect sensitive details during application development or testing. Data encryption is reversible via a decryption key.","C":"Incorrect. Masking does not use or require PKI.","D":"Incorrect. Both techniques apply to databases and various files."}},{"id":"cct_175","domain":"Application Security and Cloud Computing","question":"As part of data security in development environments, a security team implements controls to ensure that secrets (like API keys, database passwords, and tokens) are not accidentally committed to source code repositories like GitHub. Which security practice does this belong to?","options":{"A":"Secrets Management","B":"Data Loss Prevention (DLP)","C":"Full Disk Encryption (FDE)","D":"Steganography"},"correct_option":"A","explanations":{"A":"Correct! Secrets management tools and practices control access to credentials, API keys, and tokens, including pre-commit scanning to prevent them from leaking into version control repositories.","B":"Incorrect. DLP blocks sensitive documents from leaving the network perimeter but does not focus specifically on developer source code credentials.","C":"Incorrect. Full disk encryption protects physical drives against theft.","D":"Incorrect. Steganography is hiding data inside image or audio files."}},{"id":"cct_176","domain":"Identification, Authentication and Authorization","question":"In a Kerberos authentication environment, which component issues Ticket-Granting Tickets (TGTs) after verifying a user's credentials during the initial authentication step?","options":{"A":"Ticket-Granting Server (TGS)","B":"Authentication Server (AS)","C":"Key Distribution Center Client (KDC Client)","D":"Service Principal (SP)"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. The TGS (Ticket-Granting Server) issues service tickets after the user presents a valid TGT — it does not issue the TGT itself.","B":"Correct! The Authentication Server (AS), part of the Key Distribution Center (KDC), verifies user credentials and issues the initial Ticket-Granting Ticket (TGT).","C":"Incorrect. The KDC Client is the end-user workstation that initiates authentication requests; it does not issue tickets.","D":"Incorrect. A Service Principal is the application or service being accessed; it consumes service tickets but does not issue them."}},{"id":"cct_177","domain":"Identification, Authentication and Authorization","question":"Which federated identity standard uses XML-based security tokens to exchange authentication and authorization data between an Identity Provider (IdP) and a Service Provider (SP), and is commonly used for enterprise Single Sign-On (SSO)?","options":{"A":"OAuth 2.0","B":"OpenID Connect","C":"SAML 2.0","D":"RADIUS"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. OAuth 2.0 is an authorization delegation framework primarily used for granting third-party access to resources without sharing credentials; it uses JSON tokens, not XML.","B":"Incorrect. OpenID Connect is an identity layer built on top of OAuth 2.0 that uses JWT tokens for authentication, not XML assertions.","C":"Correct! SAML 2.0 (Security Assertion Markup Language) uses XML-based security assertions to pass authentication and authorization information between an Identity Provider and Service Provider, enabling enterprise SSO.","D":"Incorrect. RADIUS is a AAA protocol for network access control and does not use XML assertions for federated identity."}},{"id":"cct_178","domain":"Identification, Authentication and Authorization","question":"A directory service is configured to allow users to query and modify information about network resources. Which protocol, operating over TCP port 389, is the industry standard for accessing and maintaining distributed directory information services?","options":{"A":"RADIUS","B":"TACACS+","C":"LDAP","D":"Kerberos"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. RADIUS (port 1812/UDP) handles centralized AAA for network access but is not a directory information protocol.","B":"Incorrect. TACACS+ provides centralized AAA (especially for network device administration) but is not a directory access protocol.","C":"Correct! LDAP (Lightweight Directory Access Protocol) on TCP port 389 is the standard application protocol for querying and updating directory services like Microsoft Active Directory.","D":"Incorrect. Kerberos is a network authentication protocol using tickets; it relies on a KDC but is not a general-purpose directory access protocol."}},{"id":"cct_179","domain":"Identification, Authentication and Authorization","question":"Which type of access control allows the data owner or resource owner to control access to their own files and resources by assigning permissions directly to individual users or groups?","options":{"A":"Mandatory Access Control (MAC)","B":"Role-Based Access Control (RBAC)","C":"Discretionary Access Control (DAC)","D":"Rule-Based Access Control (RuBAC)"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. MAC enforces access based on security clearance labels set by a central authority — the data owner cannot override these decisions.","B":"Incorrect. RBAC assigns permissions based on organizational roles, not by the owner's direct decision.","C":"Correct! Discretionary Access Control (DAC) gives the resource owner the discretion to decide who can access their resource, typically implemented through access control lists (ACLs) they control.","D":"Incorrect. Rule-Based Access Control uses system-defined rules (such as firewall ACL rules) to control access, not the resource owner's choice."}},{"id":"cct_180","domain":"Identification, Authentication and Authorization","question":"An attacker gains access to an authentication token and reuses it at a later time to authenticate as the legitimate user. Which type of attack is this?","options":{"A":"Pass-the-Hash","B":"Credential Stuffing","C":"Replay Attack","D":"Brute Force Attack"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Pass-the-Hash specifically captures and reuses NTLM password hashes to authenticate without knowing the plaintext password — it is a specific form targeting Windows authentication.","B":"Incorrect. Credential stuffing uses leaked username/password lists from data breaches to attempt logins across multiple services.","C":"Correct! A replay attack captures a valid authentication token or message and retransmits it later to impersonate the legitimate user. Countermeasures include timestamps and nonces (one-time values).","D":"Incorrect. A brute force attack systematically guesses credentials by trying all possible combinations."}},{"id":"cct_181","domain":"IoT and OT Security","question":"In an industrial control system (ICS), what is the Purdue Reference Model (also known as the Purdue Enterprise Reference Architecture)?","options":{"A":"A cryptographic standard for securing SCADA communications","B":"A hierarchical model that defines network segmentation zones separating enterprise IT, supervisory, and field device levels in ICS environments","C":"A wireless communication protocol used by IoT sensors","D":"A regulatory compliance framework for power utilities"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. The Purdue Model is an architectural framework, not a cryptographic standard.","B":"Correct! The Purdue Model organizes ICS/OT networks into hierarchical levels (Levels 0–5) defining zones from physical field devices (Level 0) up through SCADA/HMI systems to enterprise IT networks, providing a security segmentation blueprint.","C":"Incorrect. The Purdue Model is not a wireless protocol; it is a network architecture reference model.","D":"Incorrect. While utilities use the Purdue Model, it is a general ICS architecture framework, not a regulatory compliance standard."}},{"id":"cct_182","domain":"IoT and OT Security","question":"Which key security challenge differentiates Operational Technology (OT) systems from traditional IT systems, and significantly complicates patching and vulnerability management?","options":{"A":"OT systems exclusively use IPv6 addressing","B":"OT systems prioritize Availability over Confidentiality and cannot tolerate downtime for patching","C":"OT systems run only on open-source software","D":"OT systems do not generate any log data"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. OT systems commonly use older legacy protocols and may use various IP versions, but IPv6 exclusivity is not the differentiating security challenge.","B":"Correct! OT/ICS environments prioritize Availability (the A in CIA) above all else because downtime in industrial processes can have physical, safety, and financial consequences. This makes regular patching extremely difficult as systems often cannot be taken offline.","C":"Incorrect. Many OT systems run proprietary vendor software, not open-source software.","D":"Incorrect. While OT logging may be limited compared to IT systems, OT systems do generate operational and event log data."}},{"id":"cct_183","domain":"IoT and OT Security","question":"A city's water treatment facility uses a SCADA system connected to the corporate IT network without proper segmentation. An attacker on the IT network compromises a workstation and pivots to the SCADA system. Which security control would have BEST prevented this lateral movement?","options":{"A":"Installing antivirus on all SCADA workstations","B":"Network segmentation with a DMZ or air-gap between IT and OT networks","C":"Enabling Windows Firewall on SCADA servers","D":"Deploying a honeypot in the IT network"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Antivirus helps but does not prevent lateral movement from the IT network if there is no network boundary between IT and OT.","B":"Correct! Network segmentation — using firewalls, DMZs, or full air-gapping — creates a security boundary that prevents an attacker who has compromised an IT system from directly pivoting to OT/SCADA systems.","C":"Incorrect. Windows Firewall provides host-based filtering but does not segment entire network zones; an attacker with full network access could bypass it.","D":"Incorrect. A honeypot is a detection tool, not a prevention control for lateral movement between network zones."}},{"id":"cct_184","domain":"IoT and OT Security","question":"What is a 'shadow IT' risk in the context of IoT device deployments in corporate environments?","options":{"A":"IoT devices generating excessive CPU shadow threads","B":"Employees connecting unauthorized personal IoT devices to corporate networks without IT department knowledge or approval","C":"Attackers creating shadow copies of IoT firmware to analyze it offline","D":"IoT devices operating in a hidden VLAN invisible to network monitors"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Shadow IT has nothing to do with CPU threading or processing.","B":"Correct! Shadow IT in IoT refers to employees or business units deploying personal smart devices (smart TVs, IP cameras, personal assistants) onto corporate networks without going through the IT/security approval process, bypassing security policies.","C":"Incorrect. Firmware analysis is a security research technique, not a shadow IT risk.","D":"Incorrect. While unauthorized devices might end up on VLANs, 'shadow IT' specifically refers to unsanctioned technology deployments."}},{"id":"cct_185","domain":"IoT and OT Security","question":"Which communication protocol is widely used by IoT devices for lightweight publish/subscribe messaging, particularly in environments with constrained bandwidth or unreliable networks?","options":{"A":"HTTPS","B":"MQTT (Message Queuing Telemetry Transport)","C":"FTP","D":"SMB (Server Message Block)"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. HTTPS is a full HTTP protocol with TLS encryption — too heavyweight for many resource-constrained IoT sensors.","B":"Correct! MQTT is a lightweight, publish/subscribe protocol designed for IoT environments with limited bandwidth and unreliable connections, operating over TCP port 1883 (or 8883 for TLS).","C":"Incorrect. FTP is a file transfer protocol, not designed for real-time IoT telemetry messaging.","D":"Incorrect. SMB is a network file-sharing protocol for Windows environments, not for IoT sensor data messaging."}},{"id":"cct_186","domain":"Computer Forensics","question":"During a digital forensic investigation, what is the correct order of volatility for evidence collection, starting from MOST volatile to LEAST volatile?","options":{"A":"Hard disk → RAM → CPU registers → Network connections","B":"CPU registers → RAM → Network connections → Hard disk","C":"Network connections → CPU registers → RAM → Hard disk","D":"RAM → Hard disk → CPU registers → Network connections"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Hard disk data is the least volatile (non-volatile storage), so collecting it first would result in losing more critical volatile data.","B":"Correct! RFC 3227 establishes the order of volatility: CPU registers/cache (fastest to change) → RAM → Network connections/routing tables → Temporary files → Hard disk → Removable media. Always collect the most volatile first.","C":"Incorrect. While network connections are very volatile, CPU registers and cache are even more so.","D":"Incorrect. Hard disk data is persistent non-volatile storage and should be collected after volatile memory sources."}},{"id":"cct_187","domain":"Computer Forensics","question":"A forensic investigator uses the 'file carving' technique on a seized hard drive image. What is file carving?","options":{"A":"Physically cutting open a hard drive to extract platters for direct data reading","B":"Recovering files from unallocated disk space based on file signatures (headers/footers), without relying on file system metadata","C":"Carving out partitions from a disk image using the partition table","D":"Encrypting a forensic image before sending it to the lab"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Physically accessing disk platters is a specialized hardware recovery technique for severely damaged drives, not file carving.","B":"Correct! File carving searches raw disk sectors for known file type signatures (e.g., JPEG starts with FF D8 FF) to reconstruct files from unallocated space even when the file system directory entries have been deleted.","C":"Incorrect. Partition extraction uses the partition table — it is not the same as file carving, which works at the raw byte level bypassing the file system.","D":"Incorrect. Encrypting an image is a chain-of-custody data protection step, not a recovery technique."}},{"id":"cct_188","domain":"Computer Forensics","question":"An investigator discovers that a suspect used 'anti-forensics' techniques before surrendering their device. Which of the following is an example of an anti-forensics technique?","options":{"A":"Enabling full-disk encryption (BitLocker) with a key stored only in the user's memory","B":"Running antivirus software regularly","C":"Enabling Windows Firewall","D":"Using a password manager"},"correct_option":"A","explanations":{"A":"Correct! Enabling full-disk encryption with a key known only to the suspect is an anti-forensics technique — it renders the encrypted data unreadable to investigators who do not have the decryption key.","B":"Incorrect. Regular antivirus is a defensive security practice, not an anti-forensics technique.","C":"Incorrect. Enabling the Windows Firewall is a security hardening measure, not evidence destruction.","D":"Incorrect. Password managers protect credential security but do not destroy or hide forensic evidence."}},{"id":"cct_189","domain":"Computer Forensics","question":"In Windows forensics, which artifact records the last time a user opened a specific file or application, and is stored in the Windows Registry under HKEY_CURRENT_USER?","options":{"A":"Prefetch files","B":"Shellbags","C":"RecentDocs / Recent Items","D":"Volume Shadow Copy"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Prefetch files (.pf) in C:\\Windows\\Prefetch record applications that have been executed, showing execution count and last run time — not opened documents.","B":"Incorrect. Shellbags store folder view preferences and accessed folder paths, not recently opened files.","C":"Correct! The RecentDocs registry key (HKCU\\Software\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\Explorer\\RecentDocs) tracks recently opened files and documents, providing forensic evidence of user activity.","D":"Incorrect. Volume Shadow Copies are point-in-time disk snapshots used for backup and recovery, not a user activity tracking artifact."}},{"id":"cct_190","domain":"Computer Forensics","question":"A forensic examiner must testify in court about their findings. Which principle ensures that the examiner's process and tools are reliable, standardized, and that the evidence is reproducible by another qualified examiner?","options":{"A":"Hearsay rule","B":"Locard's Exchange Principle","C":"Scientific Working Group for Digital Evidence (SWGDE) standards","D":"Statute of limitations"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. The hearsay rule is a legal evidence admissibility principle about out-of-court statements, not about forensic methodology.","B":"Incorrect. Locard's Exchange Principle (every contact leaves a trace) is a foundational forensic concept but not the standard ensuring reproducibility.","C":"Correct! SWGDE standards establish best practices for digital forensic examinations, ensuring that procedures are validated, documented, and reproducible — critical requirements for evidence admissibility in court.","D":"Incorrect. The statute of limitations defines the time window in which legal proceedings can be initiated, not forensic methodology standards."}},{"id":"cct_191","domain":"Computer Forensics","question":"Which Windows command-line tool can be used to schedule tasks, and is commonly abused by malware for persistence? A forensic investigator should examine which system artifact to detect this abuse?","options":{"A":"Task Scheduler — examine C:\\Windows\\System32\\Tasks\\ directory","B":"Windows Firewall — examine inbound rules","C":"Group Policy — examine GPO SYSVOL","D":"Registry Editor — examine HKLM\\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services"},"correct_option":"A","explanations":{"A":"Correct! Attackers commonly use the Windows Task Scheduler (schtasks.exe) to create persistent backdoor executions. Forensic examiners look in C:\\Windows\\System32\\Tasks\\ and HKLM\\SOFTWARE\\Microsoft\\Windows NT\\CurrentVersion\\Schedule\\TaskCache for malicious scheduled tasks.","B":"Incorrect. Examining firewall rules reveals allowed ports/applications but does not show scheduled task persistence mechanisms.","C":"Incorrect. Group Policy SYSVOL stores domain-level policies, not local scheduled tasks used for malware persistence.","D":"Incorrect. HKLM\\SYSTEM\\CurrentControlSet\\Services stores Windows services, which is a different persistence mechanism from scheduled tasks."}},{"id":"cct_192","domain":"Business Continuity and Disaster Recovery","question":"During BC/DR planning, the Recovery Time Objective (RTO) and Maximum Tolerable Downtime (MTD) have a specific mandatory relationship. Which of the following correctly describes this relationship?","options":{"A":"MTD must always be shorter than RTO","B":"RTO must always be shorter than or equal to MTD","C":"RTO and MTD are the same metric with different names","D":"MTD is only used in IT systems; RTO applies to business processes"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. If MTD were shorter than RTO, the business would fail before the recovery target is reached — this is the wrong relationship.","B":"Correct! RTO (the target time to restore a system) must be less than or equal to MTD (the absolute maximum time the business can survive without the system). If RTO exceeds MTD, the business cannot survive the outage even after technically recovering.","C":"Incorrect. RTO is the target recovery time set by the IT/management team; MTD is the absolute maximum threshold the business can survive. They measure different things.","D":"Incorrect. Both MTD and RTO apply to any critical business function or IT system. MTD is not limited to IT."}},{"id":"cct_193","domain":"Business Continuity and Disaster Recovery","question":"An organization's DR plan specifies that critical databases must be restored to no more than 4 hours before the disaster occurred. Which BC/DR metric is being defined?","options":{"A":"RTO (Recovery Time Objective)","B":"MTD (Maximum Tolerable Downtime)","C":"RPO (Recovery Point Objective)","D":"MTBF (Mean Time Between Failures)"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. RTO defines how quickly the system must be back online — a time-to-restore metric, not a data-loss tolerance metric.","B":"Incorrect. MTD is the maximum downtime the business can survive before permanent damage, not the data recency requirement.","C":"Correct! RPO (Recovery Point Objective) defines the maximum acceptable data loss expressed in time — in this case 4 hours, meaning the restored data can be at most 4 hours old.","D":"Incorrect. MTBF is a reliability metric measuring average time between hardware or system failures, not a data recovery objective."}},{"id":"cct_194","domain":"Business Continuity and Disaster Recovery","question":"Which type of disaster recovery test fully activates the alternate recovery site, transfers production workloads to it, and tests the entire failover process as it would occur in a real disaster — posing the highest risk and highest cost?","options":{"A":"Tabletop exercise","B":"Parallel test","C":"Full-interruption test","D":"Structured walk-through"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. A tabletop exercise is a paper-based discussion with no actual system activation.","B":"Incorrect. A parallel test activates the recovery site alongside production but does NOT cut over live traffic — both run simultaneously without interrupting production.","C":"Correct! A full-interruption test (also called a full-scale or cutover test) actually shuts down primary systems and fails over to the recovery site, fully testing the DR plan under real conditions. It carries the highest risk of service disruption but provides the most realistic validation.","D":"Incorrect. A structured walk-through (checklist review) has team members trace through the plan without activating any systems."}},{"id":"cct_195","domain":"Business Continuity and Disaster Recovery","question":"Which BCP/DRP concept defines the minimum level of services and resources required for an organization to continue its most critical business functions during a disaster, before full normal operations are restored?","options":{"A":"Business Impact Analysis (BIA)","B":"Minimum Business Continuity Objective (MBCO)","C":"Recovery Point Objective (RPO)","D":"Service Level Agreement (SLA)"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. BIA identifies critical functions and quantifies the impact of their disruption — it is an analysis input to BCP design, not the minimum operational level itself.","B":"Correct! The Minimum Business Continuity Objective (MBCO) defines the minimum level of services and capabilities that must be maintained or rapidly restored to protect the organization's viability during a disruption.","C":"Incorrect. RPO defines acceptable data loss in time units — it is a data recovery metric, not a service level threshold.","D":"Incorrect. An SLA is a contractual agreement on service performance between a provider and customer, not an internal continuity operational threshold."}},{"id":"cct_196","domain":"Business Continuity and Disaster Recovery","question":"A company maintains a warm site for disaster recovery. After a major data center fire, the operations team activates the warm site. Which statement BEST describes the expected recovery experience at a warm site?","options":{"A":"Operations are immediately restored in under 15 minutes since the site is pre-configured and data is real-time synchronized","B":"Hardware is pre-installed and networking is configured, but data must be restored from recent backups before going live","C":"Only empty floor space and power are available, requiring full hardware deployment before recovery can begin","D":"A warm site is a mobile trailer with portable servers that travels to the disaster site"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Immediate recovery with real-time synchronization describes a hot site, not a warm site.","B":"Correct! A warm site has servers, networking equipment, and configurations pre-installed, but data is not continuously synchronized. Recovery requires restoring data from backups (tapes or cloud), taking hours to a few days.","C":"Incorrect. Empty floor space describes a cold site, not a warm site.","D":"Incorrect. A mobile site is a portable recovery facility (trailer or van), not the definition of a warm site."}},{"id":"cct_197","domain":"Risk Management","question":"In the risk management process, what is a 'threat'?","options":{"A":"A weakness in a system that can be exploited","B":"The potential cause of an unwanted incident that may result in harm to a system or organization","C":"The financial impact caused by a successful attack","D":"A documented policy violation by an employee"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. A weakness in a system that can be exploited is a vulnerability, not a threat.","B":"Correct! A threat is any potential cause of an unwanted incident — such as a natural disaster, malicious actor, or hardware failure — that could cause harm. Risk = Threat × Vulnerability × Impact.","C":"Incorrect. The financial impact of a successful attack is the 'impact' component of risk, not the threat itself.","D":"Incorrect. A policy violation is an event or incident, not a threat in the risk management context."}},{"id":"cct_198","domain":"Risk Management","question":"An organization identifies that a specific server has an unpatched remote code execution vulnerability with no compensating controls. A threat actor is actively exploiting this vulnerability in the wild. Using the risk formula Risk = Threat × Vulnerability × Impact, which response is MOST appropriate?","options":{"A":"Risk acceptance — document it in the risk register and review next quarter","B":"Risk avoidance — immediately decommission the server","C":"Risk mitigation — immediately apply the patch or implement a compensating control","D":"Risk transference — purchase cyber insurance to cover potential losses"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Risk acceptance is appropriate for low-severity or low-likelihood risks where controls are too costly. An actively exploited critical vulnerability demands immediate action.","B":"Incorrect. Risk avoidance eliminates the activity entirely. While this would work, it may not be feasible if the server is critical to business operations.","C":"Correct! Risk mitigation reduces either the threat likelihood or the impact through controls. Patching eliminates the vulnerability component of the risk equation, which is the most direct and effective response when a patch is available.","D":"Incorrect. Risk transference (cyber insurance) covers financial consequences but does not reduce the likelihood of a compromise occurring."}},{"id":"cct_199","domain":"Risk Management","question":"Which risk assessment method assigns numerical monetary values to assets, threats, and vulnerabilities to calculate precise financial risk figures such as Annual Loss Expectancy (ALE)?","options":{"A":"Qualitative risk assessment","B":"Quantitative risk assessment","C":"Delphi technique","D":"Threat modeling"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Qualitative risk assessment uses subjective scales like High/Medium/Low — it does not produce monetary values.","B":"Correct! Quantitative risk assessment assigns specific monetary values to assets and uses formulas: SLE (Single Loss Expectancy) = Asset Value × Exposure Factor; ALE = SLE × ARO (Annualized Rate of Occurrence).","C":"Incorrect. The Delphi technique is a consensus-building method using expert opinion in rounds — typically used in qualitative assessments.","D":"Incorrect. Threat modeling identifies and prioritizes threats to a system but is a design-phase activity, not a risk quantification method."}},{"id":"cct_200","domain":"Risk Management","question":"A security manager creates a document listing all identified risks, their likelihood, potential impact, assigned owners, and treatment decisions. What is this document called?","options":{"A":"Business Impact Analysis (BIA)","B":"Security Policy","C":"Risk Register","D":"Incident Response Plan"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. A BIA identifies critical business functions and quantifies the impact of their disruption — it is an input to risk management but not the tracking document.","B":"Incorrect. A security policy defines rules and standards for protecting assets, not a risk tracking document.","C":"Correct! A risk register is the central repository documenting all identified risks, their probability, impact scores, status, treatment strategies, and responsible owners.","D":"Incorrect. An incident response plan defines the process for handling security incidents after they occur."}},{"id":"cct_201","domain":"Risk Management","question":"An organization calculates the Annual Loss Expectancy (ALE) for a server failure risk: Asset Value = $500,000, Exposure Factor = 40%, and the failure is expected to occur twice per year. What is the ALE?","options":{"A":"$100,000","B":"$200,000","C":"$400,000","D":"$500,000"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. $100,000 = $500,000 × 40% × 0.5 — this uses an incorrect ARO.","B":"Incorrect. $200,000 = $500,000 × 40% × 1 — this uses ARO=1 instead of ARO=2.","C":"Correct! SLE = Asset Value × EF = $500,000 × 0.40 = $200,000. ALE = SLE × ARO = $200,000 × 2 = $400,000.","D":"Incorrect. $500,000 is the total asset value, not the calculated ALE."}},{"id":"cct_202","domain":"Network Security Controls - Administrative","question":"A company policy requires that no single administrator can both approve and implement a firewall rule change. The change must be approved by one person and implemented by another. Which administrative security principle does this represent?","options":{"A":"Least Privilege","B":"Separation of Duties","C":"Need to Know","D":"Due Diligence"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Least privilege restricts user access to only what is required for their job — it does not inherently require two people for one task.","B":"Correct! Separation of Duties requires that critical or sensitive tasks be divided among multiple individuals to prevent fraud, errors, and abuse of privilege.","C":"Incorrect. Need to Know restricts access to information to only those who require it for their function.","D":"Incorrect. Due Diligence refers to the obligation to exercise care and investigate before taking action — not a task-splitting control."}},{"id":"cct_203","domain":"Network Security Controls - Administrative","question":"Which personnel security policy requires employees to periodically change their job functions or temporarily work in a different role, primarily to detect fraud and reduce single-person dependency on critical processes?","options":{"A":"Mandatory Vacation","B":"Background Checks","C":"Job Rotation","D":"Non-Disclosure Agreement (NDA)"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Mandatory Vacation forces employees to take leave, which helps detect fraud because another employee must cover the role and may discover irregularities — but it involves temporary absence, not role change.","B":"Incorrect. Background checks are pre-employment screening of history, not an ongoing role-change policy.","C":"Correct! Job Rotation periodically moves employees between roles, reducing the risk of one person having unchecked long-term control over a critical process, and exposing any fraud or errors.","D":"Incorrect. NDAs protect confidential information disclosure but do not involve changing job roles."}},{"id":"cct_204","domain":"Network Security Assessment","question":"A security team uses a vulnerability scanner that compares discovered software versions against a database of known CVEs without actually exploiting any weakness. What type of assessment is this?","options":{"A":"Active penetration test","B":"Non-intrusive (unauthenticated) vulnerability scan","C":"Red team exercise","D":"Physical security audit"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. A penetration test actively exploits vulnerabilities to gain access — it goes beyond detecting CVEs.","B":"Correct! A non-intrusive vulnerability scan compares observed software versions, open ports, and configurations against CVE databases to report potential weaknesses without exploiting them.","C":"Incorrect. A red team exercise is a comprehensive, adversarial simulation that mimics real attackers across multiple phases.","D":"Incorrect. A physical security audit assesses physical access controls, not network software vulnerabilities."}},{"id":"cct_205","domain":"Network Security Assessment","question":"During a penetration test, the tester successfully gains access to a server and then uses it to attack other systems in the internal network. What is this technique called?","options":{"A":"Privilege Escalation","B":"Pivoting (Lateral Movement)","C":"Persistence","D":"Exfiltration"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Privilege escalation increases the tester's access level on the compromised machine (e.g., from user to admin) — not moving to other systems.","B":"Correct! Pivoting (lateral movement) uses a compromised system as a launching point to attack other systems within the network that may not be directly reachable from the outside.","C":"Incorrect. Persistence involves establishing mechanisms to maintain access over time (backdoors, scheduled tasks) — not moving to new systems.","D":"Incorrect. Exfiltration is the unauthorized transfer of data out of the network."}},{"id":"cct_206","domain":"Network Security Assessment","question":"Which type of vulnerability assessment involves providing the scanner with valid credentials (username/password) to log into systems, allowing it to detect configuration weaknesses, missing patches, and local software vulnerabilities that cannot be seen from the outside?","options":{"A":"External vulnerability scan","B":"Credentialed (authenticated) vulnerability scan","C":"Passive network scan","D":"Fuzz testing"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. An external scan tests only what is visible from the internet, without logging into systems.","B":"Correct! A credentialed scan authenticates to the target systems and can access the OS, registry, installed software lists, and configuration files to find internal vulnerabilities that an external scan would miss.","C":"Incorrect. Passive scanning captures network traffic and infers information about hosts without actively probing them.","D":"Incorrect. Fuzz testing sends malformed or unexpected inputs to an application to find crashes and bugs, not a vulnerability scanner configuration type."}},{"id":"cct_207","domain":"Network Troubleshooting","question":"A user reports intermittent connectivity to a web server. A network engineer captures traffic with Wireshark and observes frequent TCP retransmissions and duplicate ACKs. What is the most likely cause?","options":{"A":"DNS resolution failure","B":"Packet loss causing TCP congestion control and retransmission","C":"ARP cache poisoning","D":"MTU mismatch causing IP fragmentation"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. DNS failures cause connection refusal or timeout errors before TCP is established — not retransmissions during an active session.","B":"Correct! TCP retransmissions and duplicate ACKs are signatures of packet loss on the network path. When packets are dropped, the receiver sends duplicate ACKs to signal the loss, triggering the sender to retransmit.","C":"Incorrect. ARP poisoning redirects traffic to an attacker but typically results in man-in-the-middle capture, not TCP retransmissions.","D":"Incorrect. MTU mismatch causes IP fragmentation or ICMP 'Fragmentation Needed' messages, not TCP retransmissions and duplicate ACKs."}},{"id":"cct_208","domain":"Network Traffic Monitoring","question":"An analyst notices that a workstation is sending thousands of DNS requests per minute with very long, randomly generated subdomains to an external server. What type of malicious activity does this pattern indicate?","options":{"A":"DNS Amplification DDoS Attack","B":"DNS Tunneling (data exfiltration via DNS)","C":"ARP Spoofing","D":"SQL Injection"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. DNS amplification uses DNS servers to reflect and amplify traffic toward a victim — it comes from external sources, not internal workstations sending queries.","B":"Correct! DNS tunneling encodes data within DNS query subdomains to exfiltrate information through DNS traffic (which is often not filtered). High volumes of random long subdomain queries are the key indicator.","C":"Incorrect. ARP spoofing sends false ARP replies within the LAN — it does not appear as DNS query traffic.","D":"Incorrect. SQL injection targets database inputs within web application traffic, not DNS queries."}},{"id":"cct_209","domain":"Network Logs Monitoring and Analysis","question":"A SOC analyst reviews firewall logs and notices that a single internal IP address has established outbound connections to 200 different external IP addresses on port 443 within one minute. Which type of behavior does this most likely indicate?","options":{"A":"Normal HTTPS web browsing","B":"Beaconing from malware communicating with a Command and Control (C2) infrastructure","C":"A software update server pushing patches","D":"A misconfigured load balancer"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Normal web browsing involves sequential connections to a small number of servers, not 200 different external IPs in one minute.","B":"Correct! Scanning hundreds of external IPs rapidly is a characteristic of malware performing C2 beaconing, DGA (Domain Generation Algorithm) callback attempts, or lateral scanning. This is a strong Indicator of Compromise (IoC).","C":"Incorrect. Patch servers push updates from a fixed set of known IPs, not hundreds of rotating external addresses.","D":"Incorrect. A load balancer distributes inbound traffic from clients to backend servers — it would not initiate hundreds of outbound connections from one internal IP."}},{"id":"cct_210","domain":"Cryptography","question":"Which cryptographic concept ensures that even if an attacker compromises a long-term private key in the future, previously recorded encrypted sessions cannot be decrypted?","options":{"A":"Public Key Infrastructure (PKI)","B":"Perfect Forward Secrecy (PFS)","C":"Key Escrow","D":"Certificate Pinning"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. PKI provides the framework for managing public key certificates — it does not inherently protect past session keys from future compromise.","B":"Correct! Perfect Forward Secrecy (PFS) uses ephemeral key exchange (like ECDHE) to generate unique session keys for each connection. Compromising the long-term private key cannot retroactively decrypt past sessions because each session key was independently generated and discarded.","C":"Incorrect. Key Escrow stores copies of encryption keys with a trusted third party — this increases the risk of past sessions being decrypted if the escrow is compromised.","D":"Incorrect. Certificate pinning prevents certificate substitution attacks by hardcoding expected certificates in applications, but does not protect past session keys."}},{"id":"cct_211","domain":"Cryptography","question":"In TLS 1.3, which key exchange mechanism is mandated to ensure Perfect Forward Secrecy for all connections?","options":{"A":"RSA key exchange","B":"Diffie-Hellman (static DH)","C":"Ephemeral Elliptic Curve Diffie-Hellman (ECDHE)","D":"Pre-Shared Key (PSK) only"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. RSA key exchange was removed in TLS 1.3 precisely because it does not provide forward secrecy — the server's private key could decrypt past sessions if compromised.","B":"Incorrect. Static DH uses fixed parameters that do not change per session, which does not achieve perfect forward secrecy.","C":"Correct! TLS 1.3 mandates ephemeral key exchange, specifically ECDHE, which generates a new temporary key pair per connection and deletes it after use, providing Perfect Forward Secrecy.","D":"Incorrect. Pre-Shared Keys are used for session resumption in TLS 1.3 but ECDHE is the primary mechanism for PFS in new connections."}},{"id":"cct_212","domain":"Application Security and Cloud Computing","question":"Which application security testing methodology tests the application from the outside with no knowledge of internal code or architecture, simulating an external attacker's perspective?","options":{"A":"Static Application Security Testing (SAST)","B":"White-box testing","C":"Dynamic Application Security Testing (DAST)","D":"Code review"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. SAST analyzes source code, bytecode, or binaries without executing the application — it is a white-box technique requiring code access.","B":"Incorrect. White-box testing provides full internal knowledge including source code, architecture, and documentation.","C":"Correct! DAST (Dynamic Application Security Testing) tests the running application from the outside with no source code access, sending malicious inputs and observing responses — simulating how a real attacker would probe the application.","D":"Incorrect. Code review manually examines source code for vulnerabilities — it requires full code access and is a white-box technique."}},{"id":"cct_213","domain":"Application Security and Cloud Computing","question":"The OWASP Top 10 is a standard reference document for web application security. Which vulnerability occurs when an application includes user-controlled input in a system command without proper sanitization, allowing attackers to execute arbitrary OS commands?","options":{"A":"SQL Injection","B":"Server-Side Request Forgery (SSRF)","C":"OS Command Injection","D":"XML External Entity (XXE)"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. SQL Injection inserts malicious SQL syntax into database queries — it targets the database layer, not the operating system.","B":"Incorrect. SSRF tricks the server into making HTTP requests to internal resources on behalf of the attacker.","C":"Correct! OS Command Injection occurs when unsanitized user input is passed to a system shell function (like exec(), system(), or popen()), allowing the attacker to append shell commands and execute arbitrary code on the server's OS.","D":"Incorrect. XXE exploits XML parsers that process external entity references, potentially allowing file disclosure or SSRF."}},{"id":"cct_214","domain":"Wireless Network Security","question":"A wireless security audit reveals that an access point is broadcasting its SSID but using WPA2-Enterprise instead of WPA2-Personal. What is the primary security advantage of WPA2-Enterprise?","options":{"A":"WPA2-Enterprise uses a stronger encryption algorithm than WPA2-Personal","B":"WPA2-Enterprise authenticates each user individually using 802.1X/RADIUS, eliminating the shared pre-shared key (PSK)","C":"WPA2-Enterprise requires no password, making it easier for users to connect","D":"WPA2-Enterprise is immune to the KRACK vulnerability"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Both WPA2-Personal and WPA2-Enterprise use the same AES-CCMP encryption — the difference is in authentication, not encryption strength.","B":"Correct! WPA2-Enterprise uses 802.1X with a RADIUS server to authenticate each user individually with unique credentials (certificates or username/password). This eliminates the shared PSK problem where one compromised credential exposes the entire network.","C":"Incorrect. WPA2-Enterprise requires stronger authentication (digital certificates or credentials) — it is harder to connect, not easier.","D":"Incorrect. KRACK (Key Reinstallation Attacks) affected both WPA2-Personal and WPA2-Enterprise implementations."}},{"id":"cct_215","domain":"Mobile Device Security","question":"Which mobile threat specifically targets the SIM card by convincing a mobile carrier to transfer the victim's phone number to a SIM card controlled by the attacker, allowing them to intercept SMS-based two-factor authentication codes?","options":{"A":"Bluejacking","B":"SIM Swapping (SIM Hijacking)","C":"IMSI Catching","D":"Smishing"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Bluejacking sends unsolicited messages to nearby Bluetooth devices — it does not involve phone number porting.","B":"Correct! SIM Swapping uses social engineering to trick mobile carriers into transferring the victim's phone number to an attacker-controlled SIM card, hijacking all SMS messages including MFA codes.","C":"Incorrect. IMSI Catching uses a fake base station (Stingray) to intercept cellular communications without carrier involvement.","D":"Incorrect. Smishing is SMS-based phishing (sending malicious links via text messages) — it does not involve SIM card control."}},{"id":"cct_216","domain":"Mobile Device Security","question":"An organization's MDM policy specifies that if a device is reported lost or stolen, IT can remotely erase all data on the device. Which MDM capability is being used?","options":{"A":"Geofencing","B":"Application whitelisting","C":"Remote wipe","D":"Containerization"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Geofencing triggers policy actions based on the device's geographic location — not a data erasure function.","B":"Incorrect. Application whitelisting controls which apps can be installed on the device.","C":"Correct! Remote wipe allows IT administrators to send a command to the lost or stolen device to erase all data, protecting corporate information from unauthorized access.","D":"Incorrect. Containerization creates a secure, encrypted corporate workspace on the device but does not erase the device remotely."}},{"id":"cct_217","domain":"Incident Response","question":"According to NIST SP 800-61, during which incident response phase should an organization develop incident response policies, establish a CSIRT, and conduct training exercises?","options":{"A":"Detection and Analysis","B":"Containment, Eradication, and Recovery","C":"Preparation","D":"Post-Incident Activity"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Detection and Analysis focuses on identifying and assessing the scope of an active incident — it occurs after preparation.","B":"Incorrect. Containment, Eradication, and Recovery are reactive phases executed during and after an incident.","C":"Correct! The Preparation phase (Phase 1 of NIST SP 800-61) involves establishing the incident response capability: policies, procedures, CSIRT formation, communication plans, tools, and training exercises — all done before incidents occur.","D":"Incorrect. Post-Incident Activity (Lessons Learned) occurs after an incident is fully resolved."}},{"id":"cct_218","domain":"Incident Response","question":"During a ransomware incident, the security team has identified all infected systems. According to the incident response lifecycle, what is the NEXT correct step after containment?","options":{"A":"Recovery — restore systems from backup immediately","B":"Eradication — remove all malware components, close attack vectors, and patch vulnerabilities","C":"Post-Incident Activity — write the lessons-learned report","D":"Preparation — update the incident response plan"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Restoring systems before fully removing the malware would re-infect the environment. Eradication must come before recovery.","B":"Correct! After containment (stopping the spread), the Eradication phase removes all traces of malware, backdoors, and the initial attack vector, and applies patches. Only then is Recovery (restoration) safe.","C":"Incorrect. Lessons Learned is the final post-incident phase conducted after full recovery, not immediately after containment.","D":"Incorrect. Updating the incident response plan is part of Lessons Learned, which occurs after the incident is fully resolved."}},{"domain":"Network Security Controls - Physical","question":"What is the PRIMARY purpose of a mantrap (airlock) in physical security?","options":{"A":"To prevent tailgating by creating an airlock where only one door can open at a time","B":"To provide redundant power for data center servers","C":"To shield equipment from electromagnetic interference","D":"To monitor employee attendance using biometric data"},"correct_option":"A","explanations":{"A":"Correct! A mantrap consists of two interlocking doors — only one can be open at any moment. This forces each person to authenticate individually, eliminating the risk of tailgating into secured areas.","B":"Incorrect. Redundant power is handled by UPS (Uninterruptible Power Supplies) and generator systems, not mantraps.","C":"Incorrect. A Faraday cage is the control used to block electromagnetic signals, not a mantrap.","D":"Incorrect. While mantraps may use biometrics, their primary purpose is anti-tailgating, not attendance tracking."},"id":"cct_219"},{"domain":"Network Security Controls - Physical","question":"Which physical security control is classified as DETECTIVE rather than preventive?","options":{"A":"Perimeter fencing with barbed wire","B":"Badge-access door locks","C":"CCTV camera recording system","D":"Security guards stationed at entry points"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Perimeter fencing is a preventive control — it physically stops unauthorized entry before it occurs.","B":"Incorrect. Badge-access locks are preventive — they block entry unless valid credentials are presented.","C":"Correct! A CCTV recording system is a detective control. It records events and allows review after the fact to identify security incidents. It detects rather than prevents.","D":"Incorrect. Security guards at entry points primarily prevent unauthorized access (preventive), though they can also deter and detect."},"id":"cct_220"},{"domain":"Network Security Controls - Physical","question":"What is tailgating (piggybacking) in the context of physical security?","options":{"A":"Installing hidden cameras to spy on employee activity inside the facility","B":"An unauthorized person following an authorized individual through a secured door without authenticating","C":"Cloning an RFID badge using a proximity reader to duplicate access credentials","D":"Intercepting wireless traffic from a laptop in the parking lot adjacent to the building"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Hidden camera installation is espionage/insider threat activity, not tailgating.","B":"Correct! Tailgating (piggybacking) occurs when an unauthorized person physically follows an authorized person through a secured entry point before the door closes, bypassing access controls entirely.","C":"Incorrect. RFID cloning is a badge cloning attack — it requires technical interception of radio frequencies, distinct from the physical social engineering of tailgating.","D":"Incorrect. Parking lot Wi-Fi interception is a wireless network attack, not physical tailgating."},"id":"cct_221"},{"domain":"Network Security Controls - Physical","question":"Which environmental control is MOST critical for maintaining hardware availability in a data center?","options":{"A":"CCTV surveillance system","B":"Biometric access control on server room doors","C":"HVAC (Heating, Ventilation, and Air Conditioning) system","D":"Perimeter fencing around the facility"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. CCTV is a detective/deterrent control that does not protect hardware from environmental threats.","B":"Incorrect. Biometric access control prevents unauthorized physical access but does not regulate environmental conditions.","C":"Correct! HVAC maintains temperature and humidity within the operational ranges hardware requires. Overheating and humidity extremes are leading causes of hardware failure; proper HVAC is essential for data center availability (uptime).","D":"Incorrect. Perimeter fencing is an outer-boundary deterrence control and has no effect on internal environmental conditions."},"id":"cct_222"},{"domain":"Network Security Controls - Physical","question":"A Faraday cage is used in physical security to:","options":{"A":"Prevent forced entry using reinforced concrete and steel construction","B":"Block electromagnetic signals from entering or leaving an enclosure, preventing TEMPEST attacks","C":"Detect motion using passive infrared (PIR) sensors","D":"Suppress fires without damaging electronic equipment using clean agents"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Reinforced concrete/steel construction is a structural security control for blast or ballistic resistance, unrelated to electromagnetic shielding.","B":"Correct! A Faraday cage is a metallic enclosure that blocks electromagnetic fields. In security contexts, it prevents electronic eavesdropping (TEMPEST attacks) by ensuring no electromagnetic emissions escape, and stops external signals from entering.","C":"Incorrect. PIR motion sensors are a different physical security control that detects body heat, unrelated to electromagnetic shielding.","D":"Incorrect. Clean agent fire suppression systems (FM-200, Halon alternatives) are environmental controls for fire safety, not electromagnetic shielding."},"id":"cct_223"},{"domain":"Network Security Controls - Physical","question":"What does a clean desk policy require of employees?","options":{"A":"That workstations be physically cleaned daily to prevent dust contamination of hardware","B":"That sensitive documents, removable media, and credentials are locked away whenever an employee leaves their workstation","C":"That only approved software applications are installed on company computers","D":"That employees change passwords at least every 90 days"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Physical cleaning of hardware is a facilities management task, not a clean desk security policy.","B":"Correct! A clean desk policy is an administrative control requiring that sensitive information — documents, USB drives, written passwords, access cards — are secured (locked in drawers or cabinets) whenever an employee is away, preventing unauthorized viewing or theft.","C":"Incorrect. Application whitelisting is a technical control covered under endpoint security policy, not clean desk policy.","D":"Incorrect. Password rotation is a credential management policy unrelated to physical desk security."},"id":"cct_224"},{"domain":"Network Security Controls - Physical","question":"Which type of lock provides the WEAKEST physical access control for a server room?","options":{"A":"Biometric fingerprint scanner integrated with the door lock","B":"Smart card reader requiring both card and PIN entry","C":"Traditional pin-tumbler key lock","D":"Electronic cipher lock with rotating daily access codes"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Biometric locks offer strong security — the physical characteristic is difficult to duplicate and provides an audit trail.","B":"Incorrect. Smart card + PIN is two-factor physical authentication, significantly stronger than a traditional lock.","C":"Correct! A traditional key lock is weakest because physical keys can be duplicated without detection, lost, or stolen. There is no audit trail of who accessed the room or when.","D":"Incorrect. Electronic cipher locks with rotating codes are stronger than physical keys because codes change frequently and can be revoked immediately."},"id":"cct_225"},{"domain":"Network Security Controls - Physical","question":"Which of the following is the BEST example of a deterrent physical security control?","options":{"A":"Smoke detector and suppression system in the server room","B":"Visible CCTV cameras and security warning signs at building entry","C":"Access control list (ACL) on a network switch","D":"UPS (Uninterruptible Power Supply) for critical systems"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Smoke detectors and suppression systems are detective and corrective environmental controls, not deterrents.","B":"Correct! Visible cameras and warning signs are classic deterrent controls — they discourage potential attackers from attempting an intrusion by signaling that they will be observed and recorded. Deterrent controls do not physically stop access but reduce the likelihood of an attempt.","C":"Incorrect. Network switch ACLs are technical/logical controls, not physical deterrents.","D":"Incorrect. A UPS is a corrective/compensating control ensuring power continuity — it addresses availability, not deterrence of attackers."},"id":"cct_226"},{"domain":"Cryptography","question":"What is the fundamental difference between symmetric and asymmetric encryption?","options":{"A":"Symmetric is slower and uses two different keys; asymmetric is faster and uses one key","B":"Symmetric encryption uses the same key for both encryption and decryption; asymmetric uses a public/private key pair","C":"Symmetric encryption is only used for digital signatures; asymmetric is used for bulk data encryption","D":"Symmetric encryption provides non-repudiation; asymmetric does not"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Symmetric encryption is actually FASTER than asymmetric because it uses simpler mathematical operations and a single shared key.","B":"Correct! Symmetric encryption (AES, DES) uses the same secret key to encrypt and decrypt. Asymmetric (RSA, ECC) uses a mathematically linked key pair — anything encrypted with the public key can only be decrypted with the private key.","C":"Incorrect. Digital signatures use asymmetric cryptography (private key signs, public key verifies). Symmetric encryption is used for bulk data (confidentiality).","D":"Incorrect. Non-repudiation is provided by asymmetric cryptography (digital signatures), not symmetric."},"id":"cct_227"},{"domain":"Cryptography","question":"Which block cipher was selected by NIST as the Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) in 2001?","options":{"A":"DES (Data Encryption Standard)","B":"3DES (Triple DES)","C":"Rijndael","D":"Blowfish"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. DES was the predecessor standard (adopted 1977) that AES replaced. DES uses a 56-bit key now considered too short.","B":"Incorrect. 3DES applies DES three times and was a transitional solution, not the AES winner.","C":"Correct! Rijndael, designed by Belgian cryptographers Joan Daemen and Vincent Rijmen, was selected as the winner of NIST's AES competition. It supports 128, 192, or 256-bit keys.","D":"Incorrect. Blowfish is a strong symmetric cipher designed by Bruce Schneier but was not submitted to the AES competition."},"id":"cct_228"},{"domain":"Cryptography","question":"What is the purpose of a digital signature?","options":{"A":"To encrypt a message so that only the intended recipient can read it","B":"To authenticate the sender's identity and verify that the message has not been altered","C":"To generate a symmetric session key for encrypting bulk data","D":"To compress data before transmission to reduce bandwidth usage"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Encrypting a message for confidentiality uses the recipient's public key (or symmetric encryption) — this is not what a digital signature provides.","B":"Correct! A digital signature uses the sender's private key to sign a hash of the message. The recipient verifies with the sender's public key, proving authenticity (who sent it) and integrity (message unchanged). It also provides non-repudiation.","C":"Incorrect. Session key generation is handled by key exchange protocols (Diffie-Hellman, RSA key encapsulation), not digital signatures.","D":"Incorrect. Data compression is a separate operation (gzip, LZ77) unrelated to digital signatures."},"id":"cct_229"},{"domain":"Cryptography","question":"What is the Diffie-Hellman (DH) algorithm primarily used for?","options":{"A":"Encrypting large volumes of data quickly using symmetric keys","B":"Generating message digests to verify data integrity","C":"Securely establishing a shared secret key over an insecure channel without transmitting the key","D":"Signing digital certificates to bind identities to public keys"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Fast bulk data encryption is the role of symmetric algorithms like AES, not Diffie-Hellman.","B":"Incorrect. Message digests (hashing) are generated by algorithms like SHA-256, MD5, not Diffie-Hellman.","C":"Correct! Diffie-Hellman is a key exchange protocol. Both parties exchange public values and independently compute the same shared secret without ever transmitting it — solving the key distribution problem over untrusted channels.","D":"Incorrect. Certificate signing is performed by Certificate Authorities (CAs) using RSA or ECDSA, not Diffie-Hellman."},"id":"cct_230"},{"domain":"Cryptography","question":"What type of cryptographic attack exploits the birthday paradox to find two different inputs that produce the same hash output?","options":{"A":"Preimage attack — finding the input for a known hash value","B":"Rainbow table attack — using precomputed hash chains","C":"Birthday attack — exploiting probability to find hash collisions","D":"Length extension attack — appending data to an unknown message"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. A preimage attack attempts to find ANY input that produces a specific target hash (inverting the hash function), not finding two inputs that collide.","B":"Incorrect. Rainbow table attacks use precomputed hash:plaintext pairs to crack hashed passwords, not to find general hash collisions.","C":"Correct! The birthday attack exploits the birthday paradox — the probability of two random items sharing a value grows surprisingly fast. For an n-bit hash, finding a collision requires roughly 2^(n/2) attempts rather than 2^n, making shorter hashes (MD5, SHA-1) vulnerable.","D":"Incorrect. Length extension attacks exploit specific hash function properties (Merkle-Damgard construction) to extend a valid hash without knowing the secret — a different vulnerability."},"id":"cct_231"},{"domain":"Cryptography","question":"What does a Certificate Authority (CA) do in a Public Key Infrastructure (PKI)?","options":{"A":"Generates symmetric session keys for HTTPS connections between clients and servers","B":"Issues, signs, and manages digital certificates that bind a public key to an authenticated identity","C":"Encrypts all network traffic using RSA to ensure confidentiality","D":"Stores every user's private key in a secure escrow database"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Session key generation for HTTPS is performed during the TLS handshake using Diffie-Hellman or RSA key encapsulation — not the CA's role.","B":"Correct! The CA is a trusted third party that verifies identities and issues X.509 digital certificates. The CA signs each certificate with its own private key, allowing anyone with the CA's public key to verify the certificate's authenticity.","C":"Incorrect. The CA does not encrypt traffic. It validates identities so that encrypting parties can trust each other's public keys.","D":"Incorrect. Storing users' private keys would completely undermine PKI security — private keys must never be shared. Key escrow is a separate, controversial mechanism not inherent to CA operation."},"id":"cct_232"},{"domain":"Cryptography","question":"Which cipher mode of operation provides BOTH confidentiality AND built-in message authentication?","options":{"A":"ECB (Electronic Codebook) — each block encrypted independently","B":"CBC (Cipher Block Chaining) without an additional HMAC","C":"GCM (Galois/Counter Mode) — authenticated encryption with associated data (AEAD)","D":"CTR (Counter Mode) without additional authentication"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. ECB provides only confidentiality and is considered weak — identical plaintext blocks produce identical ciphertext, revealing data patterns.","B":"Incorrect. CBC alone provides confidentiality but NOT authentication. Without HMAC, a CBC ciphertext can be tampered with (padding oracle attacks).","C":"Correct! GCM (Galois/Counter Mode) is an Authenticated Encryption with Associated Data (AEAD) mode. It simultaneously encrypts data (confidentiality) and produces an authentication tag (integrity + authenticity). Used in TLS 1.3 and AES-GCM.","D":"Incorrect. CTR mode provides confidentiality through a stream cipher approach but offers no built-in authentication — tampering won't be detected."},"id":"cct_233"},{"domain":"Cryptography","question":"Which TLS feature ensures that past session traffic cannot be decrypted even if the server's long-term private key is later compromised?","options":{"A":"TLS certificate pinning","B":"Perfect Forward Secrecy (PFS) using ephemeral Diffie-Hellman (ECDHE)","C":"HSTS (HTTP Strict Transport Security)","D":"Certificate Transparency (CT) logs"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Certificate pinning prevents MitM via rogue certificates — it ensures the client only accepts a specific certificate or public key.","B":"Correct! Perfect Forward Secrecy uses ephemeral (temporary) Diffie-Hellman key pairs for each session. Since session keys are derived from ephemeral values that are discarded after use, compromising the server's long-term private key later cannot decrypt past sessions. Required by TLS 1.3.","C":"Incorrect. HSTS forces browsers to always use HTTPS, preventing protocol downgrade — it does not affect session key confidentiality.","D":"Incorrect. Certificate Transparency logs create an auditable record of issued certificates to detect rogue CAs — unrelated to session key protection."},"id":"cct_234"},{"domain":"Network Security Controls - Administrative","question":"Which of the following is the BEST example of an administrative security control?","options":{"A":"Deploying a next-generation firewall between the DMZ and internal network","B":"Installing biometric scanners at data center entry points","C":"Enforcing a mandatory annual security awareness training program for all employees","D":"Encrypting all laptops with BitLocker full-disk encryption"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. A firewall is a technical (logical) control that actively filters network traffic — not an administrative control.","B":"Incorrect. Biometric scanners are physical controls that restrict entry to facilities.","C":"Correct! Administrative controls are policies, procedures, and training programs that govern behavior. A mandatory security awareness training program is a classic administrative control — it reduces risk by educating the human element.","D":"Incorrect. Full-disk encryption is a technical control that protects data at rest — not an administrative policy."},"id":"cct_235"},{"domain":"Network Security Controls - Administrative","question":"What is the purpose of the ISO/IEC 27001 standard?","options":{"A":"To define technical specifications for firewall and IDS configurations","B":"To specify requirements for establishing, implementing, maintaining, and improving an Information Security Management System (ISMS)","C":"To certify individual security professionals through a competency examination","D":"To define legal penalties for cybercrime under international law"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Technical configuration standards are addressed by vendor-specific guides and benchmarks (CIS Benchmarks), not ISO 27001.","B":"Correct! ISO/IEC 27001 is the internationally recognized standard that defines the requirements for an ISMS — the framework of policies, processes, and controls that organizations use to manage information security risk systematically.","C":"Incorrect. Professional certifications (CISSP, CEH, CompTIA Security+) are issued by certifying bodies, not by ISO standards.","D":"Incorrect. International cybercrime law is governed by treaties like the Budapest Convention, not ISO standards."},"id":"cct_236"},{"domain":"Network Security Controls - Administrative","question":"The principle of least privilege states that:","options":{"A":"All users should have full administrative rights to maximize productivity","B":"Users should be granted only the minimum access rights required to perform their specific job functions","C":"Privileged accounts should use the same credentials as standard user accounts for simplicity","D":"Access to sensitive systems should be denied to all employees by default, regardless of role"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Granting full admin rights to all users violates least privilege and massively increases the blast radius of any compromise or insider threat.","B":"Correct! The principle of least privilege (PoLP) limits each user, process, or system to only the access rights needed for their specific role. This limits damage from compromised accounts, malware, and insider threats.","C":"Incorrect. Privileged accounts must use separate, distinct credentials from standard accounts — sharing credentials eliminates accountability and audit trails.","D":"Incorrect. Denying all access would prevent any work from being done. Least privilege means minimum necessary access, not zero access."},"id":"cct_237"},{"domain":"Network Security Controls - Administrative","question":"What does the NIST Cybersecurity Framework (CSF) 'Identify' function focus on?","options":{"A":"Deploying firewalls and IDS/IPS systems to block known threats","B":"Developing organizational understanding of cybersecurity risk to systems, assets, data, and capabilities","C":"Restoring services after a cybersecurity incident has been contained","D":"Detecting anomalous activity through SIEM alerts and log correlation"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Deploying protective technologies falls under the 'Protect' function of the NIST CSF.","B":"Correct! The NIST CSF 'Identify' function is about understanding the organization's risk environment — inventorying assets, understanding business context, and assessing risk to prioritize cybersecurity efforts. The five functions are: Identify, Protect, Detect, Respond, Recover.","C":"Incorrect. Restoring services after an incident is the 'Recover' function.","D":"Incorrect. Detecting anomalous activity is the 'Detect' function."},"id":"cct_238"},{"domain":"Network Security Controls - Administrative","question":"What is the purpose of separation of duties (SoD) as an administrative control?","options":{"A":"To ensure that no single individual can complete a sensitive transaction or process without involving at least one other person","B":"To divide network infrastructure into separate VLANs to limit lateral movement","C":"To assign different hardware devices to separate employee roles to prevent device sharing","D":"To create separate user accounts for daily work and administrative tasks"},"correct_option":"A","explanations":{"A":"Correct! Separation of duties (SoD) requires multiple individuals to complete a sensitive process, preventing any one person from having enough access to commit and conceal fraud or errors. Classic example: the person who approves payments should not be the same person who processes them.","B":"Incorrect. VLAN segmentation is a technical network control that limits lateral movement — related to network segmentation, not SoD.","C":"Incorrect. Device assignment is a hardware asset management practice, not the SoD administrative control.","D":"Incorrect. Dual accounts (standard + privileged) is the principle of privilege separation/account separation, which is related but distinct from SoD."},"id":"cct_239"},{"domain":"Network Security Controls - Administrative","question":"An organization's security policy states that all data must be classified before storage. Which of the following is a common data classification level in government environments?","options":{"A":"Public, Internal, Confidential, Secret","B":"Unclassified, Confidential, Secret, Top Secret","C":"Low, Medium, High, Critical","D":"Open, Restricted, Private, Sensitive"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Public/Internal/Confidential/Secret is a common commercial/corporate classification scheme (e.g., used by many private organizations), not the standard government model.","B":"Correct! The US government classification scheme is: Unclassified → Confidential → Secret → Top Secret (and above that, Special Access Programs). This hierarchy drives who can access information and how it must be handled.","C":"Incorrect. Low/Medium/High/Critical is often used for risk or vulnerability severity ratings (e.g., CVSS), not data classification.","D":"Incorrect. Open/Restricted/Private/Sensitive is a custom commercial scheme, not the standard government model tested in CCT."},"id":"cct_240"},{"domain":"Network Security Assessment","question":"What is the key difference between a vulnerability assessment and a penetration test?","options":{"A":"A vulnerability assessment exploits vulnerabilities to demonstrate impact; a penetration test only scans and reports","B":"A vulnerability assessment identifies and prioritizes weaknesses; a penetration test actively exploits them to prove real-world risk","C":"Both terms are interchangeable; they describe the same activity","D":"A penetration test requires no authorization; a vulnerability assessment always requires legal permission"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. This reverses the definitions. Vulnerability assessments scan and report — they do not typically exploit. Penetration tests actively exploit.","B":"Correct! A vulnerability assessment identifies, classifies, and prioritizes vulnerabilities using automated scanners (Nessus, OpenVAS). A penetration test goes further — it actively exploits vulnerabilities to demonstrate real-world impact, simulating what an attacker could achieve.","C":"Incorrect. They are distinct activities with different scope, authorization requirements, and risk levels.","D":"Incorrect. BOTH require explicit written authorization. Unauthorized testing is illegal regardless of which activity it is."},"id":"cct_241"},{"domain":"Network Security Assessment","question":"What does CVE (Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures) provide?","options":{"A":"A framework and methodology for conducting penetration tests","B":"A standardized naming and identification system for publicly known cybersecurity vulnerabilities","C":"A numerical severity score (0-10) quantifying the exploitability and impact of a vulnerability","D":"A database of firewall signatures for detecting known exploit traffic"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Penetration testing methodologies are documented by PTES (Penetration Testing Execution Standard), OWASP, and NIST guides — not CVE.","B":"Correct! CVE (maintained by MITRE) provides a standardized identifier (e.g., CVE-2021-44228 for Log4Shell) for each publicly known vulnerability. This common language allows security tools, databases, and organizations to refer to the same vulnerability unambiguously.","C":"Incorrect. CVSS (Common Vulnerability Scoring System) provides the 0-10 severity score — a related but separate system from CVE identifiers.","D":"Incorrect. Firewall and IDS signature databases are maintained by vendors (Snort rules, Suricata rules), not by the CVE program."},"id":"cct_242"},{"domain":"Network Security Assessment","question":"Which NMAP scan type performs a 'half-open' connection, sending a SYN and recording the response without completing the TCP handshake?","options":{"A":"nmap -sV (Service/Version Detection)","B":"nmap -sU (UDP Scan)","C":"nmap -sS (SYN/Stealth Scan)","D":"nmap -sA (ACK Scan)"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. -sV probes open ports to determine service names and version numbers — it builds on an initial scan and doesn't define the scan type.","B":"Incorrect. -sU sends UDP packets to detect UDP services — a completely different protocol from TCP SYN scanning.","C":"Correct! The SYN scan (-sS) sends a TCP SYN packet. If the port is open, the target responds SYN-ACK, and Nmap immediately sends RST to avoid completing the handshake (half-open). This is stealthier than a full connect scan and requires root/admin privileges.","D":"Incorrect. -sA sends ACK packets and is used to map firewall rules (filtered vs. unfiltered), not to identify open/closed ports."},"id":"cct_243"},{"domain":"Network Security Assessment","question":"What is OSINT (Open Source Intelligence) in the context of ethical hacking reconnaissance?","options":{"A":"Exploiting SQL injection vulnerabilities to extract database information","B":"Scanning internal network ranges with Nmap to enumerate live hosts","C":"Gathering publicly available information about a target from the internet, social media, WHOIS, job postings, etc.","D":"Intercepting network traffic to capture credentials in transit"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. SQL injection is an active exploitation technique in the attack phase, not passive reconnaissance OSINT.","B":"Incorrect. Internal network scanning with Nmap is active reconnaissance requiring network access — not open-source intelligence gathering.","C":"Correct! OSINT is the collection and analysis of information from publicly available sources: DNS records, WHOIS data, social media profiles, LinkedIn, company websites, GitHub repositories, job postings, and Google dorking. It is passive and leaves no trace on the target's systems.","D":"Incorrect. Intercepting network traffic is an active attack (sniffing/MitM), requiring technical access to the network — not OSINT."},"id":"cct_244"},{"domain":"Network Security Assessment","question":"What is threat hunting in the context of network security assessment?","options":{"A":"Automatically blocking threats at the firewall based on reputation feeds","B":"A proactive, hypothesis-driven search through logs and network data to find threats that have evaded automated detection","C":"Scanning a network for unpatched vulnerabilities using an automated vulnerability scanner","D":"Monitoring SIEM alerts and responding to generated security incidents"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Automatic threat blocking based on reputation feeds is a reactive technical control (threat intelligence integration with firewalls/EDR), not threat hunting.","B":"Correct! Threat hunting is a proactive security practice where skilled analysts form hypotheses about possible attacker behaviors (based on threat intelligence and TTPs) and manually search through data to find evidence of compromise that automated tools may have missed.","C":"Incorrect. Automated vulnerability scanning is a vulnerability assessment activity, not threat hunting.","D":"Incorrect. Responding to SIEM alerts is reactive incident response — the opposite of proactive threat hunting."},"id":"cct_245"},{"domain":"Mobile Device Security","question":"What is Mobile Device Management (MDM) primarily used for in an enterprise?","options":{"A":"Encrypting all email traffic between mobile users and the mail server","B":"Centrally managing, monitoring, and enforcing security policies across all enrolled mobile devices","C":"Creating VPN tunnels so mobile devices can access the corporate network","D":"Scanning mobile applications for malware before allowing installation"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Email encryption (S/MIME, TLS) is a separate control from MDM, though MDM can enforce email encryption policies.","B":"Correct! MDM solutions (Microsoft Intune, VMware Workspace ONE) allow IT to enroll, configure, monitor, and remotely manage mobile devices. They enforce policies like screen lock, encryption, app whitelisting, and enable remote wipe if a device is lost or stolen.","C":"Incorrect. VPN client configuration is one feature MDM can deploy, but the primary purpose of MDM is comprehensive device management and policy enforcement.","D":"Incorrect. App vetting is handled by enterprise app stores, MAM (Mobile Application Management), or OS-level sandboxing — MDM can restrict app installation but is not primarily a malware scanner."},"id":"cct_246"},{"domain":"Mobile Device Security","question":"What is the purpose of containerization in mobile device security for BYOD environments?","options":{"A":"To physically protect the device with a ruggedized case and shatter-proof screen protector","B":"To sandbox corporate data and applications in a separate encrypted area, isolated from the employee's personal data","C":"To prevent the device from connecting to unauthorized Wi-Fi networks","D":"To encrypt all data transmitted over cellular networks using device-level IPsec"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Ruggedized cases are physical protection, not a security architecture. Containerization is a software concept.","B":"Correct! Containerization (used in MDM solutions like Samsung Knox) creates a secure encrypted workspace on the device. Corporate emails, apps, and files exist in this container — completely isolated from personal apps and data. If employment ends or the device is compromised, only the container is wiped, leaving personal data intact.","C":"Incorrect. Wi-Fi access restrictions are a separate MDM policy control, not what containerization addresses.","D":"Incorrect. Cellular traffic encryption is handled at the carrier level and by VPN clients — not containerization."},"id":"cct_247"},{"domain":"Mobile Device Security","question":"What is remote wipe used for in mobile device security?","options":{"A":"To push operating system updates to a fleet of mobile devices simultaneously","B":"To erase all data on a lost, stolen, or compromised device to prevent unauthorized access to corporate data","C":"To remotely install approved applications through the enterprise app store","D":"To monitor device location in real time using GPS and report it to HR"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. OS update deployment is a separate MDM capability (patch management/OTA updates), not remote wipe.","B":"Correct! Remote wipe allows IT administrators (or device owners) to send a command that completely erases all data on a mobile device. This is critical when a device is reported lost or stolen, or when an employee is terminated and returns a device with corporate data.","C":"Incorrect. Remote app installation is handled through MDM's application management capabilities, not remote wipe.","D":"Incorrect. GPS location tracking is a separate MDM feature (geolocation/geo-fencing), not remote wipe."},"id":"cct_248"},{"domain":"Mobile Device Security","question":"Which mobile connection method presents the HIGHEST security risk for corporate data in a public location?","options":{"A":"4G LTE cellular data connection with no VPN","B":"Corporate VPN over any available network connection","C":"Open, unencrypted public Wi-Fi without a VPN","D":"Bluetooth tethering to a trusted personal hotspot"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Cellular 4G/LTE is encrypted by the carrier at the radio layer and is significantly harder to intercept than open Wi-Fi — still not perfect, but not the highest risk.","B":"Incorrect. A corporate VPN over any network encrypts all traffic in a tunnel to the corporate network — this is the MOST secure option.","C":"Correct! Open public Wi-Fi sends all traffic unencrypted. An attacker on the same network can use tools like Wireshark to capture all plaintext traffic, perform man-in-the-middle attacks, and harvest credentials or sensitive data.","D":"Incorrect. Tethering to a personal hotspot uses the cellular network with WPA2/WPA3 encryption — considerably more secure than open public Wi-Fi."},"id":"cct_249"},{"domain":"Mobile Device Security","question":"What security risk does jailbreaking (iOS) or rooting (Android) a mobile device introduce?","options":{"A":"It reduces battery life and processing performance, impacting productivity","B":"It bypasses the OS security model, removing sandboxing, integrity checks, and making the device ineligible for enterprise MDM","C":"It automatically shares the device's GPS location with third-party advertisers","D":"It prevents the device from connecting to enterprise Wi-Fi networks using 802.1X"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Performance impacts may occur but are not the security risk — the concern is the removal of security controls.","B":"Correct! Jailbreaking/rooting removes OS-level security boundaries: app sandboxing is bypassed, code signing checks are disabled, and unauthorized apps (including malware) can be installed with elevated privileges. Enterprise MDM solutions typically detect and block jailbroken/rooted devices from accessing corporate resources.","C":"Incorrect. Location sharing with advertisers is a privacy concern tied to app permissions, not specifically caused by jailbreaking.","D":"Incorrect. 802.1X connectivity depends on certificate/credential configuration, not jailbreak status directly."},"id":"cct_250"},{"domain":"Mobile Device Security","question":"What is a BYOD (Bring Your Own Device) policy designed to address?","options":{"A":"Requiring employees to purchase company-approved devices with their own personal funds","B":"Establishing security requirements and acceptable use rules for personal devices that access corporate resources","C":"Preventing employees from using personal devices at work to eliminate security risk entirely","D":"Defining which mobile operating systems are approved for corporate device procurement"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. BYOD means employees use their OWN devices — they are not required to buy specific devices.","B":"Correct! A BYOD policy defines the rules for personal device usage: required MDM enrollment, acceptable use boundaries, data handling requirements, what corporate data can be accessed, and what happens to corporate data if employment ends. It balances employee privacy with corporate security.","C":"Incorrect. That would be a 'no personal devices' or 'COPE (Corporate-Owned, Personally-Enabled)' policy, not BYOD.","D":"Incorrect. Corporate device procurement standards apply to company-owned hardware — BYOD covers personal devices the employee already owns."},"id":"cct_251"},{"domain":"Incident Response","question":"According to NIST SP 800-61, what are the four phases of the incident response lifecycle?","options":{"A":"Detect, Analyze, Contain, Report","B":"Preparation; Detection & Analysis; Containment, Eradication & Recovery; Post-Incident Activity","C":"Identification, Containment, Investigation, Remediation","D":"Triage, Escalation, Remediation, Closure"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. This is a simplified partial list that does not match NIST SP 800-61's defined framework.","B":"Correct! NIST SP 800-61 Rev. 2 defines the four phases as: (1) Preparation — building IR capability; (2) Detection & Analysis — identifying and scoping incidents; (3) Containment, Eradication & Recovery — stopping spread and restoring; (4) Post-Incident Activity — lessons learned and improvement.","C":"Incorrect. This describes a common informal approach but does not match NIST's official lifecycle phases.","D":"Incorrect. This describes a help desk/ticketing workflow, not the NIST incident response lifecycle."},"id":"cct_252"},{"domain":"Incident Response","question":"What is the PRIMARY goal of the containment phase during incident response?","options":{"A":"To permanently remove all traces of malware from every affected system","B":"To prevent the incident from spreading further while preserving evidence for investigation","C":"To notify all affected users and regulators about the security breach","D":"To restore all affected systems to their pre-incident operational state"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Permanent malware removal is eradication, not containment. Containment happens first to limit spread.","B":"Correct! Containment stops the incident from worsening — isolating infected systems, blocking attacker C2 communications, and restricting lateral movement — while carefully preserving forensic evidence (memory dumps, logs) needed for investigation.","C":"Incorrect. Notification of stakeholders and regulators is part of the incident communication plan, often overlapping with post-incident activities, not containment.","D":"Incorrect. Restoring systems is recovery — the final step after containment and eradication."},"id":"cct_253"},{"domain":"Incident Response","question":"What is the role of a SIEM (Security Information and Event Management) system in incident response?","options":{"A":"To automatically patch vulnerabilities on endpoints when exploits are detected","B":"To isolate compromised machines from the network by pushing firewall rules","C":"To aggregate, normalize, and correlate log data from multiple sources, generating alerts for suspicious patterns","D":"To restore data from the most recent clean backup after ransomware is detected"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Automated patching is handled by patch management tools (WSUS, SCCM) or EDR platforms — not SIEM's primary function.","B":"Incorrect. Network isolation/quarantine is performed by firewalls, NAC, or EDR solutions — though SIEM can trigger these via SOAR integration.","C":"Correct! A SIEM collects logs from firewalls, servers, endpoints, and applications; normalizes the data; applies correlation rules; and generates alerts when patterns indicate a security incident (e.g., multiple failed logins followed by a successful one from the same IP).","D":"Incorrect. Backup restoration is performed by backup/recovery solutions (Veeam, Azure Backup) — SIEM focuses on detection and analysis."},"id":"cct_254"},{"domain":"Incident Response","question":"During an incident investigation, the chain of custody refers to:","options":{"A":"The escalation hierarchy from analyst to CISO during a critical incident","B":"A documented, unbroken record of who collected, possessed, transferred, and analyzed evidence","C":"The order in which compromised systems are restored based on business priority","D":"The list of indicators of compromise (IoCs) discovered during forensic analysis"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. The escalation path is defined in the incident response plan's communication matrix, not what chain of custody describes.","B":"Correct! Chain of custody is the documented trail proving that evidence has not been tampered with from the moment of collection through analysis and court presentation. It records who collected it, when, how it was stored, and every person who handled it — essential for legal admissibility.","C":"Incorrect. System restoration priority is defined by recovery objectives (RTO/RPO) and business impact analysis, not chain of custody.","D":"Incorrect. IoC lists are findings documents; chain of custody tracks the integrity of physical/digital evidence handling."},"id":"cct_255"},{"domain":"Incident Response","question":"What is an Indicator of Compromise (IoC) in incident response?","options":{"A":"A formal written agreement between an organization and its cloud provider defining security responsibilities","B":"A forensic artifact or observable evidence suggesting that a system has been compromised or targeted","C":"A vulnerability scan finding that indicates a system is susceptible to a known exploit","D":"A configuration deviation from the security baseline detected during a compliance audit"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. That describes a Cloud Service Level Agreement (SLA) or shared responsibility model — not an IoC.","B":"Correct! An IoC is observable evidence of a security incident: unusual outbound connections, malicious hash values, C2 domain names in DNS logs, registry run key changes, new admin accounts, large data exfiltration events. IoCs are used to detect, confirm, and scope incidents.","C":"Incorrect. A vulnerability scan finding is a pre-exploitation weakness — it indicates risk but not actual compromise. IoCs indicate a breach has occurred or is occurring.","D":"Incorrect. Configuration drift from a baseline is a compliance finding that may represent risk but is not evidence of active compromise."},"id":"cct_256"},{"domain":"Incident Response","question":"What is documented in an After-Action Report (AAR) / Lessons Learned Report following an incident?","options":{"A":"The technical specifications of the attack tools used by the threat actor","B":"A timeline of events, what worked well, what failed, and recommendations to improve future response","C":"The legal evidence package prepared for law enforcement prosecution","D":"The list of affected users who must be notified under data breach regulations"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Attack tool analysis is part of the malware/forensic report, not the AAR's primary focus.","B":"Correct! An After-Action Report (post-mortem) documents: the incident timeline, what detection/response steps worked, what gaps were exposed, what tools performed well or poorly, and concrete recommendations to improve the IR plan, tools, and training for future incidents.","C":"Incorrect. Legal evidence packages are part of the forensic documentation compiled separately for law enforcement — the AAR focuses on operational improvement.","D":"Incorrect. Breach notification lists are managed through the legal/compliance team under regulatory requirements (GDPR, HIPAA) — a separate deliverable from the AAR."},"id":"cct_257"},{"domain":"Network Troubleshooting","question":"A user can reach websites by IP address (e.g., http://8.8.8.8) but not by hostname (e.g., http://google.com). What is the MOST likely cause?","options":{"A":"The default gateway IP is misconfigured on the workstation","B":"The network interface card (NIC) driver is corrupted and needs reinstallation","C":"The DNS server is unreachable or returning incorrect responses","D":"The subnet mask is incorrect, causing traffic to be routed to the wrong network"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. If the default gateway were wrong, the user could not reach ANY external IP addresses — but they can reach 8.8.8.8, so routing works.","B":"Incorrect. If the NIC driver were corrupted, there would be no network connectivity at all — not just name resolution failure.","C":"Correct! The symptom is precisely a name resolution failure: IPs work (TCP/IP is fine) but hostnames don't. This points directly to DNS — either the DNS server is down, unreachable, misconfigured, or the client has a wrong DNS server address.","D":"Incorrect. An incorrect subnet mask would affect routing (some hosts reachable, others not) but not specifically cause hostname resolution to fail while IP access works."},"id":"cct_258"},{"domain":"Network Troubleshooting","question":"A host has been assigned the IP address 169.254.43.18. What does this indicate?","options":{"A":"The host is using a manually configured static IP in the APIPA range","B":"The host failed to obtain an address from a DHCP server and assigned itself an APIPA address","C":"The host is located in a private Class B (172.16.0.0/12) network","D":"The host received an IPv6 address translated to an IPv4-compatible format"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Administrators do not manually assign 169.254.x.x addresses — these are exclusively used by APIPA (Automatic Private IP Addressing) as a fallback.","B":"Correct! 169.254.0.0/16 is the APIPA (Automatic Private IP Addressing) range defined in RFC 3927. When a Windows or Linux host cannot reach a DHCP server after several attempts, it assigns itself an address in this range. It allows link-local communication but provides no internet access.","C":"Incorrect. Private Class B addresses are 172.16.0.0 – 172.31.255.255 (RFC 1918), not 169.254.x.x.","D":"Incorrect. IPv4-compatible IPv6 addresses use a different format (::ffff:x.x.x.x). APIPA is purely an IPv4 fallback mechanism."},"id":"cct_259"},{"domain":"Network Troubleshooting","question":"Which command should you run FIRST to verify that a remote host is reachable at the IP layer?","options":{"A":"tracert / traceroute — to map the full path to the destination","B":"nslookup — to check DNS resolution for the hostname","C":"ping — to send ICMP Echo Requests and verify basic IP connectivity","D":"netstat — to view current network connections and listening ports"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. tracert/traceroute is used once basic connectivity is confirmed — to find WHERE in the path packets are being dropped. It's a second-step diagnostic.","B":"Incorrect. nslookup checks name resolution, not IP-layer connectivity. Use it after confirming the host is reachable by IP.","C":"Correct! ping sends ICMP Echo Requests to the target and waits for Echo Replies. A successful ping confirms IP-layer connectivity between the source and destination. It's the first and fastest connectivity check.","D":"Incorrect. netstat shows the state of existing connections on the LOCAL system — it cannot test connectivity to a remote host."},"id":"cct_260"},{"domain":"Network Troubleshooting","question":"What does the `ipconfig /flushdns` command do on Windows?","options":{"A":"Releases the current DHCP lease and requests a new IP address from the DHCP server","B":"Clears the local DNS resolver cache, forcing all subsequent lookups to query the DNS server fresh","C":"Resets the TCP/IP stack to its factory default configuration","D":"Displays detailed DNS configuration including primary and secondary DNS server addresses"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Releasing and renewing a DHCP address uses `ipconfig /release` followed by `ipconfig /renew`.","B":"Correct! `ipconfig /flushdns` empties the local DNS resolver cache. This is useful when a DNS record has changed but the old (stale) cached value is still being returned, causing connection failures to recently updated hostnames.","C":"Incorrect. Resetting the TCP/IP stack requires `netsh int ip reset` — a much more destructive operation.","D":"Incorrect. Displaying DNS server configuration uses `ipconfig /all`, which shows all IP configuration details including DNS servers."},"id":"cct_261"},{"domain":"Network Troubleshooting","question":"The `traceroute` (Linux) / `tracert` (Windows) command is used to:","options":{"A":"Check whether a specific TCP port is open on a remote host","B":"Display every router hop a packet traverses to reach the destination, identifying where connectivity fails","C":"Measure available bandwidth between two hosts using UDP probe packets","D":"Perform a reverse DNS lookup to identify the hostname associated with an IP address"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Testing specific TCP port connectivity uses tools like `telnet <host> <port>`, `nmap -p <port>`, or `Test-NetConnection` (PowerShell).","B":"Correct! traceroute/tracert exploits the IP TTL (Time-To-Live) field — it sends packets with incrementing TTL values and records the ICMP Time Exceeded responses from each router. The output shows every hop (router) on the path to the destination, allowing you to identify exactly where connectivity breaks.","C":"Incorrect. Bandwidth measurement tools include iperf3, speedtest-cli — traceroute does not measure bandwidth.","D":"Incorrect. Reverse DNS lookup is performed with `nslookup <IP>` or `dig -x <IP>`."},"id":"cct_262"},{"domain":"Network Troubleshooting","question":"On a Linux system, which command shows the current routing table to verify how traffic is being forwarded?","options":{"A":"netstat -tulnp","B":"ps aux","C":"ip route show","D":"arp -n"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. `netstat -tulnp` shows listening TCP/UDP ports and their associated processes — it does not show the routing table.","B":"Incorrect. `ps aux` lists all running processes — unrelated to routing.","C":"Correct! `ip route show` (or `ip route`) displays the kernel routing table on Linux, showing which network interface and gateway is used for each destination network. The equivalent legacy command is `route -n`.","D":"Incorrect. `arp -n` shows the ARP cache (IP-to-MAC address mappings for recently contacted hosts on the local subnet) — not the routing table."},"id":"cct_263"},{"domain":"Network Traffic Monitoring","question":"What is the purpose of establishing a network traffic baseline?","options":{"A":"To encrypt all network traffic using AES-256 as a security control","B":"To document normal traffic patterns so that deviations and anomalies can be detected","C":"To apply QoS policies that prioritize voice and video traffic over bulk transfers","D":"To automatically block all traffic that exceeds a defined bandwidth threshold"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Encrypting traffic is a security control, not a baseline monitoring activity.","B":"Correct! A traffic baseline documents what 'normal' looks like: typical protocols, volumes, bandwidth usage patterns, peak times, and common destinations. Any significant deviation from the baseline (e.g., sudden large outbound transfers at 2 AM) becomes an anomaly that triggers investigation.","C":"Incorrect. QoS is a network engineering concern for service quality — it uses baselines but the purpose of establishing a baseline is anomaly detection, not QoS.","D":"Incorrect. Automated blocking based on thresholds is a rate-limiting or DDoS mitigation control, not what a traffic baseline is established for."},"id":"cct_264"},{"domain":"Network Traffic Monitoring","question":"An IDS alert shows a flood of TCP SYN packets from a single source IP to many different ports on one target host. What does this indicate?","options":{"A":"ARP cache poisoning is being performed on the local subnet","B":"A DNS amplification DDoS attack is underway","C":"A port scan (likely Nmap SYN scan -sS) is being performed to discover open services","D":"A man-in-the-middle attack is intercepting traffic between two hosts"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. ARP poisoning generates ARP Reply packets on the local LAN — not SYN packets to multiple ports.","B":"Incorrect. DNS amplification uses spoofed UDP packets targeting DNS servers to flood a victim — not TCP SYN to multiple ports on one target.","C":"Correct! SYN packets sent rapidly to many ports on one target is the signature of a port scan, specifically Nmap's SYN (-sS) scan. The scanner sends SYN to each port and looks for SYN-ACK (open) or RST (closed) responses.","D":"Incorrect. Man-in-the-middle attacks (ARP poisoning, SSL stripping) do not produce this SYN flood pattern to multiple ports."},"id":"cct_265"},{"domain":"Network Traffic Monitoring","question":"What does NetFlow provide for network monitoring?","options":{"A":"Full packet payload capture for deep content inspection","B":"Flow-level metadata (source/dest IP and port, protocol, byte/packet count) enabling traffic analysis without capturing payloads","C":"Encryption of all inter-switch traffic using 802.1AE MACsec","D":"Real-time blocking of known malicious IP addresses at the router level"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Full packet capture (PCAP) is done by tools like Wireshark or tcpdump — NetFlow captures only flow metadata, not payloads.","B":"Correct! NetFlow (Cisco) and its equivalents (IPFIX, sFlow) collect flow records from routers and switches: who communicated with whom, on what protocol/port, and how much data was exchanged. This allows traffic analysis and anomaly detection without the storage cost of full packet capture.","C":"Incorrect. 802.1AE MACsec is a Layer 2 encryption standard for switch-to-switch links — unrelated to NetFlow monitoring.","D":"Incorrect. Real-time blocking based on threat feeds is done by firewall ACLs or BGP blackholing — not NetFlow, which is a monitoring/export protocol."},"id":"cct_266"},{"domain":"Network Traffic Monitoring","question":"Which Wireshark display filter shows ONLY HTTP POST requests in a capture file?","options":{"A":"http.method == 'GET'","B":"tcp.port == 80","C":"http.request.method == \"POST\"","D":"ip.proto == 6 and port 80"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. This filter shows HTTP GET requests, not POST.","B":"Incorrect. `tcp.port == 80` shows ALL TCP traffic on port 80 (HTTP), regardless of method — GET, POST, PUT, etc.","C":"Correct! `http.request.method == \"POST\"` is a precise Wireshark display filter that shows only HTTP POST requests. This is useful for finding form submissions, credential transmissions over HTTP, or API calls that send data.","D":"Incorrect. This is not valid Wireshark filter syntax — Wireshark uses its own dissector-aware filter language, not BPF syntax for display filters."},"id":"cct_267"},{"domain":"Network Traffic Monitoring","question":"What is protocol analysis used for in network traffic monitoring?","options":{"A":"To authenticate users accessing network resources via 802.1X port-based access control","B":"To examine packet headers and payloads to detect protocol anomalies, tunneling, and policy violations","C":"To generate and distribute encryption keys for IPsec VPN tunnels between sites","D":"To configure and provision VLANs across managed switches automatically"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. 802.1X authentication is a network access control mechanism — it authenticates devices before granting network access, not protocol analysis.","B":"Correct! Protocol analysis involves dissecting captured network packets to verify they conform to expected protocol specifications, identify unusual flags or fields, detect tunneling (e.g., DNS tunneling, HTTP tunneling), and spot policy violations (e.g., unauthorized protocols or services).","C":"Incorrect. IPsec key management uses IKE (Internet Key Exchange) protocol — not protocol analysis.","D":"Incorrect. VLAN provisioning is done through switch management interfaces or SDN controllers — not protocol analysis."},"id":"cct_268"},{"domain":"Network Logs Monitoring and Analysis","question":"Which Windows Security Event ID indicates a SUCCESSFUL user logon?","options":{"A":"4625 — Failed logon attempt","B":"4624 — Successful logon","C":"4720 — User account created","D":"1102 — Security audit log cleared"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Event ID 4625 is a FAILED logon attempt. Multiple 4625 events from one source indicate a brute-force attack.","B":"Correct! Event ID 4624 is logged every time a user successfully authenticates to a Windows system. It includes the username, logon type (interactive, network, service, etc.), source IP, and timestamp — critical for detecting unauthorized access.","C":"Incorrect. Event ID 4720 is generated when a new user account is created — useful for detecting attacker persistence via backdoor accounts.","D":"Incorrect. Event ID 1102 means the Security event log was cleared — a major red flag indicating an attacker covering their tracks."},"id":"cct_269"},{"domain":"Network Logs Monitoring and Analysis","question":"What does Windows Event ID 1102 indicate, and why is it security-critical?","options":{"A":"A new administrative share was created on a Windows server","B":"The Security audit log was cleared — a strong indicator of an attacker attempting to cover their tracks","C":"Windows Defender detected and quarantined malware","D":"A user account was locked out after too many failed logon attempts"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Administrative share creation would be logged differently — Event ID 1102 specifically refers to the Security log being cleared.","B":"Correct! When the Windows Security event log is cleared (using Event Viewer or `wevtutil cl Security`), Event ID 1102 is generated. This is a critical security indicator because attackers often clear logs to destroy evidence of their activities. Organizations should forward logs to a SIEM in real time so clearing local logs doesn't destroy the evidence.","C":"Incorrect. Windows Defender generates its own events in the Windows Defender operational log, not Security event 1102.","D":"Incorrect. Account lockout generates Event ID 4740, not 1102."},"id":"cct_270"},{"domain":"Network Logs Monitoring and Analysis","question":"Which Linux log file records SSH authentication events and sudo usage on Debian/Ubuntu systems?","options":{"A":"/var/log/syslog — General system log","B":"/var/log/messages — RedHat/CentOS general log","C":"/var/log/auth.log — Authentication and authorization events","D":"/var/log/kern.log — Kernel messages"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. /var/log/syslog is the general system log on Debian/Ubuntu — it captures a wide range of system events but auth events are specifically written to auth.log.","B":"Incorrect. /var/log/messages is the equivalent general log on RedHat/CentOS systems. On those systems, /var/log/secure records authentication events.","C":"Correct! On Debian/Ubuntu, /var/log/auth.log records all authentication-related events: SSH logins (successful and failed), sudo command usage, PAM authentication, and account lockouts. Monitoring this file is essential for detecting brute-force attacks and unauthorized access.","D":"Incorrect. /var/log/kern.log records kernel-level messages — hardware events, driver messages, network interface state changes — not authentication."},"id":"cct_271"},{"domain":"Network Logs Monitoring and Analysis","question":"What is the primary purpose of a SIEM (Security Information and Event Management) system?","options":{"A":"To replace firewalls and IDS by providing a single platform for all security functions","B":"To aggregate, normalize, correlate, and alert on log data from across the infrastructure to detect security threats","C":"To encrypt log data in transit and at rest to prevent tampering","D":"To automatically patch vulnerable systems when related exploit activity is detected in logs"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. A SIEM does not replace firewalls or IDS — it aggregates data FROM those systems. It is a detection and analysis platform, not a prevention tool.","B":"Correct! A SIEM (e.g., Splunk, IBM QRadar, Microsoft Sentinel) collects logs from diverse sources (firewalls, endpoints, servers, applications), normalizes them into a common format, applies correlation rules to identify attack patterns across events, and generates prioritized alerts for analysts.","C":"Incorrect. While secure log transmission (TLS) and storage are best practices, encrypting logs is not the SIEM's primary purpose.","D":"Incorrect. Automated patching is handled by vulnerability management/patch management tools. SIEM focuses on detection, not remediation."},"id":"cct_272"},{"domain":"Network Logs Monitoring and Analysis","question":"A security analyst reviews Apache web server logs and sees hundreds of requests with status code 404 (Not Found) for paths like '/admin', '/wp-admin', '/phpmyadmin'. What does this most likely indicate?","options":{"A":"Normal traffic — users frequently mistype URLs or follow broken links","B":"A web application vulnerability scan or directory enumeration attack","C":"A DDoS attack designed to overwhelm the web server with garbage requests","D":"SEO bots crawling the website to index it for search engines"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Occasional 404s are normal, but hundreds of 404s for specific administrative paths in rapid succession is not normal user behavior.","B":"Correct! Systematic requests to common admin panel URLs (/admin, /wp-admin, /phpmyadmin, /.env, /config.php) is the signature of directory enumeration/forced browsing, typically performed by web vulnerability scanners (Nikto, DirBuster, gobuster). The attacker is trying to discover hidden resources.","C":"Incorrect. A DDoS would involve massive volumes of requests to the SAME URL to overwhelm the server — not targeted requests to specific admin paths.","D":"Incorrect. Search engine bots follow links and sitemaps to index content — they don't probe for admin panels or configuration files."},"id":"cct_273"},{"domain":"Wireless Network Security","question":"Which wireless security protocol is considered MOST secure for enterprise environments as of current best practices?","options":{"A":"WEP (Wired Equivalent Privacy) with 128-bit key","B":"WPA (Wi-Fi Protected Access) with TKIP","C":"WPA2-Personal (PSK) with AES-CCMP","D":"WPA3-Enterprise with 192-bit security and SAE"},"correct_option":"D","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. WEP is completely broken — its RC4 implementation has fatal flaws. An attacker can crack WEP keys in minutes using captured packets.","B":"Incorrect. WPA with TKIP was a stopgap fix for WEP and is also deprecated. TKIP has known vulnerabilities.","C":"Incorrect. WPA2-Personal (PSK) is still widely used and much stronger than WEP/WPA, but PSK mode has a fundamental weakness: a captured 4-way handshake allows offline dictionary attacks against the shared passphrase.","D":"Correct! WPA3-Enterprise uses SAE (Simultaneous Authentication of Equals, replacing PSK), GCMP-256 encryption, and 192-bit security suite (CNSA) for the highest security. SAE eliminates offline dictionary attacks by providing perfect forward secrecy per session."},"id":"cct_274"},{"domain":"Wireless Network Security","question":"What is an Evil Twin attack in wireless security?","options":{"A":"A denial-of-service attack that floods an access point with deauthentication frames to disconnect all clients","B":"A rogue access point that mimics a legitimate AP's SSID to trick clients into connecting and intercept their traffic","C":"Capturing a WPA2 4-way handshake and cracking the Pre-Shared Key offline using a GPU","D":"Injecting forged ARP Reply packets to redirect traffic through an attacker's machine on the local network"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Flooding APs with deauthentication frames is a deauth/disassociation DoS attack (using tools like aireplay-ng), not an Evil Twin.","B":"Correct! An Evil Twin (rogue AP) attack deploys a fake access point with the same SSID (and often stronger signal) as a legitimate network. When clients connect to the attacker's AP instead, all their unencrypted traffic can be intercepted and credentials captured. Often combined with a captive portal to steal credentials.","C":"Incorrect. Capturing and cracking WPA2 handshakes is a WPA cracking attack (using aircrack-ng, hashcat) — a different technique.","D":"Incorrect. Forged ARP Replies is an ARP poisoning/spoofing attack that works on wired or wireless networks regardless of AP — not specifically an Evil Twin attack."},"id":"cct_275"},{"domain":"Wireless Network Security","question":"What does the IEEE 802.1X standard define?","options":{"A":"The channel frequencies and bandwidths used by 5 GHz 802.11ac/ax networks","B":"Port-Based Network Access Control (PNAC) — authentication before granting LAN/WLAN access using EAP","C":"The WPA3-SAE encryption handshake for wireless authentication","D":"Quality of Service (QoS) prioritization for wireless VoIP traffic"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Wireless channel frequencies and PHY specifications are defined in 802.11 standards (802.11a/b/g/n/ac/ax).","B":"Correct! IEEE 802.1X defines Port-Based Network Access Control. Before a device is allowed onto a LAN or WLAN, it must authenticate via EAP (Extensible Authentication Protocol) through three roles: Supplicant (client), Authenticator (switch/AP), and Authentication Server (RADIUS). This is the foundation of WPA2/WPA3-Enterprise authentication.","C":"Incorrect. WPA3-SAE's handshake is defined in the WPA3 specification by the Wi-Fi Alliance, not IEEE 802.1X.","D":"Incorrect. QoS for wireless is defined in IEEE 802.11e (Wi-Fi Multimedia, WMM)."},"id":"cct_276"},{"domain":"Wireless Network Security","question":"What is wardriving?","options":{"A":"An attack that sends malformed 802.11 management frames to crash access points","B":"Driving or moving through an area while scanning for Wi-Fi networks, often to identify unsecured or vulnerable APs","C":"Using a directional antenna to extend the range of an Evil Twin attack","D":"Jamming a wireless network by transmitting on the same frequency as the target AP"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Sending malformed management frames to crash APs is a wireless DoS/management frame attack, not wardriving.","B":"Correct! Wardriving involves traveling (driving, walking, or flying a drone) while using a Wi-Fi-enabled device and software (Kismet, NetStumbler) to discover and log wireless networks — SSIDs, security configurations, signal strength, and GPS location. Used by attackers to find open or WEP-protected networks and by researchers to map wireless infrastructure.","C":"Incorrect. Using directional antennas for extended Evil Twin range is a separate technique during the exploitation phase.","D":"Incorrect. Wi-Fi jamming uses RF transmitters to flood the 2.4/5 GHz band — this is RF jamming, not wardriving."},"id":"cct_277"},{"domain":"Wireless Network Security","question":"What specific attack captures the WPA2 4-way handshake to enable offline password cracking?","options":{"A":"Bluejacking — sending unsolicited Bluetooth messages to nearby devices","B":"Deauthentication attack followed by handshake capture and offline dictionary attack","C":"KRACK (Key Reinstallation Attack) — forcing nonce reuse in AES-CCMP","D":"Bluesnarfing — accessing Bluetooth device data without authorization"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Bluejacking is a Bluetooth attack involving unsolicited messages — unrelated to WPA2 handshake capture.","B":"Correct! The classic WPA2 cracking method: (1) Use aireplay-ng to send deauthentication frames, forcing clients to disconnect and reconnect. (2) Capture the resulting 4-way handshake using airodump-ng. (3) Use aircrack-ng or hashcat to perform an offline dictionary/brute-force attack against the captured PMKID or handshake hash.","C":"Incorrect. KRACK is a real vulnerability (2017) that forces nonce reuse in AES-CCMP to potentially decrypt traffic, but it is a different attack from handshake capture for PSK cracking.","D":"Incorrect. Bluesnarfing exploits Bluetooth OBEX vulnerabilities to access phone book/messages without pairing — completely unrelated to Wi-Fi WPA2."},"id":"cct_278"},{"domain":"Identification, Authentication and Authorization","question":"Which of the following is a valid example of multi-factor authentication (MFA)?","options":{"A":"Using a 25-character complex password that includes symbols and numbers","B":"Answering two security questions (What is your pet's name? What city were you born in?)","C":"Entering a username/password AND approving a push notification on a registered mobile device","D":"Logging in with both a work email address and a personal email address"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. A complex password, regardless of length, is still a single factor (something you know). MFA requires factors from different categories.","B":"Incorrect. Both security questions are 'something you know' — two factors from the SAME category does not constitute MFA. MFA requires factors from at least two DIFFERENT categories.","C":"Correct! Password = something you know; push notification on a registered mobile device = something you have (possession of the device). These are two different factor categories, making this genuine MFA.","D":"Incorrect. Two email addresses are both 'something you know/have' in a weak sense but typically just represent two username inputs — not true multi-factor authentication."},"id":"cct_279"},{"domain":"Identification, Authentication and Authorization","question":"What is Single Sign-On (SSO)?","options":{"A":"A policy requiring users to use a single, unified password across all corporate systems","B":"An authentication mechanism allowing users to authenticate once and access multiple authorized systems without re-entering credentials","C":"A hardware token that generates a single one-time password for use across all applications","D":"A biometric system that permanently replaces passwords with facial recognition scans"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Using the same password everywhere is a security anti-pattern (credential stuffing risk), not what SSO is. SSO uses authentication tokens, not shared passwords.","B":"Correct! SSO (implemented via SAML, OAuth 2.0/OIDC, Kerberos) allows a user to authenticate once against a central Identity Provider (IdP). That authentication token is then presented to other systems (Service Providers), granting access without requiring the user to log in again — improving both UX and security (fewer password prompts, centralized control).","C":"Incorrect. A hardware OTP token (RSA SecurID, YubiKey) is an MFA factor, not an SSO solution.","D":"Incorrect. Biometric authentication is one authentication method that can be USED with SSO, but SSO is the access paradigm, not a biometric technology."},"id":"cct_280"},{"domain":"Identification, Authentication and Authorization","question":"What type of access control model assigns permissions based on a user's position and responsibilities within the organization?","options":{"A":"Mandatory Access Control (MAC) — controlled by a central authority based on classification labels","B":"Discretionary Access Control (DAC) — resource owners grant permissions to other users","C":"Role-Based Access Control (RBAC) — permissions tied to job roles","D":"Attribute-Based Access Control (ABAC) — permissions based on multiple contextual attributes"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. MAC assigns access based on security labels (classification levels) and clearance levels — used heavily in government/military — not based on job roles.","B":"Incorrect. DAC allows resource OWNERS (users or admins) to grant permissions to whoever they choose — highly flexible but less controlled than RBAC.","C":"Correct! RBAC assigns permissions to roles (e.g., 'HR Manager,' 'Network Admin,' 'Read-Only Auditor') and then assigns users to those roles. Users inherit the permissions of their role, making access management scalable and tied to job function.","D":"Incorrect. ABAC makes authorization decisions based on multiple attributes (user attributes, resource attributes, environmental conditions like time/location) — more granular and context-aware than RBAC."},"id":"cct_281"},{"domain":"IoT and OT Security","question":"What is a Programmable Logic Controller (PLC) in an Operational Technology (OT) environment?","options":{"A":"A cloud-based server used to aggregate telemetry data from IoT sensors","B":"An industrial ruggedized computer that automates physical processes by reading sensors and controlling actuators","C":"A network protocol used for communication between SCADA systems and remote field devices","D":"A specialized firewall designed for industrial control system (ICS) network segmentation"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Cloud-based IoT aggregation is performed by IoT platforms (AWS IoT, Azure IoT Hub) — PLCs are on-premises hardware controllers.","B":"Correct! A PLC is a ruggedized industrial computer programmed with control logic to automate machinery: it reads inputs (sensors, switches) and controls outputs (motors, valves, conveyors). PLCs are the brains of manufacturing floors, power plants, and water treatment facilities.","C":"Incorrect. SCADA communication protocols include Modbus, DNP3, OPC-UA — these are industrial protocols, not what a PLC is.","D":"Incorrect. ICS-specific firewalls (Claroty, Dragos, Nozomi) provide OT network protection — PLCs are the controlled devices, not the security tool."},"id":"cct_282"},{"domain":"IoT and OT Security","question":"Why are IoT devices often considered difficult to secure compared to traditional IT systems?","options":{"A":"IoT devices run full enterprise operating systems that require intensive patch management resources","B":"Many IoT devices have limited CPU, memory, and no update mechanism, often shipped with default credentials and no security controls","C":"IoT security is entirely managed by the Internet Service Provider at the network perimeter","D":"IoT devices use proprietary encryption algorithms that cannot interoperate with enterprise security tools"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. IoT devices typically run stripped-down firmware or RTOS (Real-Time Operating Systems) to minimize resource use — NOT full enterprise OSes.","B":"Correct! IoT security challenges include: constrained hardware (low CPU/RAM prevents encryption or security agents), firmware rarely updated (many devices never receive patches), default credentials (admin/admin) that users never change, no display/interface for user interaction, and lack of standard security frameworks. These factors create a massive, difficult-to-manage attack surface.","C":"Incorrect. ISPs provide basic network connectivity and may offer some DDoS protection, but IoT device security is the responsibility of the manufacturer and device owner.","D":"Incorrect. Many IoT devices use standard protocols (MQTT, CoAP, TLS) — the security problem is not incompatible encryption but rather a lack of any meaningful security implementation."},"id":"cct_283"},{"domain":"IoT and OT Security","question":"What is the BEST practice for protecting SCADA and Industrial Control Systems (ICS) from cyber threats?","options":{"A":"Connecting SCADA systems directly to the internet to enable efficient remote management","B":"Using default vendor credentials to ensure field technicians can always access the system","C":"Air-gapping or strictly isolating ICS networks from corporate IT and the internet, with strict access controls","D":"Patching ICS systems on the same monthly schedule as standard IT systems"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Internet-exposed SCADA systems are extremely dangerous — Shodan regularly finds thousands of exposed ICS/SCADA systems. Attackers can cause physical damage to infrastructure.","B":"Incorrect. Default credentials are a critical vulnerability — Mirai and similar IoT botnets primarily exploit default credentials. They must always be changed.","C":"Correct! The primary defense for ICS/SCADA is network isolation: air-gapping (no connection to external networks) or at minimum using a DMZ with unidirectional gateways (data diodes). ICS protocols (Modbus, DNP3) were not designed with security in mind and are highly vulnerable if exposed.","D":"Incorrect. ICS systems often CANNOT be patched on regular schedules because patches require equipment downtime and extensive testing in OT environments — industrial processes may run 24/7 for months. This makes air-gapping even more critical as a compensating control."},"id":"cct_284"},{"domain":"Computer Forensics","question":"According to RFC 3227, what is the correct Order of Volatility for collecting digital evidence (most volatile first)?","options":{"A":"Hard disk → RAM → Network connections → CPU cache → Removable media","B":"CPU registers/cache → RAM → Network connections/state → Running processes → Disk → Removable media → Backups","C":"Network connections → Disk image → RAM → CPU registers → Cloud backups","D":"RAM → Network connections → CPU registers → Running processes → Disk → Removable media"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. This order is wrong — hard disk comes AFTER RAM and network state in volatility order.","B":"Correct! RFC 3227 defines the Order of Volatility: CPU registers/cache (lost instantly at power-off) → RAM (lost on shutdown) → Network connections and state → Running processes → Disk storage → Removable media → Archival backups (most persistent). Evidence must be collected from most volatile to least volatile.","C":"Incorrect. Network connections come after RAM in volatility, and disk comes before network connections in this incorrect option.","D":"Incorrect. CPU registers are MORE volatile than RAM and should be collected first — they are lost instantly even before RAM is lost."},"id":"cct_285"},{"domain":"Computer Forensics","question":"What is a write-blocker used for during digital forensic evidence collection?","options":{"A":"To prevent the forensic analyst from accidentally overwriting their investigation notes","B":"To allow read-only access to storage media so that forensic tools cannot inadvertently modify evidence","C":"To encrypt forensic images before storage to maintain confidentiality","D":"To block network writes from a seized device during live forensic examination"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Write-blockers protect storage EVIDENCE, not the analyst's documents.","B":"Correct! A write-blocker (hardware or software) intercepts all write commands sent to a storage device and silently discards them, allowing forensic tools to read every sector without changing a single bit. This preserves evidence integrity and ensures hash values computed before and after examination match — critical for chain of custody.","C":"Incorrect. Forensic image encryption is a separate data-at-rest protection measure applied after acquisition, not what a write-blocker does.","D":"Incorrect. Network write blocking (preventing a device from communicating on a network) is achieved through network isolation — a different tool from a storage write-blocker."},"id":"cct_286"},{"domain":"Computer Forensics","question":"Which open-source forensic tool suite provides a graphical interface for analyzing disk images, recovering deleted files, and examining file metadata?","options":{"A":"Metasploit Framework","B":"Wireshark","C":"Autopsy / The Sleuth Kit (TSK)","D":"Volatility Framework"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Metasploit is a penetration testing and exploitation framework — not a forensic analysis tool.","B":"Incorrect. Wireshark is a network packet capture and analysis tool — useful in forensics for network traffic analysis but not disk forensics.","C":"Correct! Autopsy is a free, open-source digital forensics platform built on The Sleuth Kit. It analyzes disk images and file systems to recover deleted files, view browser history, examine email artifacts, hash files against known databases (NSRL), and generate forensic reports.","D":"Incorrect. Volatility is an excellent open-source MEMORY forensics framework (RAM analysis), not disk/file system forensics."},"id":"cct_287"},{"domain":"Computer Forensics","question":"What is the purpose of computing an MD5 or SHA-256 hash of a forensic image immediately after acquisition?","options":{"A":"To encrypt the forensic image to prevent unauthorized access during storage and transport","B":"To verify the integrity of the evidence — proving the copy is an exact bit-for-bit duplicate and has not been altered","C":"To compress the forensic image to reduce storage requirements on the analysis workstation","D":"To identify the operating system and file system type on the acquired disk image"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Hashing verifies integrity — it does not encrypt. MD5/SHA-256 are one-way functions that produce a fixed-size fingerprint, not encryption.","B":"Correct! After creating a forensic image (using dd, FTK Imager, Guymager), computing and recording its hash value creates a verifiable proof of integrity. If the hash of the copy matches the hash of the original, it proves the copy is exact. If the hash ever changes, it proves tampering occurred — essential for legal admissibility.","C":"Incorrect. Hash functions produce a small fixed-size value (128 or 256 bits) — they do not compress the image.","D":"Incorrect. File system identification is done by forensic tools analyzing the image structure (boot sector, partition table), not by the hash."},"id":"cct_288"},{"domain":"Business Continuity and Disaster Recovery","question":"What is the Recovery Time Objective (RTO)?","options":{"A":"The maximum acceptable amount of data loss, measured as a time interval (e.g., lose no more than 1 hour of data)","B":"The maximum allowable downtime for a business process or system before recovery must be achieved","C":"The total time required to perform and validate a full backup restoration from offsite storage","D":"The scheduled time window during which disaster recovery drills must be conducted annually"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. This definition describes RPO (Recovery Point Objective), not RTO.","B":"Correct! RTO defines the maximum time a business can tolerate being without a specific system or process. For example, RTO = 4 hours means the system must be restored and operational within 4 hours of the outage. Shorter RTOs require more expensive recovery solutions (hot standby sites).","C":"Incorrect. The actual time it takes to restore a backup is what the RTO CONSTRAINS — the RTO is the goal, not the measurement of the restore process duration.","D":"Incorrect. DR drill schedules are defined in the BC/DR plan as a governance requirement, not what RTO means."},"id":"cct_289"},{"domain":"Business Continuity and Disaster Recovery","question":"What is the Recovery Point Objective (RPO)?","options":{"A":"The maximum downtime a business can tolerate before operations must be restored","B":"The point during the recovery process when systems are declared fully operational","C":"The maximum acceptable amount of data loss, expressed as the time between the last backup and the failure event","D":"The minimum recovery bandwidth required to restore systems within the RTO window"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. This describes RTO (Recovery Time Objective), not RPO.","B":"Incorrect. Systems being declared operational is the completion of recovery, not the RPO definition.","C":"Correct! RPO defines how much data loss is acceptable: if RPO = 2 hours, the organization must be able to recover data from no more than 2 hours before the failure. This drives backup frequency — an RPO of 2 hours requires backups at least every 2 hours.","D":"Incorrect. Recovery bandwidth planning is a technical implementation detail of the DR solution, not the RPO definition."},"id":"cct_290"},{"domain":"Business Continuity and Disaster Recovery","question":"Which disaster recovery site type provides the fastest recovery time but is also the MOST expensive?","options":{"A":"Cold site — empty physical space, no equipment, requires full setup before recovery can begin","B":"Warm site — partially equipped with hardware, activation takes hours to a day","C":"Hot site — fully equipped, mirrored environment with real-time data synchronization, near-instant failover","D":"Mobile site — truck-mounted portable equipment dispatched to any location after a disaster"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. A cold site is the CHEAPEST option but has the longest recovery time (days to weeks) since equipment must be procured and configured from scratch.","B":"Incorrect. A warm site is a middle-ground option — equipment exists but data is not continuously synchronized, taking hours to activate.","C":"Correct! A hot site is a fully operational duplicate of the primary environment with real-time or near-real-time data replication. Failover is nearly instantaneous (minutes), making it ideal for mission-critical systems. It is the most expensive option because you pay for fully provisioned duplicate infrastructure continuously.","D":"Incorrect. Mobile sites are portable options for scenarios where geography is an issue — not the fastest recovery type."},"id":"cct_291"},{"domain":"Business Continuity and Disaster Recovery","question":"What is the primary purpose of a Business Impact Analysis (BIA)?","options":{"A":"To test the disaster recovery plan by simulating a full system failure","B":"To identify critical business processes and determine the financial and operational impact of their disruption","C":"To negotiate SLA uptime guarantees with cloud service providers","D":"To conduct penetration testing against business-critical applications"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Testing the DR plan is done through tabletop exercises, simulations, or full failover tests — not what a BIA is.","B":"Correct! A BIA identifies which business functions are critical, the consequences (financial, operational, regulatory) of their disruption over time, and determines the RTO and RPO requirements for each process. It is the foundation of the entire BC/DR planning effort — you cannot define recovery objectives without first knowing which processes matter most.","C":"Incorrect. Negotiating SLAs with cloud providers is a vendor management activity — informed by BIA results but not what a BIA is.","D":"Incorrect. Penetration testing assesses security vulnerabilities, not business continuity impacts."},"id":"cct_292"},{"domain":"Risk Management","question":"How is Annual Loss Expectancy (ALE) correctly calculated?","options":{"A":"ALE = Asset Value × Exposure Factor (EF)","B":"ALE = Single Loss Expectancy (SLE) ÷ Annual Rate of Occurrence (ARO)","C":"ALE = Single Loss Expectancy (SLE) × Annual Rate of Occurrence (ARO)","D":"ALE = Asset Value + Threat Likelihood"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Asset Value × Exposure Factor = SLE (Single Loss Expectancy), which is the value of a single loss event — not ALE.","B":"Incorrect. Dividing SLE by ARO is mathematically wrong and would give a nonsensical value smaller than a single loss.","C":"Correct! ALE = SLE × ARO. SLE = Asset Value × Exposure Factor (the monetary value of a single incident). ARO = how often that event is expected to occur per year. ALE = total expected annual loss from that threat. Example: SLE=$10,000 × ARO=0.5 (once every 2 years) = ALE=$5,000/year.","D":"Incorrect. This is not a recognized formula — risk calculations use specific quantitative formulas, not simple addition of unrelated values."},"id":"cct_293"},{"domain":"Risk Management","question":"What is qualitative risk analysis?","options":{"A":"Using financial models and statistical calculations to assign exact monetary values to risks","B":"Rating risk likelihood and impact using descriptive scales (Low/Medium/High/Critical) based on expert judgment","C":"Calculating precise Annual Loss Expectancy values using asset value and exposure factor formulas","D":"Using machine learning to predict future risks based on historical incident data"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Assigning monetary values with financial models is QUANTITATIVE risk analysis (ALE, SLE, ARO).","B":"Correct! Qualitative risk analysis uses expert judgment and descriptive categories rather than hard numbers. Risks are rated as Low/Medium/High/Critical based on the estimated likelihood of occurrence and potential impact. Results are typically shown in a risk heat map. It's faster and more practical when exact data isn't available.","C":"Incorrect. ALE/SLE/ARO calculations are quantitative risk analysis methods.","D":"Incorrect. ML-based prediction may be used in advanced threat intelligence platforms, but that's not what defines qualitative risk analysis."},"id":"cct_294"},{"domain":"Risk Management","question":"Which risk response strategy involves purchasing cyber liability insurance to cover potential losses?","options":{"A":"Risk avoidance — stopping the activity that creates the risk entirely","B":"Risk acceptance — acknowledging the risk without taking action","C":"Risk transference — shifting the financial impact to a third party (insurer or vendor)","D":"Risk mitigation — implementing controls to reduce probability or impact"},"correct_option":"C","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Risk avoidance means stopping the risky activity altogether (e.g., discontinuing a product, not entering a market). Insurance still allows the activity to continue.","B":"Incorrect. Risk acceptance means knowingly accepting the potential loss without taking mitigating action — no insurance is purchased.","C":"Correct! Risk transference (also called risk sharing) moves the financial consequence of a risk to another party. Cyber liability insurance is the classic example — if a breach occurs, the insurer covers costs up to policy limits. Outsourcing a risky function to a vendor with contractual liability is another example.","D":"Incorrect. Risk mitigation involves implementing security controls (firewalls, MFA, encryption) to reduce either the likelihood or the impact of the risk — the organization retains the risk but reduces it."},"id":"cct_295"},{"domain":"Risk Management","question":"What is a Risk Register?","options":{"A":"A government database of all registered cybersecurity incidents reported by critical infrastructure operators","B":"A formal document that records identified risks, their likelihood, impact, risk owner, and mitigation strategies","C":"A technical tool that automatically scans systems for vulnerabilities and assigns risk scores","D":"A legal agreement between an organization and its auditors defining the scope of annual security assessments"},"correct_option":"B","explanations":{"A":"Incorrect. Government incident databases (US-CERT, CISA advisories) are external references — a risk register is an internal organizational document.","B":"Correct! A risk register is a central repository documenting all identified risks: their description, threat source, likelihood rating, impact rating, calculated risk score, who owns the risk (risk owner), what controls are in place, the chosen response strategy, and residual risk after controls. It is maintained and reviewed regularly as the core artifact of a risk management program.","C":"Incorrect. Vulnerability scanners (Nessus, Qualys) are technical tools that find technical weaknesses — a risk register is a governance document, not a scanner.","D":"Incorrect. Audit scope agreements are defined in engagement letters between organizations and their auditors — a very different document."},"id":"cct_296"}];
